<HEAD>Foreign Minister Cited as Possible Takeshita Successor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Sousuke Uno has emerged as the
most likely candidate to succeed scandal-tainted Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita, who will resign soon, news reports said Saturday.
   Party leaders said Uno emerged as the top contender after talks
Friday between Takeshita and Masayoshi Ito, chairman of the party's
policy-making Executive Council, according to reports in the
mass-circulation Asahi, Yomiuri and Mainichi newspapers.
   Takeshita was scheduled to meet with party Secretary-General
Shintaro Abe Saturday afternoon to discuss the selection of Uno,
the reports said.
   Uno, 66, a 10-term member of the powerful lower house, has
served as foreign minister under Takeshita since 1987. He has held
the international trade and industry portfolio and served as party
deputy secretary-general.
   An official at Uno's office said the reports about his being top
contender were rumors and refused further comment. Takeshita's
office was closed Saturday.
   Party leaders reportedly favor Uno because he is untainted by
the Recruit scandal, which already has led to more than a dozen
arrests, and has experience in foreign affairs.
   Opposition to Uno remains, however, as he is a leading member of
the party faction headed by Takeshita's predecessor, Yasuhiro
Nakasone, who earlier this week was forced to testify about his
links to the scandal before parliament.
   Ito's refusal May 13 to take the top job created a leadership
vacuum in a governing party desperately in need of a leader with a
clean enough reputation to steer the party out of scandal.
   The Recruit Co., a publishing conglomerate at the center of the
scandal, is accused of trying to influence government policy by
selling underpriced, unlisted shares in a real estate subsidiary
and by doling out millions of dollars of political donations.
   Along with Takeshita's resignation, the scandal has led to the
downfall of three Cabinet ministers and the arrest of a former
chief Cabinet secretary. Many governing party members have called
it the worst crisis since the party was founded 34 years ago.
   In the meeting with Ito on Friday, Takeshita agreed to stay on
as prime minister until a successor is found, though on April 25 he
vowed to leave office soon after the year's budget clears
parliament. The budget package is due to become law on Sunday.
   The head of the governing party routinely serves as prime
minister because of the party's large majority in both houses of
parliament.
   But due to the current crisis, the Liberal Democrats are
reportedly considering installing separate individuals in the two
posts _ thus placating party elders who fear they may lose power if
a young prime minister is named.
   The reports said a possible combination is former Prime Minister
Takeo Fukuda, 84, who would assume the party presidency, and Uno as
premier.
   Fukuda, now in Washington D.C., said Friday said a younger man
should be chosen for prime minister. He is to return to Japan
Sunday. Ito also cited his age and poor health as reasons for
declining the job.
   Other names that have come up in the leadership race are lower
house speaker Michita Sakaka, 72, former Deputy Prime Minister Shin
Kanemaru, 74, and Masaharu Gotoda, 74, who heads the party
Political Reform Committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
