<FIRST>u w AM-Coelho-Thumbnail     05-26 0145</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coelho-Thumbnail,150</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tony Coelho, the third-ranking Democrat in the
House, began his political career with advice from comedian Bob
Hope.
   Coelho was raised on a dairy farm near Fresno, Calif. In college
at Loyola University, he discovered he had epilepsy and was turned
down for his first career _ the Catholic priesthood.
   But Hope's wife, Dolores, heard about Coelho's situation and the
comedian suggested that Coelho try politics. Coelho came to
Washington, where he worked for Rep. B.F. Sisk, the 15th District's
congressman, for 15 years.
   When Sisk retired in 1978, Coelho ran for his seat and won.
Three years later, shortly after Ronald Reagan was elected
president, he took over as chairman of the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee and proved to be a master at raising money.
   After the 1986 election, Coelho was picked as majority whip, the
third-ranking position.
</TEXT>
