<FIRST>r w PM-MissingTorah     05-26 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Missing Torah,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Desperately Seeking Scroll: Schumer Asks State Department Help</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department needs to know more if
it's going to help find a sacred Jewish scroll that was being
smuggled from Iran to the United States when it was allegedly
seized by officials in the United Arab Emirates.
   ``Without more information, there's no way that the department,
which wants to be helpful, can be,'' a State Department official
said Thursday, speaking on condition that his name not be used.
``There just doesn't appear to be anywhere else to turn.''
   Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., has asked the State Department to
help recover the 150-year-old Persian Torah, which had been
destined for a new Persian synagogue in Queens, N.Y.
   But the State Department has been unable to locate the holy
book, the man who was transporting it or the official who allegedly
confiscated the scroll in the tiny Arab emirate of Ras Alkheimeh.
   A spokesman for the Embassy of the United Arab Emirates did not
return several phone calls Thursday.
   The Torah's owner, an Iranian woman, asked a friend of her
husband in November 1988 to smuggle the sacred scroll to Dubai.
Iranian law prohibits exporting a Torah, according to Schumer.
   The woman was sending the Torah to her brother in Brooklyn,
N.Y., who was planning to donate it to synagogue Beit Knesset Omid.
   ``We were going to have a grand opening at the synagogue and I
was expecting to put this Torah at the grand opening,'' the brother
said in an interview from New York. He spoke on condition that his
name not be used for fear that the Iranian government might
retaliate against his family.
   The brother said the scroll had been in his family for
generations.
   ``The value of this Torah, if you are Jewish, is priceless,'' he
said.
   Schumer put its price in the tens of thousands of dollars if it
is indeed 150 years old.
   The smuggler took the scroll by boat from a port in southern
Iran to Dubai, where he planned to mail it to the United States,
Schumer said. But in Ras Alkheimeh, the courier was stopped by
government officials and the scroll was confiscated, Schumer said.
   In a letter to Secretary of State James A. Baker, Schumer said
he has learned that the person who seized the Torah was Javad
Hadad, a member of the Justice-Police Department. Schumer provided
a phone number for Hadad, but there was no answer there Thursday.
   The State Department spokesman said the U.S. consul in Dubai had
tried to chase down Schumer's leads to no avail.
   ``That name has been given before but they have not been able to
track him down, as much as they've tried,'' the spokesman said.
``We're really at a stone wall right now.''
   Schumer blamed the Torah's alleged confiscation on Arab
anti-Semitism.
   ``It's a human rights issue,'' he said. ``I think they can be
embarrassed because this is the most vulgar kind of anti-Semitism
that could exist.''
</TEXT>
