<DOCNO> AP890526-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 0155EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MomentofSilence     05-26 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Moment of Silence,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commercial Radio Stations Plan Moment of Silence Friday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of commercial radio stations across
the United States will go silent for 30 seconds Friday morning as
part of a campaign to show the importance of radio in daily life.
   ``The day the radio stopped'' will mark the beginning of a $100
million campaign with the theme: ``Radio. What would life be
without it.''
   At 7:42 a.m. local time, the booming voice of actor James Earl
Jones will tell listeners that ``for the next 30 seconds this
station and others would like you to imagine your life without
radio. Imagine if all your days sounded like this. ...''
   Following the 30 seconds of dead air, Jones will say: ``Thirty
seconds seems like a long time, doesn't it? Now think how radio
fills that silence for you.''
   About 8,000 stations, about 80 percent of the nation's
commercial stations, will participate, according to the Radio
Advertising Bureau.
   The simultaneous promotion will be the largest in the history of
radio, said bureau spokesman Danny Flamberg. The biggest previous
event was in 1986, when 2,000 radio stations simultaneously
broadcast ``We Are The World'' to promote hunger relief.
</TEXT>
