<FIRST>r w PM-DroughtRelief     05-26 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drought Relief,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0417 to fix category code.</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Panel Passes Emergency Relief for Drought-Stricken Farmers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Agriculture Committee has approved
emergency relief legislation to help farmers cope with drought
devastation to their crops.
   The bill passed Thursday was originally intended to apply only
to winter wheat crops, but numerous amendments offered by
congressman in non-wheat states expanded it to include feed grains,
cotton, rice, soybeans, peanuts, sugar beets, sugar cane and
tobacco.
   Rep. Dan Glickman, D-Kan., chairman of the Agriculture
subcommittee on wheat, soybeans and feed grains and chief architect
of the legislation, said the inclusion of the other crops, which
either have been affected by dry weather or are susceptible to
future drought, was a ``political accommodation.''
   ``We felt if we were going to come with a disaster program, we
had only one bite of the apple,'' he said, recognizing that
producers of crops other than wheat needed help but acknowledging
that a multitude of legislation was not feasible.
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter told the committee in a
letter to Glickman that he would not recommend that President Bush
sign the bill unless it was ``budget neutral.'' In that case, it
would have to apply only to 1989 crops affected by drought and be
accompanied by a promise that Congress would agree to use crop
insurance as the sole vehicle for disaster assistance after this
year.
   ``I think we are in the ballpark,'' said Rep. Kika de la Garza,
D-Texas, chairman of the Agriculture Committee, after the vote.
   The concern about crop insurance remains a stumbling block
because farmers consider the current program unsatisfactory.
   ``I hope the secretary won't hold this bill hostage in order to
pass crop insurance,'' said Rep. Bill Sarpalius, D-Texas. He said
the current system, which requires farmers to pay insurance
premiums to protect against the effects of bad weather, doesn't
work.
   De la Garza pointed out that House improvements to the crop
insurance bill would not be completed in time for action on this
bill. But he said the progress Congress is making should indicate
that continued emergency relief such as this legislation will not
be needed in the future.
   John Campbell, deputy agriculture secretary in charge of
commodities, appeared before the committee to explain Yeutter's
concerns. After the vote, he said the secretary's first question
would be, ``How much will it cost?''
   De la Garza estimated that the bill would cost about $1 billion,
an amount close to what the government will save in price support
payments to farmers. An amendment to the bill offered by Rep. Fred
Grandy, R-Iowa, prohibits disaster relief from exceeding the amount
saved in price supports.
   Since the drought caused a shortage in commodities supply _
primarily wheat _ prices should rise, alleviating the need for
government subsidies. The money that had been set aside for the
price supports would therefore be used to pay the farmers who lost
their crops to drought.
   The administration wants farmers to purchase crop insurance
rather than depend on the government to bail them out when bad
weather causes crop failures.
   The bill would require farmers to have insurance after this year
to cope with bad weather or other natural disasters.
</TEXT>
