<FIRST>r a PM-FishStory     05-26 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fish Story,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angler Rescues Girl From River</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Montagna says a 15-pound salmon was small
fry compared to the 9-year-old girl he saved from drowning.
   Montagna, 43, had landed the fish Sunday at the Deschutes River
when he saw little Amber Blankenship slip from a rock ledge into a
treacherous sinkhole.
   ``I jumped in where I thought she'd be and went down too,''
Montagna said. When he surfaced from the 30-foot-deep river, the
girl was nowhere to be seen.
   ``It was the sickest moment of my life. She could have been
inches from my fingers.''
   Moments later the girl popped out of the water about 12 feet
away. Montagna, an ironworker, grabbed the girl and pulled her out
of the water with the help of others on shore.
   Amber wasn't breathing, but her heart was still beating, and she
was revived, said her mother, Lola Blankenship.
   ``There are no thanks big enough for this gentleman,''
Blankenship said. ``Very few people come out alive because of the
rocks. The river is so mean; it just boils.''
   ``I was in the right place at the right time,'' Montagna said.
   The Deschutes runs through Bend in central Oregon, about 160
miles southeast of Portland.
</TEXT>
