<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 0057EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-IowaExplosion     05-26 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iowa Explosion,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Probe Relationship Between Two Shipmates in USS Iowa
blast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Navy and FBI investigators, stymied so far in
their search for accidental causes of last month's explosion aboard
the battleship Iowa, are conducting a ``very thorough'' criminal
investigation involving two shipmates who had a falling out,
officials say.
   The officials, most of whom asked not to be identified, said no
conclusive evidence has been developed suggesting criminal intent _
either homicide or suicide _ was behind the April 19 blast that
killed 47 sailors.
   ``But there are some unusual aspects to the relationship between
these sailors that is being investigated,'' said one source.
   ``We have no evidence to prove homicide or suicide here,'' added
Deborah Johnson, a Naval Investigative Service agent in Norfolk,
Va., where the Iowa is based. She described theories of homicide or
suicide as ``possibilities among many possibilities.''
   ``Let me put it this way,'' said Peter Williams, the Pentagon's
chief spokesman. ``The Navy is investigating all leads that it
gets. It wants to be very thorough with this investigation.''
   Williams agreed publicly Thursday that the Navy's inquiry had
``a criminal investigation aspect to it'' and that the FBI was
doing more than just helping the Navy sift through forensic
evidence. But he declined further discussion of the criminal
inquiries.
   At the same time, Williams announced that investigators had
ruled out another leading accident explanation for the explosion in
the Iowa's No. 2 gun turret: that the powder for the 16-inch gun
had been rendered unstable by improper storage last summer.
   The Navy is still investigating why the Iowa's powder was stored
aboard hot, non-air-conditioned barges last summer during an
overhaul. But Williams said subjecting the powder to high
temperatures affects its shelf life, not its stability.
   As for the criminal inquiry, the sources said investigators are
looking into the relationship between 25-year-old Gunner's Mate
Clayton M. Hartwig, who died in the blast, and Gunner's Mate 3rd
Class Kendall Truitt, 21, who survived.
   The two had been best friends and named each other as life
insurance beneficiaries, but had a falling out last year when
Truitt got married. Truitt stands to collect $100,000 from the life
insurance policy on Hartwig.
   Truitt worked at the bottom of the seven-level gun turret aboard
the Iowa while Hartwig worked at the very top, next to the huge
guns. The only men to survive the explosion were those at the very
bottom.
   NBC News has quoted unidentified sources as saying the Navy is
investigating the possibility that a detonating device was hidden
in a burlap patch that gunners insert between bags of powder. The
patches are designed to clean the barrels of the battleship's guns
during firing.
   Johnson of the NIS said Thursday that in a search of Truitt's
home after the explosion, investigators found one of the burlap
patches. ``Yes, it was there, but it wasn't tampered with,'' she
said. ``It's a fact that people pick up items for memorabilia.''
   A search of Hartwig's car last Monday, meanwhile, turned up a
crude detonating device and the book ``How to Get Even Without
Going to Jail,'' New York Newsday reported Thursday. The book
explains how to build booby traps and other deadly devices,
according to sources the newspaper did not name.
   Truitt was quoted in reports last week as saying the Navy
created homicide or suicide explanations involving him and Hartwig
to make them scapegoats for an explosion investigators cannot
otherwise explain.
   Alan Holt, the father of a Fort Myers, Fla., man killed in the
explosion, said he also was skeptical of reports suggesting
sabotage was behind the blast.
   Holt said he wondered ``if they're going to let those two guys
take the blame to get it off the Navy's neck.''
   His wife, Karla Holt, added, ``You have to wonder about whether
(the suspected sailors) are scapegoats.'' The Holts' only son,
Scott Alan, was among the 47 people killed.
   Truitt, from Tampa, Fla., has said that in response to
investigators' questions, he denied a homosexual relationship with
Hartwig. He is on leave from the ship and is being transferred to
another post, Williams said Thursday.
   Truitt arrived at Miami International Airport on Thursday night
in the company of his wife and Miami attorney Ellis Rubin. Truitt
refused to talk, but reporters asked Rubin if his client had been
charged.
   ``No, but there's been a lot of media accusations, and you've
got to respond to them,'' Rubin said. ``So we're going to do that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
