<FIRST>r w PM-SubmarineCracks     05-26 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Submarine Cracks,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Investigating `Severe' Cracks in Hull of New Atomic Submarine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The discovery of two serious cracks is
necessitating the replacement of part of the steel hull of a
nuclear submarine under construction at a Groton, Conn., shipyard,
the Electric Boat Co. said.
   Navy officials said Thursday they have opened an investigation
into the cracks on the Topeka, a SSN-688 fast-attack sub.
   The problem in the Electric Boat shipyard is ``quite severe''
and ``a very unusual occurrence,'' the company said in a memo to
lawmakers.
   ``A thorough investigation is being conducted which will include
recommendations for repair,'' the memo said. ``Topeka will not put
to sea until Electric Boat and the Navy are fully satisfied that
the vessel is safe.''
   Electric Boat, a division of General Dynamics Corp., said
workers discovered the cracks on the outer steel hull Monday
afternoon during sandblasting operations in Groton and reported
them to the Navy.
   The hull is made at Electric Boat's plant in North Kingstown,
R.I., and assembled at the company's main plant in Groton.
   Company spokesman Neil Ruenzel, reached late Thursday, said the
memo may have ``overstated things as far as severity.''
   Ruenzel said a ``very small section'' of the hull has been
removed and will be replaced.
   ``It's quite severe from the standpoint that we would not let
that matter go unattended and we felt and do feel that it was
necessary to remove that section, not only for analysis but we
would not deliver that submarine with cracks,'' he said. ``So the
severity meant that the section needed to be replaced.''
   ``It's a big job, but we're equipped to handle that,'' Ruenzel
said.
   He provided no cost estimate and said he did not know if the
replacement will delay the project. Ruenzel said he was unaware of
any similar cracking of a submarine hull.
   Perry Pockros, an aide to Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn., who
represents the Groton district, said it was clear the cracks would
force Electric Boat to push back its Sept. 30 commission date.
   Lt. Jim Wood, a Navy spokesman on submarine issues, said the
Navy had no immediate comment.
   The Topeka, designated SSN-754, is a 360-foot, 6,900-ton, Los
Angeles-class submarine. The vessels, designed to hunt down enemy
subs and surface warships, are armed with Mark 48 anti-submarine
torpedoes, Harpoon missiles and Tomahawk cruise missiles.
   Construction of the Topeka, ordered by the Navy in 1983, was
begun on Jan. 23, 1988. It is scheduled to be commissioned on Sept.
30.
   The Los Angeles-class submarines are built by Electric Boat and
the Newport News (Va.) Shipbuilding Co. The last SSN-688 is
expected in the 1990 fiscal budget. The subs will be replaced by
the SSN-21 Seawolf.
   Ruenzel said Armco Inc. of Parsippany, N.J., supplied the steel
on the part of the hull that cracked.
   ``It is too premature to identify any financial liabilities,''
the memo said. ``Results of a complete investigation will be
required.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
