<FIRST>r i PM-Obit-Takatsukasa     05-26 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Takatsukasa,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Emperor's Sister Dies at 59</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kazuko Takatsukasa, the elder sister of Emperor
Akihito, died of heart failure at a Tokyo hospital early today,
Imperial Palace officials said. She was 59.
   Mrs. Takatsukasa was the third daughter of the late Emperor
Hirohito, Japan's longest reigning monarch, who died Jan. 7.
   She served as Lord Custodian of the Great Shrine of Ise, a major
Shinto shrine in western Japan, for 14 years. She resigned in
October, citing poor health.
   She had been suffering from internal ailments for the past two
years, reportedly breast and rectal cancer. Imperial Palace and
hospital officials declined to comment on the reports.
   She had been intermittently hospitalized since her first surgery
in 1987, said an official of the Imperial Household Agency on
condition of anonymity.
   In December, Mrs. Takatsukasa underwent a second breast surgery
and chemotherapy.
   In 1950, Mrs. Takatsukasa married Toshimitsu Takatsukasa, member
of one of the five families who have traditionally served as chief
advisers to the imperial family. Her husband died in 1966.
   She is survived by an adopted son, Naotake, 44.
   There was no announcement of funeral arrangements.
</TEXT>
