<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-ContraAid     05-26 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Contra Aid,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Consider Congressman's Threat to Hold Up Contra Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bush administration officials are trying to
decide how to handle a congressman's threat to hold up aid for
Latin America unless officials concede they misled lawmakers about
U.S. efforts to win third-country help for Nicaraguan rebels.
   State Department and White House officials met Thursday to
discuss a letter Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., chairman of the House
Appropriations subcommittee on foreign operations, sent to
Secretary of State James A. Baker III, said a congressional source
who asked not to be named.
   An administration official confirmed discussions were being held
on the letter.
   Obey complained that his committee, which acts on the
administration's requests for foreign aid, ``was clearly misled by
administration spokesmen in the past concerning the linkage of U.S.
aid to the Contras.''
   He asked Baker to provide him with a letter ``for the record to
show that the administration understands that, so we can move on to
other business.''
   ``I would hope that this matter could be cleared up by a simple
letter so that further hearings would not be required before we''
vote on aid to Latin America, he said.
   Obey pointed out that time is short, since the vote is expected
to take place within the next two weeks.
   Further hearings could delay the vote on the administration's
request for some $700 million in Central American aid for fiscal
1990, said an Obey aide, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The United States has backed the Contra rebels since 1981 in
their fight to oust the leftist government in Nicaragua.
   Documents that surfaced at former White House aide Oliver
North's recent trial and other information ``would seem to justify
a committee conclusion that aid to Honduras, Guatemala, El Salvador
and Costa Rica was used as leverage to get those countries to help
the Contras'' and circumvent a 1984 congressional ban on such
assistance, Obey wrote.
   He also noted that Michael Kozak, acting assistant secretary of
state for Latin America, testified before Obey's panel last month
that a plan to expedite aid to Honduras in return for its promise
to help the rebels was never carried out.
   ``But clearly it was,'' Obey said.
   Obey said he wrote to Kozak asking him to clear up discrepancies
between his testimony and other documents, but did not receive an
answer.
   ``If the administration has other documents which can back up''
Kozak's contentions, they should be supplied to the committee
immediately, Obey said.
</TEXT>
