<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 0304EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-OverseasEd     05-26 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Overseas Ed,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Seeks Review of Challenge to Workload at Overseas School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court is calling for a
review of a labor union's challenge to increase teaching workloads
at overseas schools.
   At issue are additional duties for teachers at 250 schools for
children of U.S. military personnel, operated by a unit of the
Defense Department.
   The appeals court on Thursday reversed a decision of the Federal
Labor Relations Authority that had supported the Defense
Department's refusal to bargain with the teachers about the extra
work.
   ``The Authority never measured the impact of management's
changes upon the ... employees,'' said the ruling by U.S. Court of
Appeals Judge Spottswood Robinson.
   In 1984, administrators with the Department of Defense Dependent
Schools announced changes that would reduce hiring of substitute
teachers, thereby requiring full-time teachers were to fill in.
Hiring of outside help to monitor lunchrooms and playgrounds also
would be discontinued, with full-time teachers and professionals
handling these chores. Additional work was subsequently instituted
for compensatory education programs as well.
   The Overseas Education Association submitted proposals designed
to minimize the effect of the changes. DODDS bargained on some of
them, but refused to do so on others.
   The Labor Relations Authority upheld the Defense Department
unit, saying the union's proposals interfered directly with
management's reserved right to assign work.
   The union, however, said its proposals qualified for bargaining
because they involved adversely-affected employees.
   The extra duties, said the union, forced the teachers do some
work on their own time at home.
   ``The Authority missed the point completely,'' said the judge.
Robinson and two judges who concurred in a separate opinion
reversed the Authority's decisions and sent the cases back for
further consideration.
</TEXT>
