<FIRST>r a PM-Memorial-Death     05-26 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Memorial-Death,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>High School Student Dies While Memorializing Friends</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOLTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school student's effort to honor two
classmates killed in a car accident ended in his own death when a
500-pound soccer goal post toppled onto him as he placed a memorial
wreath on top of it.
   Jason Goldfarb, 17, a junior from Stow, died at Clinton Hospital
where he was taken after the accident Thursday morning.
   Nashoba Regional High School Principal Sam Pawluk said Goldfarb
and several other students were distraught over the deaths of
classmates Steven Rausch and Joanne Basteri. Rausch and Basteri
were killed Wednesday night when the car they were riding in struck
a tree.
   ``Today some kids were having trouble coping with that. In their
grief and sorrow, they'd walk out to the soccer field and just sit
and cry out there,'' Pawluk said. ``(Goldfarb) was climbing on the
goal to leave something there as a remembrance. It toppled, fell
over and killed him.''
   Police said Goldfarb was climbing the soccer goal on the campus
field to sit with friends mourning Rausch and Basteri, who Pawluk
said were soccer players in this town about 30 miles west of Boston.
   The principal said that a few students were already sitting on
the 8-foot-high steel goal. One student was treated for minor
injuries and released from the hospital. The others escaped injury.
   Pawluk said the school canceled today's classes but the building
would be open, and teachers and counselors would be available if
students want to talk about the tragedies.
   ``It's been a devastating experience for everyone here, but
we'll get over it,'' Pawluk said. ``We'll grow from it.''
</TEXT>
