<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     05-26 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls Sharply Against Yen, Stocks Rise in Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell sharply against the Japanese yen
Friday, while stock prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange advanced to
a new high.
   The dollar, which started at 140.85 yen, closed at 140.40 yen,
down 1.95 yen from the previous day's close of 142.35 yen. The
currency changed hands between 139.90 yen and 141.10 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which gained 153.57 points
Thursday, added another 186.23 points, or 0.55 percent, to close at
34,191.62 points, a new high.
   ``The dollar was sold slightly during early morning, but as a
whole it was a seesaw game,'' said a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo
who spoke anonymously.
   Another dealer said the market appears to be headed for another
choppy day of short-term, directionless trade.
   Commenting on a government report showing an increase of 3.3
percent in the Tokyo-area consumer price index, Finance Minister
Tatsuo Murayama told a news conference Friday morning that the
report ``is not something to be alarmed about.''
   Maruyama said currency rates had little impact on the latest
Tokyo consumer price index figures, released by the Management and
Coordination Agency. The May index showed an increase of 0.6
percent from the previous month.
   On the stock marekt, dealers said the Nikkei index rose, with
shares being bought broadly due to the relative stability of
exchange rates.
</TEXT>
