<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Environmental Groups Sue EPA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two environmental groups joined the state of
California and the AFL-CIO in suing the Environmental Protection
Agency for allegedly failing to protect consumers from dangerous
pesticides in food.
   The suit asks that the federal courts require the EPA to impose
more stringent regulations on cancer-causing chemicals in food,
especially in processed fruits and vegetables often consumed by
small children.
   Al Meyerhoff, an attorney for the Natural Resources Defense
Council, said the suit is aimed at forcing the EPA to be more
aggresive in prohibiting the use of pesticides on food and to ban
them altogether if they are found to cause cancer.
   Under current EPA procedures, the agency allows the use of some
older pesticides even though agency officials concede that if the
same chemicals were newly introduced they would not be approved
because of health concerns.
   In addition to the Natural Resources Defense Council, plaintiffs
in the lawsuit are Public Citizen, a private environmental and
consumer group in Washington, the state attorney general of
California and the AFL-CIO. The NRDC is a private, non-profit
environmental organization.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Congress Asked To Overhaul Medicare Payments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Physicians and lawmakers are urging Congress
to overhaul the system of Medicare payments that enables a doctor
in New York to receive $7,500 for triple-bypass surgery while a
Kansas colleague only gets $3,500.
   ``The current system is completely out of whack,'' Rep. Wayne
Owens, D-Utah, told the House Energy and Commerce subcommittee on
health and the environment Thursday.
   Witnesses who testified before the House panel agreed the
Medicare physician reimbursement system discriminates against
doctors practicing in rural areas, but they disagreed over ways to
eliminate the inequities.
   Under discussion were the recommendations of the Physician
Payment Review Commission, an independent agency that monitors
Medicare payments and has proposed replacing the present system
with a Medicare fee schedule.
</TEXT>
