<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 0516EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Doctors-Deception     05-26 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Doctors-Deception,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Many Doctors Say They Would Deceive Patients</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many doctors say they would lie to a patient's
family if their errors had led to the patient's death, a study on
deception in the medical profession shows.
   The survey published today in the Journal of the American
Medical Association said many doctors would engage in various forms
of deception to help themselves or to protect patients.
   The lead researcher said the results should not signal distrust
in physicians.
   ``People who read the study superficially might think, `My god,
you can't trust your doctor anymore; they're deceptive,''' said Dr.
Dennis H. Novack.
   ``I would challenge that,'' said Novack, an associate professor
of community health at Brown University Program of Medicine in
Providence, R.I.
   More than two-thirds of doctors surveyed indicated a willingness
to help patients get insurance benefits by misrepresenting a test,
according to the study.
   Doctors ``appear to justify their decisions in terms of the
consequences and to place a higher value on their patients' welfare
and keeping patients' confidences than on truth-telling for its own
sake,'' the researchers said.
   But ``under extreme circumstances, some physicians would
consider deceiving to benefit themselves.''
   More than one-third of the doctors surveyed for the article
indicated they would offer incomplete or misleading information to
the family of a very sick patient after making a mistake that led
to the patient's death.
   Such behavior is not necessarily unethical, said Daniel
Callahan, director of the Hastings Center of Briarcliff Manor,
N.Y., a research institute that studies ethical problems in
medicine. Callahan, a non-physician, was not involved in the study.
   ``I think it is inevitable physicians are fallible, and we need
to understand their fallibility,'' he said. ``I think they don't
have to reveal their errors to patients.''
   Novack said 80 percent of respondents indicated they ``rarely or
never'' use deception in their own practices. The hypothetical
cases posed ``some of the hardest cases they could have,'' he said
in a telephone interview Thursday.
   The researchers presented four hypothetical problems to 211
physicians in an unspecified Northeast state. The doctors answered
multiple-choice questions about what courses of action they would
choose and why.
   More than half of the doctors said they would permit a patient
who had contracted gonorrhea from a prostitute to mislead his wife
_ not the doctor's patient _ about the nature of the disease.
   The deception involved letting the patient tell his wife the
disease was a non-specific urethritis not acquired through sex.
That way, the patient could have his wife get treatment without
jeopardizing his marriage.
   Less than 10 percent of the physicians said they would deceive a
mother to avoid revealing an adolescent daughter's pregnancy, while
more than 30 percent said they would leave the decision entirely up
to the girl.
   Callahan said tradition favors allowing the patient to decide.
   ``If there's any firm rule in medicine _ probably the most firm
rule _ it is that doctors need to maintain patient
confidentiality,'' he said in a telephone interview. ``Refusing to
break a medical confidence has never been called deception.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
