<SECOND>PM-Where's My Gun?,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen Arrested on Gun Charge Asks for Weapon Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 13-year-old boy arrested in the morning with a
loaded automatic handgun went back to police in the evening asking
for his gun back.
   ``He made the trip to come down here to inquire about his gun so
I would at least think that he was serious,'' said Lt. Joseph
Lacorazza.
   In 15 years as a transit police officer, Lacorazza said, he's
never seen anything like it. ``Basically he was informed that the
gun is evidence in the investigation and he couldn't have it.''
   The boy, whose name was not released because of his age, was
stopped at a subway station in the borough of Brooklyn when a
transit policeman saw him enter without paying a fare, said Al
O'Leary, a transit police spokesman.
   As the officer was questioning him, the boy ``made a move inside
his jacket toward his waist,'' O'Leary said. The officer grabbed
him and, with the help of another officer, forced him to the ground.
   The boy was carrying a 9mm Beretta handgun loaded with 15 shots,
as well as three vials of crack cocaine and a beeper, O'Leary said.
   He was charged with criminal possession of a weapon, a
controlled substance and stolen property (the beeper), resisting
arrest and fare-beating.
   After a hearing at Family Court around noon the boy was released
into the custody of a guardian.
