<FIRST>r a PM-HolidayTraffic     05-26 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Holiday Traffic,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Safety Council Predicts 370-470 Holiday Highway Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The summer travel season gets under way with the
Memorial Day holiday weekend and the National Safety Council
predicts that up to 470 people would die in traffic accidents.
   ``Traditionally, Memorial Day means increased traffic on the
highways,'' Bernard Hyland of the Chicago-based council said
Thursday.
   The holiday travel period begins at 6 p.m. Friday and runs until
midnight Monday. The safety council predicted that between 370 and
470 people would die in traffic accidents.
   Last year there were 404 traffic fatalities for the three-day
weekend. The Memorial Day record was set in 1968 when 629 people
were killed in traffic accidents over a four-day weekend. The
three-day record of 597 was set in 1969.
   Although gasoline prices have risen nationwide in the past two
months, the safety council said it was unable to say whether that
would keep more people off the highways.
   ``It's hard to say,'' said Terry Miller of the council's
statistical bureau. ``Nobody knows for sure. If the mileage goes
down, the accidents and fatalities would go down. But nobody knows
how the public will react to the increased prices.''
</TEXT>
