<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     05-26 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Kem is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PLAINS, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the Fat Gang had one thing on
their minds after winning the town's annual community dieting
contest.
   Food.
   ``I'm going to have fried potatoes and corn bread and greasy
fish for dinner tonight,'' a 20-pounds-thinner Kem Friga said as a
dreamy smile crossed his face on Thursday.
   Randy Jackson was met with cold stares when he asked his five
Fat Gang friends, ``Anybody want to come over to my house for some
tuna?''
   For the past eight weeks, 65 teams consisting of six members
each dieted and exercised in hopes of shedding enough pounds to win
the $600 top prize in the community Slim-A-Thon contest sponsored
by the Ozarks Medical Center.
   Collectively, the 282 members of the 47 teams that finished the
contest lost 2,640 pounds. Or put another way, West Plains,
population 10,000, lost 18 imaginary residents weighing about 150
pounds each.
   Co-workers, relatives and friends made up teams sporting names
such as Fat Mommas, Eaton 2 Much, Size 5 In Disguise, The Munchers,
Future Thin and Boatmen's Buffet Busters.
   The groups avoided the embarrassment of weighing individually at
periodic weigh-ins by climbing aboard cattle scales together.
   Some contestants let out a loud ``Moos'' when members of
opposing teams got on the scales Thursday for the final weigh-in at
the hospital parking lot.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City crews discovered gold when they decided to
clean up a statue that hadn't glittered in years.
   The 81-year-old bronze statue of Chief Seattle was stripped of
dirt, grime and corrosion Wednesday to reveal gold leaf applied to
the statue many years ago.
   ``We started stripping and found it,'' said Patricia Tuttle, who
is doing restoration work on the statue for the city. ``It was a
real surprise.''
   The bronze statue located in Tilikum Square was painted with
gold leaf before it was delivered by sculptor James When, Tuttle
said. Records found in Tacoma confirmed the coating.
   Tuttle said it is doubtful that many of the city's approximately
50 bronze statues have gold coats. It is rare to cover bronze with
gold leaf, she said.
   While the name used on the statue is Chief Seattle, the real
name of the Indian chief who befriended white settlers was Chief
Sealth.
</TEXT>
