<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-26 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls Sharply in Tokyo, Stocks Soar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell sharply against the Japanese yen in
Tokyo today, sending stock prices soaring to a record high, traders
said.
   The dollar, which had risen 2.95 yen between Monday and the end
of trading Thursday, finished the week at 140.40 yen, down 1.95 yen
from Thursday's close of 142.35 yen.
   After opening sharply lower at 140.85 yen, the dollar ranged
during the day between 139.90 and 141.10 yen.
   Dealers attributed the dollar's decline to growing cautiousness
about its recent rise.
   ``Most players were beginning to feel the dollar was going up
too far too fast,'' said Masato Sanjo, a dealer at the Tokyo office
of Manufacturers Hanover Trust. ``Also, widespread speculation that
the Bank of Japan will increase its discount rate contributed to
the dollar's decline.''
   The nationally circulated newspaper Asahi Shimbun reported today
that the central bank planned to lift its official discount rate by
0.75 percentage points to 3.25 percent on Wednesday. Bank officials
declined to comment on the report.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average,
which gained 153.57 points Thursday, rose another 186.23 points, or
0.55 percent, to close the week at 34,191.62, another record high.
   Dealers said the rebound in the yen motivated investors to buy
shares which had lost ground this week due to the dollar's sharp
rise.
   ``The market environment is improving,'' said a dealer at a
major Japanese brokerage who spoke on condition of anonymity.
``Once the domestic political situation settles down, I think we
can expect another rally.''
   Volume on the market's first section was estimated at 700
million shares, the same as Thursday.
</TEXT>
