<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 0547EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Ban     05-26 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Ban,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deputies, Minister Squabble Over Restrictions on Rioting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deputies to the new Soviet congress today
quarreled over legal restrictions on demonstrations after a deputy
complained that anti-riot forces were deployed to break up a public
meeting.
   Conservatives won the fight, and a ban on public gatherings in
Moscow remained in effect.
   Minutes after the Congress of People's Deputies convened for a
second day, sociologist Tatyana Zaslavskaya told her colleagues
that voters had called her early today to report that special
forces broke up a gathering on Moscow's Pushkin Square.
   She said the crowd had assembled to meet deputies from the new
congress and demanded the body vote to lift a ban on unauthorized
public gatherings for the duration of the congress' inaugural
session.
   Soviet law permits city authorities to ban parades and
demonstrations to maintain public order. The restrictions often are
invoked against unofficial political activities.
   Yuri Mityunov, a spokesman for the Democratic Union, a
self-styled opposition party with a few thousand members across the
country, told The Associated Press that Thursday's late-night
meeting was called to appeal for more democracy and to meet Moscow
deputies.
   There were no arrests, but the police ``behaved very
aggressively,'' he said.
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who was chosen president by the congress
on Thursday, called Interior Minister Vadim Bakatin to the podium
after Zaslavskaya's speech.
   Bakatin said voters had gathered nationwide to discuss the first
day of the congress and no incidents were reported.
   But the Moscow meeting was different, he said, because city
authorities had banned it in advance.
   Bakatin's statement touched off a noisy quarrel on the floor of
the Congress, whose televised proceedings are part of the Soviet
Union's democratic reforms.
   Conservatives from Central Asia applauded loudly to drown out
podium statements by Moscow reformers Sergei Stankevich and Andrei
D. Sakharov, the human rights activist.
   Stankevich, 35, said he went to the square, which in recent
months has become a gathering place for political debate and
frequent site of demonstrations, and found more than 2,000 people
surrounded by police and special anti-riot forces.
   Sakharov said he went to the square Thursday night after a
crying girl telephoned him from the site.
   ``I spoke to these people, it was a very good conversation about
the problems of the congress,'' he said. ``These are our young
people, our future, actively interested in the congress. They asked
us to go there every day after the end of debates.''
   ``We must not surround these people with police units,''
Sakharov said, recalling that at least 20 people died in Soviet
Georgia last month after security forces broke up a
pro-independence demonstration.
   Gorbachev, as presiding officer of the congress, moved to
resolve the dispute by putting to a vote Ms. Zaslavskaya's request
that Moscow city authorities lift the ban on unauthorized public
meetings while the congress meets.
   During the balloting, Gorbachev announced he had received word
from Moscow Communist Party boss Lev N. Zaikov that city
authorities would permit meetings at Luzhniki, a large park and
stadium area in western Moscow.
   That did not satisfy Mityunov, who said his group will meet in
Pushkin Square anyway, and the conservatives in the Congress held
sway.
   The vote was 1,261-831 against lifting the ban; 30 deputies
abstained.
</TEXT>
