<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 0625EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RocketFailure     05-26 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rocket Failure,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crews Ready Delta Rocket After Scrubbed Launch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Technicians today prepared a Delta 2
for its fifth launch attempt as troubleshooters studied an
electrical problem that stopped the rocket a second before liftoff.
   Air Force officials predict it will be at least Wednesday before
they try again to launch the $20 million Delta 2, which is to carry
a military navigation satellite into orbit for the United States
and its allies.
   Experts concluded Thursday that an electrical problem at the
launch pad caused a computer to shut down the main engine of the
Delta 2. Engineers investigating the aborted launch ``determined
that its cause is most likely an electrical problem and (they)
highly suspect ground equipment,'' said Capt. Ken Warren, an Air
Force spokesman.
   A team of engineers from the Air Force and the rocket's maker,
McDonnell Douglas Astronautics Co. of Huntington Beach, Calif., was
assembled after the scrubbed takeoff Wednesday night of the Delta 2
and its $65 milion payload, a Navstar Global Positioning Satellite.
   A source who requested anonymity said experts found nothing
wrong with the rocket and are investigating the possibility that
thunderstorms, which forced three previous launch postponements,
may have caused a problem in the launch pad's circuitry.
   Officials said a valve stuck shut and starved the Delta 2's main
engine of liquid oxygen, which mixes with a kerosene-type fuel to
propel the rocket. A computer discovered the closed valve and shut
the engine off before it could ignite.
   Launch controllers had sent an engine ignition command, but it
never reached the fuel valve. An open electrical circuit apparently
blocked the command, according to a source.
   The Navstar satellite will tell U.S. and allied military units
their location within 50 feet _ on land, at sea, or in the air _
anywhere on the globe. Launch attempts on Saturday, Sunday and
Tuesday were scrubbed.
</TEXT>
