<FIRST>r i PM-Taiwan-China     05-26 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Taiwan-China,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>1,600 Taiwanese Cut Short Visits to China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,600 Taiwanese cut short their
visits to China and returned home because of spreading unrest
linked to a power struggle in the Chinese leadership, airline
officials reported today.
   Officials of China Airlines, Taiwan's official carrier, and the
Hong Kong-owned Cathay Pacific Airways said they had to assign six
additional flights in the past four days to bring the Taiwanese
back from Hong Kong.
   There are no direct flights between Taiwan and China, and most
Taiwanese fly to Hong Kong or Japan for connecting flights to the
mainland.
   The Nationalist government, which lost a civil war to the
Communists in 1949, opposes official contacts with the Chinese
government.
   But two years ago, it sanctioned visits to China by Taiwanese
for family reunions and later expanded this to include athletes,
journalists, filmmakers and businessmen.
   The United Daily News today reported that violence and looting
occurred in some cities following a student-led democracy movement
that began in Beijing last month and spread throughout China.
   Hsiao Wen-pin, a retired soldier who returned Thursday, said he
and his wife cut short their visit to his hometown in Guiyang in
southern China because the city was a ``dead town,'' the newspaper
reported.
   Hsiao said residents locked themselves indoors to escape street
violence, and he witnessed workers looting a store, the newspaper
reported.
   The student movement brought into the open a power struggle in
the Chinese leadership between hardliners, led by Premier Li Peng,
and moderates, headed by Communist Party Secretary-General Zhao
Ziyang. Zhao was reported under house arrest today, and sources
said he was stripped of his party post.
</TEXT>
