<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Pound Indiana, Ohio</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Scattered severe thunderstorms extended from the lower Great
Lakes into the Ohio Valley early today, hours after a wave of
thunderstorms caused flooding and tornadoes in Indiana and Ohio.
   Six people suffered storm-related injuries in central Indiana
Thursday, including a Markleville woman who injured her leg when a
tree crashed through the living room of her mobile home,
authorities said.
   Elsewhere in the state, a tornado touched down in Portland
Mills, and strong thunderstorm winds blew down a barn and trees in
Jay County and knocked out windows at a courthouse in Rockville.
Golf ball-size hail pounded Gaston, Fishers and northern sections
of Indianapolis.
   By early today, up to 5 inches of rain had fallen across central
Indiana since Thursday afternoon. People had to be rescued from
their cars because of flooding along creeks in northwest
Indianapolis and flood waters were waist deep in Carmel.
   Heavy rain also fell across parts of west-central Ohio, and
roads were flooded across parts of northeast Ohio.
   A tornado in northwest Ohio in Fayette, about 30 miles west of
Toledo, damaged buildings, ripped the tops off trees and turned
around cars and blew out their windows early Thursday, authorities
said. No injuries were reported.
   Severe thunderstorms also rumbled across southern and eastern
Missouri, with golf ball-size hail falling at Brazito, Buffalo and
near Monett. Thunderstorm winds reached 60 mph near Owensville, Mo.
   Severe thunderstorms were developing across Oklahoma and showers
were scattered across eastern Colorado, northwest Kansas and
eastern North Dakota.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
in Oklahoma, Arkansas, the Tennessee and Ohio valleys, the Great
Lakes, New York and much of New England; widely scattered showers
in the Pacific Northwest and western Montana; and widely scattered
thunderstorms in southern Florida.
   Predicted highs: 50s and 60s in the Pacific Northwest, the
northern and central Rockies, the northern Plains and the upper
Great Lakes; 90s from the middle and southern Atlantic Coast across
the Gulf Coast and most of Texas; 100s in southwest Texas and the
desert Southwest; 70s and 80s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 31
degrees at Butte, Mont., to 86 at Del Rio, Texas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 74 fair; Boston 64 partly cloudy; Buffalo 64
rain; Charleston, S.C. 75 foggy; Cincinnati 75 foggy; Cleveland 67
showers; Detroit 64 cloudy; Miami 78 fair; New York 61 fair;
Philadelphia 61 partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 65 foggy; Portland, Maine
57 cloudy; Washington 70 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 44 cloudy; Chicago 62 foggy; Dallas-Fort
Worth 78 partly cloudy; Denver 45 showers; Des Moines 55 fair;
Indianapolis 65 thunderstorms; Kansas City 55 fair; Minneapolis-St.
Paul 53 windy; Nashville 79 fair; New Orleans 78 foggy; St. Louis
63 foggy.
   _West: Albuquerque 65 fair; Anchorage 45 fair; Las Vegas 72
fair; Los Angeles 59 fair; Phoenix 76 fair; Salt Lake City 50 fair;
San Diego 60 fair; San Francisco 51 fair; Seattle 51 partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 61 fair; Toronto 59 showers.
</TEXT>
