<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     05-26 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down in Market Correction, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was down sharply in moderate European
trading today, a trend analysts saw as an expected correction after
a strong surge. Gold prices rose.
   Analysts said the dollar remained fundamentally strong, but that
it needed to come down to about 1.9620 marks before another rise
could be anticipated. The dollar traded at 1.9648 against the West
German currency this morning.
   ``I think the market players feel they can relax a little now
after the dollar's surprising rush earlier this week,'' said one
trader in Milan, Italy.
   Still, the dollar's growing strength raised a question for West
Germany and Japan, which must decide whether to raise interest
rates.
   ``It's a big dilemma for the central banks,'' said another
Italian analyst. ``Higher interest rates will have a positive
effect on exchange rates, but a negative effect on inflation.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar closed down sharply at 140.85 yen, dropping 1.95
yen from Thursday's close. During the Tokyo trading day, the dollar
moved as low as 139.90 yen. Later, in London, the dollar drifted
lower to 140.15 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Thursday:
   _1.9648 West German marks, down from 1.9965
   _1.7225 Swiss francs, down from 1.7650
   _6.6588 French francs, down from 6.7675
   _2.2243 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2480
   _1,242.00 Italian lire, down from 1,444.50
   _1.2040 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2105
   In London, the British pound traded at $1.60 up from about $1.58
late Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $365.75 a troy ounce, up
from $364.75 late Thursday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $367.20.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.55 an ounce to a closing bid
of $366.41.
   Silver bullion in London rose to a bid price of $5.34 a troy
ounce, from $5.26 bid late Thursday.
</TEXT>
