<FIRST>r a PM-WinerySlayings     05-26 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Winery Slayings,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Battle Shaping Up Over Custody of Carmina Salcido</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of killing seven people,
including his wife and two daughters, will ask a court to award
permanent custody rights over his surviving daughter to his Mexican
relatives, his attorney says.
   Ramon Salcido, a former winery worker, also is accused of
slashing 3-year-old Carmina's throat and leaving her to die in a
dump and rock quarry with her sisters. Carmina recovered and is
living with her maternal grandfather.
   Public Defender Marteen Miller said Salcido is claiming his
mother and his siblings have the same right to rear Carmina as the
relatives of his dead wife, Angela Richards Salcido.
   Salcido's mother, Valentina Bojorquez Armendariz, lives in Los
Mochis, northwest Mexico, and is married to a fisherman, Ebitasio
Seja, Salcido's stepfather. Salcido also has two adult sisters and
two adult brothers living in or near Los Mochis, Salcido's hometown.
   On May 10, Superior Court Judge Arnold Rosenfield granted
temporary custody of Carmina to Robert Richards, her maternal
grandfather, after the toddler's release from Petaluma Valley
Hospital.
   The Press Democrat of Santa Rosa said in story published today
that Salcido will contest any attempt by the court to grant
permanent custody to anyone other than members of his family.
   ``She's my daughter and I love her. She's everything I have,''
Salcido said in a telephone call to the newspaper Monday night.
   Rosenfield set a hearing for Tuesday to determine Carmina's
legal status and permanent custody. Salcido probably will attend
the hearing, Miller said.
   ``I'm appalled he's trying to maintain any relationship with her
at all,'' said Richards' lawyer, James DeMartini. ``It's beyond my
comprehension.''
   Salcido is accused of killing Carmina's two sisters, Sofia, 4,
and Teresa, 2. The other victims included Salcido's mother-in-law,
Marian Louise Richards; his sisters-in-law, Ruth Richards, 12, and
Marie Richards, 8; and a co-worker at Grand Cru Vineyards, Tracy
Toovey.
</TEXT>
