<FIRST>r a PM-Networks-Sweeps 1stLd-Writethru a0416 05-26 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Networks-Sweeps, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0416,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Network Viewing Down, But Spiral Slows in May Sweep</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to add that ratings come from A.C. Nielsen Co.;
Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Big-event programming for May and expiration of
the effects of the 1988 scriptwriters strike helped the three
networks at least slow the rate of audience erosion that has
plagued them in recent seasons.
   The networks had a combined average audience share of 65 for the
May sweep, 2 percent lower than May 1988, according to A.C. Nielsen
Co. ratings. Their combined rating was 37.8, compared with 38.7 in
May 1988.
   The decline was less than the 3 percent rate of audience loss
the networks suffered in the 1988-89 season compared with the
1987-88 season. That loss has been chalked up to the effects of the
strike, which delayed the start of the season, and inroads by
cable, videocassettes and independent channels.
   May is one of four ``sweeps'' months a year when local
television ratings are measured for use in negotiating future
advertising rates. The networks tend to load their schedules with
special programming to help local affiliates.
   NBC, which just completed its fourth season win in a row, won
the May sweep, too, with an average rating of 14.6. CBS had an
11.8. Even though ABC had the two top-rated shows in the sweep, the
made-for-TV movie ``Everybody's Baby: The Rescue of Jessica
McClure'' and the sitcom ``Roseanne,'' it came in third with an
11.4.
   NBC's two-parter, ``I Know My First Name Is Steven,'' was the
highest-rated multipart movie of the sweep, with a 24.5 rating and
39 share. It was the highest-rated multiparter for NBC since
``Fatal Vision'' in November 1984, and the highest-rated
multiparter on any network since ``Lonesome Dove'' on CBS in
February.
   ABC's five-part conclusion of ``War and Remembrance'' was the
second highest-rated multiparter of the sweep, though it had a
so-so 14.9 rating.
   ``Everybody's Baby,'' based on the real-life 1987 rescue of a
Midland, Texas, baby from an abandoned water well, had a 22.9
rating and 36 share to become the top-rated show of the sweep.
   ABC's ``Roseanne'' beat out NBC's ``The Cosby Show'' for second
place, which NBC attributed to the effects of sunlight. ``Cosby''
had a lower rating, but higher share, because of its 8 p.m. EDT
time period. Fewer people are in front of their sets in the early
evening because it's still light outside. ``Roseanne'' has a 9 p.m.
time period. And despite the performance of ``Roseanne,'' which was
pre-empted at times during the sweep, ABC lost Tuesday night to NBC.
   NBC won its 16th sweep in 17 sweeps. ABC had broken its winning
streak in February 1988 with the Winter Olympics. NBC has become
such a juggernaut, it is having a hard time finding new
superlatives.
   Gerald Jaffe, NBC's vice president for research projects, said
he was so impressed that NBC had won five nights a week during the
May sweep, he had his staff check to see when a network last
accomplished that feat. The answer: NBC _ in the last sweep in
February.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890526-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 0832EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0482 05-26 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0482,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian Buildup Reported in Lebanon, Israel Watching Closely</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Arab Summit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with details Israeli Cabinet meeting,
reports of Israeli jets flying over Lebanon, details of Syrian flights.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syria has reinforced its 40,000 troops in
Lebanon with an armored tank brigade, and Syrian fighter planes
flew over Christian positions today, Israeli and Lebanese media
reported.
   Israel's Cabinet met in special session to discuss the troop
moves, Israel radio said. An Israeli official, who requested
anonymity, confirmed a special Cabinet session was convened
Thursday night but refused to give details.
   Israeli officials said they were watching the situation closely
but saw no reason to interfere as long as Israel's northern border
was not affected.
   ``As long as we don't feel directly threatened, there is no way
Israel is going to intervene,'' said Foreign Ministry spokesman
Alon Liel.
   It was not immediately clear how the Syrian moves would affect
the fighting in Lebanon. More than 350 people have been killed and
nearly 1,400 wounded since Christian and Moslem forces began
shelling each other's positions March 8 in the latest round of
fighting in Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war.
   The Syrian reinforcements also came as the Arab League met in
Morocco to discuss ways of enforcing a cease-fire it declared in
Lebanon on May 11.
   A spokesman for Christian forces in Lebanon said two Israeli
warplanes flew over the Chouf mountains southeast of Beirut today
and drew heavy anti-aircraft fire from Syrian-backed Druse
militiamen. No hits were observed, he said.
   The media reports did not say how many additional Syrian troops
were moved into eastern Lebanon, but the daily Yediot Ahronot said
they included 40 tanks. The troop movements were part of an
exercise involving helicopter commandos backed by aircraft and
tanks, the newspaper and radio reports said.
   The Syrian exercise was reportedly taking place in the Bekaa
Valley near the Syrian border and not near the Golan Heights, which
would be of major concern to Israel. But Christian radio reports in
Lebanon said Syrian aircraft were flying over Beirut and the
Christian enclave.
   A spokesman for the Christian army commander, Gen. Michel Aoun,
said four Syrian jet fighters flew at high altitudes ``from the
northern border to Beirut for more than an hour beginning at 6:15
a.m.''
   ``They veered off over Beirut and headed back north. They
carried out the practice repeatedly,'' said the spokesman.
   He said Christian army units did not open fire at the jets.
   Motta Gur, a former army chief of staff, said on Israel radio
that the troop movements seemed more a political move aimed at Arab
leaders attending the Arab League summit in Casablanca than a
threat to Israel's security.
   ``We have to watch the situation closely, but in my assessment
it's more an inner-Arab issue. The fact is that in Casablanca they
got into difficulties,'' he said. The summit is trying to find a
compromise to Syria's refusal to end its fight with Christian armed
forces.
   Syria has rejected calls from Iraq to withdraw its forces from
Lebanon to help end that nation's civil war. Syrian soldiers have
been in Lebanon since 1976 under an Arab League peacekeeping
mandate.
   Israel maintains a six-to-10-mile-wide security zone in southern
Lebanon.
   Military sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said Israel
had not raised the alert status of its troops along the border.
   Syria's movement of anti-aircraft missiles into Lebanon in 1981
touched off a crisis, and the two armies clashed during Israel's
invasion of Lebanon in 1982. Tensions also increased after Syria
sent troops back into Beirut.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
