<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 0855EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--MomentofSilence     05-26 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Moment of Silence,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commercial Radio Stations Broadcast Moment of Silence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 8,000 commercial radio stations nationwide
went silent for 30 seconds today to mark the beginning of a $100
million advertising campaign aimed at highlighting what life would
be like without radio.
   At 7:42 a.m. EDT, actor James Earl Jones told listeners that
``for the next 30 seconds this station and others would like you to
imagine your life without radio. Imagine if all your days sounded
like this. ...''
   The following 30 seconds were filled with silence. Jones then
cut in and said, ``Thirty seconds seems like a long time, doesn't
it? Now think how radio fills that silence for you.''
   About 80 percent of the nation's commercial stations
participated in the opening stage of the yearlong campaign, the
Radio Advertising Bureau said.
   The simultaneous promotion is the largest in the history of
radio, said Danny Flamberg of the Radio Advertising Bureau. In
1986, 2,000 radio stations simultaneously broadcast ``We Are The
World'' to promote hunger relief.
</TEXT>
