<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru   05-26 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0498,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fourteen Sentenced to Death in Slaying of Policeman</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with details, appeal promised. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today sentenced 14
black people to death in the 1985 killing of a black police officer
who was beaten and set on fire by a mob.
   The defendants, singing an African hymn as they marched into
court in the northwest city of Upington, were among 25 people
convicted of murder in the slaying of police Constable Lucas
Sethwala in nearby Paballelo township.
   Under South African law, the death sentence is mandatory for
people convicted of murder unless the judge determines there were
mitigating circumstances.
   The 11 other defendants are to be sentenced next week, but the
judge already has determined there were extenuating circumstances
and the death penalty will not be imposed. Sentencing also is
scheduled for a 26th defendant convicted of attempted murder.
   Most of the 13 men and one women sentenced to death today
proclaimed their innocence during the hearing before Supreme Court
Justice Jan Basson.
   ``I am an elderly woman and have been found guilty for something
I have not done. ... Other people committed this crime,'' said
Evelina de Bruin, 60.
   Only one of the 25, Justice Bekebeke, was found to have
committed the act that killed Sethwala, said defense lawyer Andy
Durbach.
   She said the sentences will be appealed. The group is the
largest ever sentenced to death in a single crime in South Africa,
she said.
   Bekebeke, 24, did not maintain his innocence in his address to
the court today but said the case was ``based on racial prejudice.''
   Because the death sentence is mandatory, the defendants knew
their sentences because the judge already had ruled on Thursday
that there were no extenuating circumstances.
   Prosecutors said the 25 people were part of a crowd of 300 who
pelted the victim's house with stones. At one point he fired a gun
out the window, wounding a small boy, which defense lawyers said
incited the crowd to assault the man and set him on fire.
   Basson noted that 3,000 people had gathered on a soccer field in
the township the previous day to protest rent hikes and other
actions by township authorities. He said the killing was
politically motivated, part of a conspiracy to attack authorities.
   He rejected defense arguments that the individual defendants
could not be held accountable for the actions of the crowd. One of
those convicted was described by witnesses as a best friend of the
victim.
   Defense lawyer Anton Lubowski said 10 defendants were sentenced
to death but found to not have physically contributed to the
officer's death.
   The 25 were convicted of murder in April 1988 under the
principle of common purpose, which holds them responsible for the
actions of a crowd if they were part of the group.
   The same principle was used against the Sharpeville Six, a group
of black men and women convicted of slaying a black town council
member during the nationwide political unrest that gripped black
townships from 1984-86.
   After an international campaign, President P.W. Botha last year
commuted the death sentences for the Sharpeville Six and replaced
them with lengthy prison terms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
