<FIRST>r a PM-JetBaby     05-26 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jet Baby,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>No-Contest Plea By Mother of Baby Left on Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REDWOOD CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mother who abandoned her newborn
daughter in a jetliner's restroom before a cross-country flight has
pleaded no contest to felony child endangerment.
   Christine LoCasto, 27, of New York City, entered her plea
Thursday after a prosecutor promised not to seek a prison term.
Sentencing was set for Aug. 9.
   She originally pleaded innocent.
   The baby, Alyssa, was found under a restroom sink July 13
shortly after the jetliner landed in San Francisco and the
passengers departed. The child had apparently been born shortly
before the plane took off from Newark, N.J.
   The child, now 10 months old, is in the custody of her paternal
grandparents in New York.
   Mrs. LoCasto was accompanied by her husband, Louis, when she
entered the plea in San Mateo County Superior Court. The couple
have two other children.
   LoCasto, who was on the flight with his wife last July, was
apparently unaware she was pregnant and did not know she had given
birth in the restroom.
   Judge Margaret Kemp gave no indication she will accept
prosecutor Steve Wagstaffe's recommendation against prison. The
felony charge carries a maximum penalty of six years in state
prison, six years' probation and a $10,000 fine.
   The prosecutor noted that Mrs. LoCasto had no criminal record
and that the baby was unharmed. And he said he still does not know
why the mother abandoned the baby.
   Her attorney, Richard Bennett, said Mrs. LoCasto's explanation
was ``very complicated'' and that he did not want to invade her
privacy by talking about it.
</TEXT>
