<FIRST>r a PM-BusShooting     05-26 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bus Shooting,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Passenger Fatally Shot in Argument Over Bus Fare</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A city bus driver argued with a passenger over an
unpaid fare and then shot the man to death as he was leaving,
authorities said.
   Chauncey J. Plummer, 37, a Dallas bus driver for 10 years, was
charged with murder Thursday in the death of David Hayden, 25. He
was released on $25,000 bond.
   Plummer picked up Hayden and a woman on a downtown street
Wednesday, said Ron Whittington, spokesman for Dallas Area Rapid
Transit. The driver told authorities that in his rearview mirror he
saw the woman hand her bus pass to Hayden, who then tried to use it
for his fare.
   The driver told Hayden he could not use the pass, an argument
ensued and Plummer ordered Hayden off the bus. The man was shot in
the back with a revolver as he exited, then he stumbled off the bus
and collapsed, witnesses said.
   The driver radioed for help, then waited in the bus for police
to arrive and surrendered without incident.
   Hayden died Wednesday evening at Baylor University Medical
Center.
   Because of the shooting, DART is reviewing its procedure for
checking drivers for weapons, and may begin placing plainclothes
police officers on routes where problems have been reported.
   Drivers on Thursday expressed concern about the incident.
   ``They wanted us to be aware that there are some problems on the
routes and we need to address those,'' Whittington said. ``That
does not condone what has allegedly happened, but we're trying to
be sensitive to the drivers.''
   Plummer has been assaulted twice on the bus route in the past
couple of years, once breaking his hand and the other time
suffering a black eye, Whittington said.
</TEXT>
