<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-HungerStrike 1stLd-Writethru a0484 05-26 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Hunger Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0484,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korean Radical Students Copy Chinese Hunger Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 3 grafs after last, ``Radicals claim ...'' to UPDATE with
minister denouncing flag burnings, new government body for U.S. affairs.
No Pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 300 radical students adopted
tactics used by Chinese protesters and began a hunger protest today
to demand the government admit that police killed a student leader.
   Students chanted anti-government slogans and songs at Myongdong
Cathedral to call for the fall of President Roh Tae-woo's
government and demand police acknowlege they fatally tortured
student leader Lee Chol-gyu.
   ``Overthrow the murder regime!'' and ``Down with Roh Tae-woo!''
protesters chanted. Riot police watched but made no move to
intervene.
   About 100 students chanted slogans at the Roman Catholic
cathedral's main gate. The other students rested in the compound or
took part in discussion groups, taking water but no food. Students
stayed out of the cathedral and administration buildings.
   Radical student leaders said they were using the same tactics as
Chinese students fasting in Beijing to demand the introduction of
democracy and other sweeping changes. Some students claimed they
would fast to the death if their demands were not met.
   ``We are more determined than the students fasting in China,'' a
student leader told a news conference after the protesters moved
into the cathedral compound overnight.
   In recent days, newspapers have pointed out the differences
between the pro-democracy Chinese protesters and the anti-Western
Korean students, who demand an ill-defined ``workers and farmers
state.''
   The newspapers have commended the Chinese for their peaceful
tactics and urged Korean students to end violent protests. The
editorials have urged Korean students to abandon their leftist
views, saying the Chinese protesters are inspired by opposition to
communism.
   ``It is regrettable that some students and intelluctals in our
country are obsessed with socialism, an old ideology that communist
nations are trying to reform,'' the moderate Jooang Daily News said
Thursday.
   Radical students in South Korea lack popular support because of
their extreme views and violent tactics. Some student groups have
been trying to switch tactics after six riot troopers were killed
May 3 in a clash in the southern city of Pusan.
   A seventh riot trooper injured in the May 3 clash died Thursday
night, police said. The deaths outraged the public.
   Radical students and dissidents claim Lee was tortured and
killed by police and are demanding the government acknowledge a
cover-up. Lee's body was found May 10 in a reservoir near the
southern city of Kwangju.
   Police and government officials deny any official involvement in
Lee's death, although police tried to detain him at a roadblock
just before he disappeared. The government says an autopsy proves
Lee was not tortured, and officials speculate he slipped into the
reservoir and drowned.
   The protesters in the cathedral compound today put up posters
with color pictures of Lee's bloated body.
   Crowds of up to 100,000 people marched in Kwangju last week to
demand the government admit police killed Lee. The demonstrations
also called for Roh's fall for the bloody suppression of a 1980
uprising in Kwangju. Radicals claim the United States was involved
in Kwangju and are demanding expulsion of the 43,000 U.S. troops
based in South Korea under a defense treaty.
   Protests in Korea often include the burning of U.S. flags, which
Culture and Information Minsiter Choe Byung-yul deplored today as
``an uncivilized act'' intended to damage Seoul's friendship with
Washington.
   Also today, the government announced Foreign Minister Choi
Ho-joong will lead a new government body of 10 vice ministers with
authority to decide on U.S.-related issues involving American
troops, anti-Americanism and trade.
   Seoul has been seeking greater control over crimes involving
American troops and other matters.
</TEXT>
