<FIRST>r a PM-IllinoisGunControl     05-26 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Illinois Gun Control,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Illinois Senate Rejects Gun Control Measures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS CONRAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Illinois Senate shot down a package
of measures that would have toughened handgun laws and imposed a
limited ban on semiautomatic assault weapons.
   By a 2-1 margin, lawmakers Thursday defeated bills requiring
handgun owners to register their weapons with state police, obtain
identification cards, and notify authorities of change of address.
   The Senate fell two votes short of banning semiautomatic weapons
using magazines or ammunition belts containing more than 10 rounds.
California recently enacted a similar ban.
   ``People are more concerned with the will of the National Rifle
Association than they are of the desires of their own
constituents,'' said William Marovitz, one of two sponsors of the
bills.
   Sen. David Barkhausen said the bill's proposal to register the
guns would have cost $7.6 million and created a bureaucratic
nightmare.
   Currently, people may own any type of firearm with a single
firearm owner's identification card. The rejected measure would
have required a separate card for handguns.
   The Senate did approve a measure sponsored by Marovitz that
would allow revocation of a firearm owner's identification card if
a judge determines that the owner presents a ``clear and present
danger'' to himself or others.
   Another rejected measure would have banned former mental
patients from owning handguns.
   Gun control advocates had hoped their efforts would gain after
incidents like the shooting spree last May 20 in a Winnetka
elementary school. Laurie Dann, a mentally disturbed woman, shot
five students, killing one, before committing suicide.
</TEXT>
