<FIRST>r i PM-Kenya-Sudan     05-26 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kenya-Sudan,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sudanese Rebels To Meet Khartoum Officials for Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY CHEGE MBITIRU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sudanese rebels will meet officials of the
Khartoum government next month to discuss ending a six-year civil
war that has killed hundreds of thousands of people, a rebel
spokesman said today.
   Lam Akol, international relations director of the Sudan People's
Liberation Army, said Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi's government
requested the meeting, which will take place at the rebels'
headquarters in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia.
   ``Our position has not changed,'' Akol said in Nairobi. ``But
they asked for a meeting, and we said it would be OK.''
   On Thursday, university professor Hamad Baggadi announced in
Khartoum that he would lead the government's peace committee to a
June 10 meeting with the southern-based rebels. Baggadi is a member
of Mahdi's governing Umma party.
   Akol said the rebels want Mahdi to lift the state of emergency,
abrogate Sudan's military pacts with other nations, and convene a
conference of all Sudanese political parties to draft a new
constitution. The second demand is aimed at Libya, which has helped
Sudan fight the southern rebellion.
   Mahdi already has formed a new, broader-based government and won
Parliament's approval to suspend harsh Islamic laws _ moves made
under pressure from the military, which wants to negotiate an end
to the insurrection.
   Rebel leader John Garang recently announced a monthlong
unilateral cease-fire to permit the United Nations to get emergency
food and other supplies to southern Sudan, where 100,000 people
face starvation from war-induced famine.
   The rebels took up arms in 1983 against the Moselm-dominated
government, demanding social and economic reforms for the southern
minority, who are mainly Christians and animist.
</TEXT>
