<FIRST>r a PM-EvergladesFire     05-26 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Everglades Fire,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Dampens Everglades Fire, But Lightning Creates Smaller Blazes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK REYNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rainstorm aided firefighters battling a
10-day-old blaze in Everglades National Park today but lightning
started several small fires in neighboring Big Cypress National
Preserve, officials said.
   Firefighters said they hoped to declare the 85,000-acre
Everglades blaze contained by sunset, with only isolated patches of
smoke and fire remaining.
   ``Our fire is about 85 percent contained,'' said forest ranger
Paul Krumland, who expected the fire to be declared contained by 6
p.m.
   Thursday afternoon's rain ``did more good than bad for us,''
Krumland said. ``But bad lightning strikes did come down in Big
Cypress National Preserve, and they're working on that now.''
   At Big Cypress, which is west of the Everglades, spokesman Kevin
Walsh said 20 firefighters worked through the night to contain a
300-acre fire that began earlier. In addition, he said, lightning
began eight smaller fires Thursday, each covering only a few acres.
   The Everglades fire is centered about 30 miles southwest of
Miami. Nearly 250 firefighters from around the country have fought
the blaze since it was started by lightning May 16.
   The marshy sawgrass and isolated hardwood hammocks in the area
hadn't burned in more than 30 years, said park spokeswoman Pat
Tolle. Such fires before the rainy season normally cause only
limited damage by burning off the top of the grass.
   ``We'll see,'' she said. ``As soon as the summer rains begin,
there'll be a lush regrowth of the sawgrass.''
   On Tuesday, the fire briefly threatened the Miccosukee Indian
village at the park's northern edge. But then it shifted direction,
and heavy smoke kept the park's neighboring Shark Valley visitor
center closed until Thursday morning.
   About 400 wildfires have scorched 350,000 acres of grass and
brush in southern Florida since last October, according to state
estimates.
</TEXT>
