<FIRST>r a PM-DayCareCharges     05-26 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Day Care Charges,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sex Charges Dropped Against Former Day Care Operator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARKHAM, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors have dropped sex-abuse charges
against a former day-care center operator who said she was elated
but felt ``violated'' by more than two years of investigations and
a trial.
   Sandra Fabiano had been charged with sexually abusing four
preschool-age girls at her two day-care centers in suburban
Chicago. The first trial, involving one of the girls, ended in
acquittal March 30.
   Mary Ellen Cagney and Richard Burke, assistant Cook County
state's attorneys, said the remaining charges were dropped Thursday
to spare child witnesses from the trauma of a trial.
   ``I feel like a champagne bottle has just been opened,'' said
Mrs. Fabiano, 42.
   ``I am a free woman now, but I felt that I didn't have any
rights throughout the whole thing,'' she said. ``I felt I was
violated as was my family and my children.''
   She accused prosecutors of mishandling the case and said she
believes the charges were dropped because the state had no evidence
in the remaining cases.
   But Ms. Cagney said the investigation was ``very thorough'' and
``sensitive to the rights of the family.''
   ``She was not locked up,'' Ms. Cagney said. ``We were very aware
of her rights and those of her family throughout the
investigation.''
   Mrs. Fabiano's lawyers have filed a lawsuit asking that a judge
overturn the state's decision to revoke her day-care license. And
the parents of the four girls have sued Mrs. Fabiano.
   The investigation began in April 1987, when the mother of the
child involved in the first trial said her 3-year-old daughter had
said that ``Teacher Sandy did something to me.''
   Mrs. Fabiano said she hoped dismissal of the charges would
inspire new laws protecting teachers and others who work with
children from unfounded charges of sexual abuse. ``I would never
want to see anyone else go through this,'' she said.
</TEXT>
