<FIRST>r a PM-People-O'Connor     05-26 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-O'Connor,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cardinal Says Going to Lebanon is Priestly Responsibility</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John O'Connor says he will travel to
Lebanon despite the obvious risks because there are ``suffering
people out there who look to the church.''
   ``The chances of having something undesirable happen are real,
but I'm leaving with the expectation of coming back,'' O'Connor
said shortly before leaving the United States Thursday. O'Connor
heads the Roman Catholic archdiocese of New York.
   O'Connor acknowledged that the State Department warned him of
the danger of being killed or taken captive.
   ``I don't think I'd be worth much as a captive,'' O'Connor said,
adding that he appreciated the government's expressions of concern.
   ``But I'm a priest and I have priestly responsibilities,'' he
said.
   O'Connor said the church ``is very fragile there. It could be
obliterated.''
   O'Connor said he was making the journey on a Vatican passport
and visa.
   The visit of about three days will permit O'Connor, in his role
as head of the Catholic Near East Welfare Mission, to visit
clinics, hospitals and orphanages the church operates in Lebanon.
