<FIRST>u p PM-Mondale-Senate 2ndLd-Writethru a0528 05-26 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mondale-Senate, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0528,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mondale Won't Seek Senate Seat</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with additional comment from Mondale news
conference, Boschwitz reaction and background; no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY R. SANDOK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Vice President Walter F. Mondale said
today he will not enter the 1990 race for a U.S. Senate seat in
Minnesota and will not seek any other elective office in the future.
   ``I believe it's time for other candidates to step forward,''
said Mondale, a former senator who was the Democratic Party's
presidential nominee in 1984. ``It was a very difficult choice for
us.''
   Mondale, 61, said he has enjoyed his life out of political
office and has seen too many colleagues remain in the Senate for
too long. He was considering running against incumbent Rudy
Boschwitz, a Republican.
   ``I'm at peace with myself,'' Mondale said. ``We took a lot of
time making this decision and it's a basic one. It's a lot easier
deciding when to get into politics as opposed to when to leave.''
   A poll commissioned by Mondale indicated that the former vice
president could defeat Boschwitz in the 1990 race. The poll,
released by Mondale's son, Ted Mondale, shows Mondale leading
Boschwitz 51 percent to 40 percent, with 8 percent undecided.
   ``Fritz Mondale clearly would have been the toughest competitor
I could have had,'' Boschwitz told a news conference in St. Paul.
``I certainly do have a sense of relief that he will not be the
competitor.''
   Mondale, a protege of the late Hubert H. Humphrey, generally had
been considered the most formidable candidate Democrats could field
against Boschwitz, a two-term senator. Mondale's announcement was
expected to result in an immediate scramble among Minnesota
Democrats for the 1990 Senate endorsement.
   The only announced challenger to Boschwitz is Democratic
National Committee member Paul Wellstone, a political science
professor at Carleton College and a leader of the Rev. Jesse
Jackson's 1988 presidential campaign in Minnesota.
   Boschwitz, 58, was elected to the Senate in 1978.
   Mondale represented Minnesota in the Senate from 1965 until
1976, when he left to be Jimmy Carter's vice president. He ran
unsuccessfully for president against Ronald Reagan in 1984.
   Speculation that he planned to run again began in June 1987,
when Mondale moved from Washington, D.C., back to Minnesota to
practice law with a Minneapolis firm.
   Mondale said today he was certain two years ago that he would
``not be tempted by yet another race for political office.'' But he
said he considered running against Boschwitz because he loved
public life and the U.S. Senate and believed he would have a strong
chance of winning.
   Mondale said he decided two days ago, after seeking advice from
numerous friends and associates, to end his political career.
   He and his wife, Joan, spent more than 30 years in the
``political pressure cooker,'' Mondale said.
   ``For the first time in our lives, we have time to enjoy private
life, to be with our family and friends and time to pursue our
other interests that we could never do before,'' he said.
   ``I am finding that I can be heard on public matters while
remaining in private life.''
   Mondale said those from whom he sought counsel were nearly
unanimous in urging him to run, but nearly all of them also said
they would understand if he didn't.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
