<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 1112EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan     05-26 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Takeshita's Departure Postponed By Lack of Candidates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disgraced Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita will stay
in office longer than expected because the governing party has been
unable to find a successor, party officials said today.
   Liberal Democratic Party officials also said Takeshita accepted
a request from party executives to help in the search, which has
been stalled since the most likely candidate rejected the post.
   Although he originally was scheduled to step down at the end of
this month, Takeshita has agreed to remain in office until the
party selects a new prime minister.
   Officials who spoke on condition of anonymity said Takeshita
will meet party Secretary-General Shintaro Abe on Saturday to
discuss possible choices.
   Takeshita announced April 25 that he would leave office when the
fiscal 1989 budget cleared parliament to take responsibility for a
bribery scandal and consequent loss of confidence in his party.
   The budget bill becomes law Sunday, but no candidates have
emerged to replace Takeshita.
   The Liberal Democrats' search for a new leader suffered a major
setback May 13 when Masayoshi Ito, a reform-minded party veteran,
refused to take the job. He cited his age of 75, failing health and
a disagreement with party leaders over political reform measures.
   A new leader is needed to clean up the party's scandal-tainted
image and salvage its plunging popularity before an election for
half the seats in parliament's upper house, expected in June.
   The party is facing the worst crisis in its 34-year history
because of a corruption and influence-peddling scandal named after
Recruit. Co, an information and publishing congolemerate accused of
selling politicians shares at low prices in exchange for favors.
   The scandal forced Takeshita's resignation and led to indictment
of a former Cabinet minister and senior bureaucrats. It also has
damaged the political futures of dozens of senior politicians,
including former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone.
   News reports speculate that two of the most likely prospects to
replace Takeshita are former Prime Minister Takeo Fukuda, 84, and
former lower house Speaker Michita Sakata, 72.
</TEXT>
