<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-Escapes     05-26 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Escapes,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ultralight Pilots Say They Spirited Friend From East Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two ultralight planes landed in front of the
Reichstag building in West Berlin early today, and two men
reportedly claimed they flew a friend to freedom in a daring escape
from East Germany,
   Police said they were mystified by the landings and had no
independent confirmation of the reported escape.
   The planes were abandoned after landing in front of the
Reichstag building, next to the Berlin Wall, at about 5 a.m.,
police said. The pilots were not seen, and police later towed the
aircraft away.
   Police first said they doubted the planes were used for an
escape but later said they were not ruling out such a possibility.
   An anonymous caller telephoned several radio stations to claim
he flew his relatives out of East Germany to West Berlin.
   Rainer Hildebrandt, head of a private organizaton that monitors
escapes from East Germany, said two men came to his office and
claimed they were the pilots. He said the two men told him they
flew into East Germany, picked up a friend and flew back to West
Berlin.
   Hildebrandt said he could not confirm the claim. It was not
immediately clear why the men would have needed to planes to pick
up their friend.
   The men told Hildebrandt they had recorded the flight on film
and wanted to sell it, Hildebrandt said. They refused to appear
before reporters, Hildebrandt said in a telephone interview.
   He said the men were between 30 and 40 years of age but did not
identify themselves. They said they were former East German
citizens who have been living in the West, he said.
   Hildebrandt heads Working Group August 13, a private
organization that monitors escapes and human rights in East Germany.
   Witnesses reported the propeller-driven aircraft flew parallel
to the Berlin at an alititude of about 165 feet, police said.
   Police said the olive-green planes were marked with red stars
pasted onto the wings with yellow tape. This could have been a ruse
designed to fool East German border guards, police said.
   Police said the abandoned ultralights appeared to be the same as
two aircraft transported to West Berlin from West Germany four
weeks ago.
   The planes were transported in parts and authorities had given
permission for the aircraft to be assembled but not flown, police
said.
</TEXT>
