<HEAD>Police Stop Hijack of Czech Passenger Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today stopped a 41-year-old
man from hijacking a Czechoslovak passenger plane as it flew from
Prague to the nearby town of Karlovy Vary, the official CTK news
agency.
   The man, identified as Bohuslav Behula, was ``rendered harmless
by the police during the attempt,'' the agency said.
   That is a phrase security forces often use when they kill a
dangerous criminal, but it was not possible to determine whether
Behula was slain.
   Czechoslovak planes normally have one or more security agents
aboard, but the report did not say how Behula was subdued.
   None of the 24 passengers or crew of the Soviet-made JAK 4O
plane was injured, CTK said. The plane landed in Karlovy Vary, 70
miles west of Prague.
