<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Ban     05-26 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Ban,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judges Reject Journalists' Appeal of Broadcast Banp ^Eds: MccGwire
cq in 9th graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court today upheld the government's ban on
broadcast interviews with members of extremist groups in Northern
Ireland. Lawyers for journalists said they may appeal.
   Six broadcast journalists said the ban on interviews with groups
such as the Irish Republican Army and the Ulster Freedom Fighters
was unlawful, an unjustifiable interference with freedom of
expression, and a violation of the European Convention on Human
Rights.
   But three High Court judges ruled that Home Secretary Douglas
Hurd acted reasonably and lawfully, and with the majority approval
of Parliament, in imposing the ban in October.
   Hurd's order prohibits the British Broadcasting Corp. and the
Independent Broadcasting Authority, which oversees commercial TV,
from broadcasting words spoken by Northern Ireland extremists. The
extremists' actions, objectives and views can be reported.
   The rule applies to the IRA and its legal political wing Sinn
Fein, which are fighting to end British rule in Northern Ireland,
as well as the Ulster Freedom Fighters, an outlawed Protestant
extremist group that wants the province to remain British.
   Lord Justice Tasker Watkins, announcing the decision, said the
ban did not prevent either the BBC or commercial television from
reporting events in Northern Ireland ``with due impartiality.''
   He said the reasonableness of Hurd's ban was reflected in the
parliamentary debates in which many lawmakers said the restrictions
were justified by the need to fight terrorism in Northern Ireland.
   Jacob Ecclestone, deputy general secretary of the National Union
of Journalists, said an appeal was likely all the way to the House
of Lords, Britain's highest court.
   Broadcaster Scarlett MccGwire, one of the plaintiffs, called the
ruling ``a blow to the British public.''
   ``The case is not just about journalists not being able to
report Northern Ireland properly. It is about people not being able
to understand what is happening there because it is not reported
properly,'' she said.
   The plaintiffs claimed the restrictions were unjustified,
especially since the amount of broadcasting time given in the past
to interviews with members of proscribed organizations had been
``trifling'' and had not shown those interviewed in a good light.
   Watkins said the question for the court was not whether Hurd's
decision was politically wise or unwise but simply whether it was
lawful.
</TEXT>
