<FIRST>u a PM-SwindallTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0458 05-26 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Swindall Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0458,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Battle Lines Drawn In Trial Of Former Congressman Swindall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, `Mullaney, the..', with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with morning testimony, problem with videotape. Picks up 5th graf pvs,
`He said...'. SUBS 11th graf, `The two-term...', to add background on election.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Battle lines have been drawn in the perjury trial
of former Rep. Pat Swindall, with prosecutors saying he negotiated
to borrow drug money and lied about it and Swindall's lawyers
saying he was duped.
   Swindall is accused of lying to a federal grand jury about his
dealings with an Internal Revenue Service undercover agent, Mike
Mullaney, and a Swindall associate, Charles LeChasney, later
convicted of money laundering.
   Prosecutors say Swindall negotiated to use LeChasney as a
middleman in an attempt to borrow $850,000 for construction of his
luxury home from a money broker representing drug interests _
actually the undercover agent.
   Mullaney, the first witness for the prosecution, testified today
that at his first meeting with Swindall in August 1987, the
congressman ``brought up the possibility'' of having LeChasney
create ``some sort of corporation ... and he would basically get
his money from Charles LeChasney's company.''
   Prosecutors played a videotape for the jury of that meeting, but
jurors complained they couldn't hear the soundtrack properly. A
recess was called while court officials worked on the problem.
   On Thursday, when he began his testimony, Mullaney had said that
LeChasney told him that Swindall ``didn't care where the money came
from.''
   He said he also was interested in meeting Swindall to
investigate whether Swindall's plans to sell a $1 million note at a
discount for cash ``would lead to an evasion of his income taxes''
and violations of currency laws.
   In opening statements Thursday, Swindall's attorney, Richard
Hendrix, told the jury that Swindall and the government were duped
by ``Charles LeChasney, the master manipulator.''
   Hendrix described LeChasney as ``a man with a severe mental
disorder ... a sociopath,'' and said LeChasney repeatedly fooled
Swindall into thinking the money was legitimate, and fooled the
government into thinking that Swindall was a tax-evading ``crook.''
   Hendrix told the jury that Swindall never agreed to the deal and
that he continued to shop for and ultimately got other financing
for his home.
   After Swindall did his best to recall for the grand jury in
February 1988 events of five months earlier, Hendrix said, the
former congressman was indicted anyway by a government
``predisposed to believe he's a crook.''
   Swindall was indicted Oct. 17 on 10 counts of lying to a federal
grand jury, each of which carries a penalty of 10 months to five
years in prison.
   The two-term Republican congressman lost his 4th District seat
in Atlanta's eastern suburbs to Democrat Ben Jones, a onetime actor
in television's ``Dukes of Hazzard,'' in November. The campaign was
one of the most bitter House races in the country and one of only a
handful that ended up in the defeat of an incumbent congressman.
   Briefs unsealed Thursday showed prosecutors have sought to
introduce tapes of LeChasney telling the undercover agent that
Swindall didn't want to know details about the money scheme because
the congressman said he wanted to be sure he could pass a
lie-detector test if necessary.
   The prosecutors said the tapes would show Swindall planned to
lie to the grand jury.
   But defense attorneys contended that if the tapes were admitted
as evidence, they should be allowed to submit evidence that
Swindall passed a lie detector test in which he was asked if he had
lied to the grand jury. Such evidence previously has been ruled
inadmissible in most cases.
</TEXT>
