<HEAD>School Divided in Sexual Assault Case of Mentally Retarded Girl</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs with newspaper report of youth being asked to videotape
assault, superintendent's comments.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARLENE E. SUPERVILLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLEN RIDGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The five teen-agers charged with
sexually assaulting a mentally retarded girl with a toy baseball
bat and a broom handle have been suspended from school for 10 days.
   ``They were not suspended because of the alleged acts, but
because of the disruption their presence in the school would have
on the educational program,'' said Glen Ridge Superintendent of
Schools Rose McCaffrey.
   The five Glen Ridge High School students were arrested Wednesday
and charged with sexually assaulting the girl at the home of two of
the boys, co-captains of the football team, in this Newark suburb.
   Eight other male teens, including the son of a Glen Ridge police
lieutenant, cheered the attack on the 17-year-old girl without
intervening, investigators said. The eight are considered witnesses
and have not been charged.
   At the school's annual ``spring day'' Thursday, the picnics and
games were marred by fights, vandalism and the discovery of
graffiti on walls inside the school building, students said.
   One student shook his head as he removed a rock and shards of
glass from the back seat of his car. Some passers-by in cars
shouted ``rapists'' as they drove past the school.
   Damian DeVito, a 17-year-old junior, defended the accused teens,
two of whom are his football teammates. He said has known the
victim since elementary school and said he believed she willingly
participated in the March 1 incident.
   ``I know them well enough to know they wouldn't do anything
against somebody's will,'' DeVito told reporters. ``These kids are
really not bad kids at all.''
   Karl Greiner, a spokesman for the Association for Retarded
Citizens-New Jersey, called the attack demeaning.
   ``I suppose that she was treated like an object ... a
dehumanizing affair at best, with spectators cheering on,'' Greiner
said. ``It's difficult enough to live your life with a handicap.
It's especially difficult to be treated in a dehumanizing way.''
   A 17-year-old football teammate of some of those charged says he
was asked to videotape them having sex with the victim the day
after the assault, the New York Post reported today.
   Charles Figueroa said he refused to make the tape and eventually
informed authorities about the attack, the newspaper said. There
was no answer this morning at a telephone listing for Figueroa.
   Figueroa's comments are suspect because he ``likes to
fantasize,'' McCaffrey said. She said the student undergoes
counseling in a school resource room.
</TEXT>
