<FIRST>r a PM-LATeachers 1stLd-Writethru a0466 05-26 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-LA Teachers, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0466,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teachers Return To Class Today With More Money, Power</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with teachers returning to class,
quotes from student, principal; Picks up 2nd graf, `The teachers ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers returned to classrooms today with
higher salaries and more authority in the schools after approving a
three-year contract to end a bitter strike in the 594,000-pupil
district.
   Teachers, students and administrators expressed joy and relief
today at the return to regular classes.
   ``I feel just fine because everything is back to normal now,''
said smiling 10th-grader Brenda Montoya as she headed to class at
Belmont High. ``We have our teachers back and now we can get back
to our studies.''
   Principal Marta Lavat Vin told students gathered for an assembly
that it was time for them to get back to their studies.
   ``I said I didn't want to see anyone leaving school without
their books today, I told them if they were heading out of the
building and didn't have their books, they'd better have a good
excuse.''
   The teachers approved a pact Thursday that increases pay by 24
percent over three years, gives them greater curricula control, and
reduces outside classroom duties such as yard supervision.
   ``Things in the Los Angeles Unified School District, as far as
teachers are concerned, have changed for all time,'' proclaimed
United Teachers-Los Angeles President Wayne Johnson before the
agremeement was approved by the union's members in a voice vote at
the Sports Arena.
   Teachers lost on the issue of recovering pay that had been
docked because of job actions that preceded their May 15 walkout.
Many teachers had refused to patrol school yards or work on grading
after school.
   Board members also approved the pact, reached by negotiators at
1 a.m. Thursday.
   ``I look forward to healing, not only on the board but in the
district as a whole,'' said board President Roberta Weintraub.
   One board member, Rita Walters, criticized the $600 million
salary plan as a drain on other parts of the budget.
   ``There is money being taken away from the children by the
district, from other workers in our district in order to support
the teacher raise. I think that's unconscionable,'' she said.
   The teachers carved out a site-management program under which
they share power with parents and administrators in overseeing
curriculum and discipline.
   The union represents 22,000 of the Los Angeles Unified School
District's 32,000 teachers, counselors and librarians.
   Salaries under a contract that expired in July 1988 range
between $23,440 and $43,319 a year, depending on experience and
education. The pact raises salaries in the first year to between
$25,316 and $46,594 and at the end of three years to between
$29,529 and $53,938.
   Teachers will receive a retroactive pay raise for the past
school year, during which they worked without a contract.
   The district, the second largest in the nation after New York,
brought in substitutes when teachers walked out. But attendance
plummeted and classes became mostly baby-sitting sessions.
</TEXT>
