<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador 1stLd-Writethru a0467 05-26 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0467,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leftist Groups Searched After Heavy Combat in San Salvador</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with with searches of leftist groups.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers and police officers
today searched the offices of several leftist unions, human rights
groups and farming cooperatives after the heaviest combat in the
capital in years.
   The U.S.-backed government and armed forces consider the leftist
organizations fronts for Marxist-led guerrillas waging a 9-year-old
revolutionary war.
   Troops from the 1st army brigade, the National Police and the
Treasury Police surrounded the headquarters of the labor
organizations UNTS, Fenastras and FUS. The offices of COACES, a
group representing cooperative farming enterprises, CRIPDES, a
refugees organization, and the non-governmental human rights
commission also were surrounded and searched.
   Troops and police had searched at least three of the
organizations by mid-morning, but there was no immediate word on
whether arrests were made or what was found inside.
   The UNTS labor organization reported in paid radio announcements
that two members of its directorate were arrested.
   Security forces prevented journalists and other interested
parties from approaching the buildings. No one was allowed to enter
or leave the buildings.
   The searches came several hours after leftist guerrillas
attacked parts of the capital a week before a rightist party takes
power. Authorities said six guerrillas were killed Thursday night.
Five members of the National Police, one army soldier and three
civilians were wounded, officials said.
   Col. Orlando Zepeda, commander of the capital-based 1st army
brigade, told journalists the leftist groups harbored guerrillas
who took part in an attack on his brigade Thursday evening.
   Combat raged through much of northern San Salvador, near the
brigade headquarters and three other police and military posts.
   Rebels of the Faribundo Marti National Liberation Frontr dubbed
the offensive ``All Against Arena. We're going to win.''
   Arena is the Spanish acronym of for Republican Nationalist
Alliance, the rightist party that is to take power June 1.
   The guerrillas have pledged ``to make the country ungovernable''
by stepping up attacks in the days leading up to the inauguration
of President-elect Alfredo Cristiani, who is to take office from
centrist Jose Napoleon Duarte, a Christian Democrat.
   Col. Zepeda said about 30 insurgents took part in the attack
Thursday evening, including four men aboard a jeep who fired
U.S.-made M-79 grenades and Soviet-made RPG-18 rocket-propelled
grenades at the brigade headquarters.
   At least six projectiles landed inside the base perimeter and
caused property damage but no casualties, Zepeda said.
   ``We knew the level of violence had to increase. We're ready to
repel anything they try to do,'' he told reporters at brigade
headquarters.
   Thursday's fighting began about 6 p.m. and lasted about 80
minutes.
   About 7,000 Marxist-led guerrillas have been waging trying to
topple the government. The war has killed about 70,000 people, most
of them civilians.
</TEXT>
