<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Vietnam-Schools     05-26 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Vietnam-Schools,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Third of Children Cannot Afford School in Vietnamese City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A third of the children in Vietnam's
southern commercial center, Ho Chi Minh City, can't afford to go to
school, the Vietnam News Agency reported Friday.
   City resources are being severely strained by ``an alarming
population explosion'' of 70,000 more mouths to feed each year, the
official agency said.
   ``Every year, about 150,000 adults reaching the working age
cannot find a job. This does not include 29,000 people who stay at
home as housewives,'' it said. ``Thirty-seven percent of the
children at school age cannot afford schooling and this is one of
the many reasons for the rise in the crime rate.''
   The city of 5 million people hoped to lower the annual
population growth rate to one percent by 1990, the report said.
   ``This is no easy target because the feudalist tendency to view
happiness as synonymous with having many children still prevails
among large sections, especially peasants,'' it said.
   Under the city's family planning program, couples who have no
more than two children get preferential treatment in housing,
wages, and tourist trips, the report said.
</TEXT>
