<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 1247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Heir     05-26 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Heir,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Being No. 2 in China is a Losing Proposition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The apparent demise of Communist Party chief Zhao
Ziyang has proven again that heirs to power in China often end up
on the fast track to oblivion.
   As head of the 47 million-member ruling party, Zhao was in line
to succeed Deng Xiaoping as China's untitled but undisputed leader.
Many had predicted that Deng, 84, would retire by the end of the
year.
   Sources now say Zhao has been stripped of his post after
crossing with Deng over the handling of the pro-democracy student
uprising. Zhao was sympathetic with its goals and sought
compromise; Deng demanded a crackdown and declared martial law in
Beijing.
   Zhao is hardly the first to be raised up, only to be slapped
down by an autocratic ruler.
   The most recent was Zhao's predecessor, Hu Yaobang, who was
forced to resign in similar circumstances in January 1987.
   Hu also was Deng's unofficially designated successor until
student demonstrations in December 1986 kindled a battle between
party hardliners and moderates. Deng, an economic reformer with
conservative views on political reform, moved to stamp out
``bourgeois liberalization,'' or favoring Western ideas.
   Hu was ousted for being too soft on the students, and it was his
death April 15 that triggered the recent, bigger unrest.
   The most tragic case of a deposed No. 2 was that of Liu Shaoqi,
one of Mao Tse-tung's earliest supporters. By the 1950s he was
Mao's second-in-command, and in 1959 became head of state.
   But Mao turned on Liu during the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution,
branding him a traitor. Liu and his wife were personally humiliated
in Red Guard struggles, and he is believed to have died in prison
in 1969.
   Liu's downfall in the Cultural Revolution was paralleled by the
rise of Defense Minister Lin Biao. A party congress in 1969
formally named Lin vice chairman and designated him as Mao's
successor.
   But Lin plotted to assassinate Mao in 1971 so he could seize
power before rivals could mount a challenge to his position.
According to official accounts, his conspiracy was uncovered and he
was killed in a plane crash while trying to flee to the Soviet
Union.
   Mao's next designated heir, Hua Guofeng, did make it to the top,
but his stay was short-lived. In 1976, backed by Mao's reported
deathbed comment ``with you in charge, I'm at ease,'' Hua arrested
the leftist ``Gang of Four'' led by Mao's wife and assumed
leadership of the party and government.
   But Hua, who spent most of his career in the provinces, was no
match for Deng, who was purged during the Cultural Revolution but
came back after the decade of chaos to steadily gain supporters for
his new pragmatic policies.
   By 1978, Deng was in charge and Hua was heading to the
sidelines. Today he is a little-seen and much-ignored party cadre.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890526-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 1247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Laos-US     05-26 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Laos-US,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tropical Storm Delays MIA Search in Laos</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. military officials searching for
bodies of American servicemen missing in Laos since the Vietnam War
were forced to return to Bangkok on Friday because of tropical
storm Cecil, a U.S. diplomat said.
   The 15-man team will remain in Bangkok until weather conditions
around the excavation site improve before going back to begin
excavation a crash site in southern Laos, said U.S. Embassy
spokesman Ross E. Petzing.
   Petzing said the group of experts from the Joint Casualty
Resolution Center and the army Central Identification Laboratory,
both in Hawaii, arrived in Savannakhet Province on Friday, but they
couldn't fly to the site because of the storm.
   The storm lashed the coast of central Vietnam of Thursday,
destroying houses and sinking boats, the Vietnam News Agency
reported. It flooded tens of thousands of acres of rice nearing
harvest, the report said.
   The planned excavation would be the sixth joint project between
the United States and Laos since the war. Previous digs have
resulted in the recovery of remains of U.S. servicemen.
   The United States says 2,360 Americans are missing in Indochina,
with 545 of them missing in Laos.
</TEXT>
