<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Zimbabwe-Kenya     05-26 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Zimbabwe-Kenya,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilgrim Families to Return to Zimbabwe in Reverse Exodus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kenya will send home hundreds of
Zimbabweans who settled in the east African nation while on aborted
pilgrimages to Jerusalem generations ago, it was reported Thursday.
   The Harare and Nairobi governments have agreed to work together
to ensure a ``planned and orderly'' exodus, Zimbabwe Foreign
Affairs Minister Nathan Shamuyarira told the Zimbabwe Inter-African
News Agency.
   About 400 black families of the Apostolic Faith, a church
founded in Zimbabwe in 1929, traveled north in the 1940s and 1950s
in the hope of reaching Jerusalem. Most abandoned the pilgrimage
when they reached Kenya, mainly because they were short of money.
   Many of the men of the church now hold key posts in commerce,
industry and agriculture.
   The repatriation is part of a Kenyan exercise to send home
illegal aliens, African diplomatic sources told The Associated
Press.
   About 300 foreign Africans, including Zimbabweans, were ordered
to go home by a Nairobi court this week.
   Several families of the Apostolic Faith recently returned to
Zimbabwe voluntarily, Shamuyarira said.
