<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 1253EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Heart-Rescue     05-26 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Heart-Rescue,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors Save Man's Life By Using Fingers To Plug Bullet Holes in
Heart</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOLIET, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man with two bullet wounds in his heart
was saved by doctors who plugged the holes with their fingers until
he could be transferred to a hospital with the needed equipment.
   The gunshot victim, Tommy Lee Hairston of Joliet, underwent open
heart surgery at Loyola University Medical Center in Maywood on
Thursday after doctors kept him alive during the helicopter flight
from Joliet, 25 miles away.
   Hairston, 29, was listed in critical condition this morning, but
is expected to recover, said nursing surpervisor Linda Krzemienski.
A neighbor who had a dispute with Hairston was charged with
attempted murder.
   Dr. Robert Freeark, chief of surgery at Loyola, said doctors
have had to use their fingers to plug wounds in the heart before,
but he had never heard of a patient being kept alive for such a
distance under such circumstances.
   ``To my knowledge, no one has ever transferred a patient by any
means _ ambulance or certainly helicopter _ from one hospital to
another while a surgeon had a finger occluding (blocking) a hole in
the heart,'' Freeark said.
   Dr. Wendy Marshall, a trauma surgeon and director of Loyola's
trauma center, was awakened at 5 a.m. Thursday by an urgent call
from doctors at Silver Cross Hospital in Joliet.
   They said they were using nothing but their fingers to plug two
bullet holes in Hairson's heart and ``couldn't couldn't stop the
bleeding,'' Ms. Marshall recounted.
   She took a medical helicopter to Joliet, where she used her own
fingers to plug the holes as the victim was flown back to Maywood.
Three times, when the man's heart stopped, she squeezed it to get
it going again.
   ``Anyone who has got a blood pressure can be saved,'' she said.
``So you go for it.''
   Hairston, a landscaper, was shot Wednesday night after an
argument with a neighbor over missing property, police said. The
neighbor, Robert Knox, was charged with attempted murder, armed
violence and unlawful use of a weapon, police said.
   Hairston was rushed to Silver Cross, where he was operated on
immediately but his heart was not opened up. However, after
surgery, Hairston started bleeding again.
   ``This time, the surgeon opened Hairston up and found two holes
in his heart,'' Freeark said.
   Because Silver Cross didn't have the proper equipment for the
open-heart surgery, Ms. Marshall was summoned and Hairston was
transferred to Loyola. By Thursday afternoon, Hairston had awakened
a few times, which is considered a positive sign, Ms. Marshall said.
</TEXT>
