<FIRST>r w AM-Sullivan-Doctors     05-26 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sullivan-Doctors,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>HHS Secretary Predicts Period of `Great Tension' in Medicine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health and Human Services Secretary Louis W.
Sullivan told medical school graduates Friday they face ``a period
of great stress and great tension in medicine.''
   He said this country ranks first in the world in per capita
expenditures for health care, with those costs currently consuming
almost 12 percent of U.S. gross national product and continuing to
rise ``at an unsustainable rate.''
   ``Yet, the United States lags far behind other industrialized
countries in some basic indicators of health status: life
expectancy, maternal mortality and an infant mortality rate of 10.4
deaths per 1,000 live births, which ranks us 19th in the world,''
Sullivan said.
   Sullivan, himself a physician and former medical dean at
Morehouse College in Atlanta, spoke at commencement ceremonies for
the George Washington University School of Medicine and Health
Sciences.
   He said ``certain segments of our population lag unconscionably
in health status and in access to health care,'' namely blacks,
Hispanics, native Americans, rural people and inner-city residents.
   ``In fact, parts of cities and some counties in our country have
health indices no better than those of Third World countries,'' he
said.
   Sullivan urged the medical school graduates to become ``21st
century renaissance health professionals'' who are not only
technically competent but sensitive to a broad range of issues
involving health care across the United States and around the globe.
</TEXT>
