<HEAD>Israeli, Syrian Jets Fly Over; Reports of Syrian Reinforcements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli and Syrian warplanes patrolled
the sky Friday, and reports circulated that Syria was holding
maneuvers and sending reinforcements for its battle with Lebanese
Christians.
   Syrian troops and Gen. Michel Aoun's Christian army units fired
machine guns and rocket-propelled grenades across Beirut's
sectarian dividing line for two hours. Police said no casualties
were reported.
   An Arab League summit in Morocco, agreed to call for Syrian
withdrawal from Lebanon, then dropped the demand. Syria has 40,000
soldiers in the country under a peacekeeping mandate granted by the
league in 1976, when the Lebanese civil war was a year old.
   An explosion was reported in the densely populated Abu Samra
neighborhood of Tripoli, a Syrian-controlled port about 35 miles
north of Beirut, the Lebanese Red Cross said. The cause was not
known immediately.
   ``It started a fire, but no details are available because
telephone contacts with Tripoli are down,'' a Red Cross spokesman
said.
   The U.S. Embassy denied a report by the daily Al-Anwar,
published in Christian east Beirut, that Aoun's Christian cabinet
had expelled Charge d'Affaires Daniel Simpson for policies
``hostile'' to Lebanon.
   An embassy spokesman, who would not let his name be used, said
Simpson ``was asked by the American government to go back to
Washington as a routine measure. He left yesterday.''
   Al-Anwar said Simpson was told ``to leave Lebanon in 48 hours
because the constitutional Lebanese government considers him
persona non grata due to his hostile stands and practices.''
   Christian newspapers have accused Simpson of supporting Syria's
role in Lebanon.
   In addition to comanding the 20,000 Christians of Lebanon's
army, Aoun also leads one of the two rival governments that
resulted from a political crisis last September. Premier Salim Hoss
heads the Moslem cabinet.
   Artillery duels with Druse militiamen, soon joined by the
Syrians, began March 8, two days after Aoun's forces blockaded
illegal ports operated by Moslem militias.
   As the intensity increased, Aoun declared the fight a war of
liberation against the Syrians and said his goal was to drive them
from the country. More than 350 people have been killed and nearly
1,400 wounded, nearly all of them civilians.
   Israel radio said the Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's Cabinet
met to discuss reports that Syria had sent an armored armored
brigade and helicopter-borne commandos into Lebanon.
   In Damascus, the official Syria Times said Syrian army,
artillery, and air force units conducted mock attacks on ground
troops, but did not say where the exercise took place.
   Syrian television quoted the defense minister, Gen. Mustafa
Tlass, as saying without elaboration: ``The maneuver on a
full-stage battle against the enemy was successful.''
   A reliable source in Damascus, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said he was ``almost certain'' the maneuvers did not
take place in Lebanon.
   Both the Christians and Syrians have stockpiled weapons and
ammunition in the relative calm of a partially successful
cease-fire the Arab League called two weeks ago.
   Reports have circulated in Lebanon that the Syrians plan an
assault on the 310-square-mile enclave east of Beirut where about 1
million Christians live.
   On Thursday, the Markaziyeh newsletter published in the
Christian sector said 40 Syrian tanks and armored personnel
carriers had entered Lebanon and taken positions in mountains south
and east of Beirut that overlook the Christian enclave.
   A spokesman for Aoun's Christian army units said two Israeli
warplanes broke the sound barrier at 35,000 feet over the Chouf
mountains southeast of Beirut at noon Friday.
   The planes drew heavy anti-aircraft fire from Walid Jumblatt's
Druse militia but no hits were observed, he said.
   Earlier, four Syrian jets criss-crossed the Christian enclave
and Beirut at high altitude, flying ``from the northern border to
Beirut for more than an hour,'' the spokesman said.
</TEXT>
