<FIRST>r i AM-BushSecurity     05-26 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush Security,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tight Security in Rome for Bush's Visit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-NATO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Determined to prevent the terrorist attacks that
marred the last visit to Italy by an American president, police
adopted extraordinary security measures Friday to protect President
Bush.
   ``Rome is in a state of siege,'' said the state-run RAI
television.
   Elite Carabinieri paramilitary policemen, armed with submachine
guns and wearing bulletproof vests, guarded the U.S. Embassy on Via
Veneto, the U.S. ambassador's residence a mile away and other
American interests.
   Wary of possible car bombs, police roped off adjacent streets
into no-parking zones.
   Authorities said more than 1,000 uniformed and plainclothes
police had been deployed for security duties during Bush's
three-day visit. Sharpshooters were posted on rooftops along Bush's
motorcade route.
   Via Veneto, once synonymous with the ``Dolce Vita'' era of
nightclubs and movie stars, was lined with pairs of policemen every
few dozen feet.
   A blue police van was parked in front of the embassy gates, and
another was stationed across the street in front of the Hotel
Ambasciatori.
   The U.S. embassy sits at the heart of what is known as the
``triangle of death,'' an area whose embassies, airline offices and
popular tourist cafes have been a target of Arab terrorists. More
than a dozen attacks, killing five people, have occurred in the
area since 1979.
   On Wednesday, police explosives experts were called in to remove
a suspicious car parked across from the embassy compound. They blew
out the windows to get inside, but it turned out to be a false
alarm.
   Police vans were also parked at every corner of the Villa
Taverna, the seven-acre compound in the posh Parioli district where
U.S. Ambassador Maxwell Rabb lives. Bush will be spending Friday
and Saturday nights at the 17th century villa.
   Rabb served throughout Ronald Reagan's eight-year presidency and
had been scheduled to leave last week but extended his stay because
the Senate has not yet acted on Bush's nomination of Michigan
businessman Peter Secchia.
   The most recent anti-American terrorist attacks in Rome occurred
June 9, 1987, as President Reagan and other leaders of the world's
major industrialized nations were holding a summit meeting in
Venice.
   First, a car bomb exploded on Via Boncompagni along the side of
the U.S. Embassy compound, damaging other parked cars and blowing
out two large windows in the nearby Hotel Excelsior. Except for an
Italian woman passer-by who suffered from shock, there were no
injuries.
   Less than an hour later, two homemade rockets were fired over
the gates of the U.S. Embassy, causing minor damage but no
injuries. A similar rocket landed harmlessly in an ornamental pool
at the British Embassy, about a half-mile away.
   The rockets aimed at the U.S. Embassy were launched from the
balcony of a fifth-floor room of the Hotel Ambasciatori.
   The terrorists were never caught, but Italian authorities pieced
together descriptions of suspects and issued arrest warrants for
members of the Japanese Red Army, a Lebanese-based group sponsored
by Libya.
   The same group was blamed for the car bomb attack on a U.S.
servicemen's club in Naples in April 1988 that killed five people,
including an American woman.
   Security was also stepped up Friday at airports and train
stations. Authorities said police helicopters and restricted air
routes would be used for Bush's trips by helicopter.
   Police said the strict security measures were taken as a
precaution, not because they had received any threats or
indications of terrorist activity.
   Despite the tight security, advertisements were published in
Rome newspapers Friday inviting the public to the Memorial Day
ceremony Bush is scheduled to attend Sunday at the American World
War II cemetery in Nettuno, about 45 miles south of Rome.
</TEXT>
