<FIRST>r a PM-SpoletoFestival 1stLd-Writethru a0475 05-26 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spoleto Festival, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0475,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spoleto Festival U.S.A. to Serve Up Smorgasbord of the Arts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with festival beginning; Picks
up 3rd graf, `Chamber music ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From grand opera to chamber music,
marionettes to Mozart, the Spoleto Festival U.S.A. will serve up a
smorgasbord of the arts over the next 16 days in Charleston.
   The 13th edition of the festival, founded by composer Gian Carlo
Menotti, opened today with a ceremony on the steps of City Hall.
   ``Let the music begin, let the dancers dance, let the choirs
sing and let the children play,'' Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr.
announed in his traditional proclamation. ``I hereby declare that
the 13th Spoleto Festival U.S.A. has begun.''
   Chamber music, Bellini's opera ``La Straniera,'' and Eileen
Heckart and Joanna Gleason in the Lee Blessing play
``Eleemosynary'' were on tap for the festival's opening day.
   During the festival, 111 performances will be presented before
Spoleto closes amid a thundering fireworks display over Middleton
Place Plantation on June 11.
   Festival organizers were predicting a record box office, with
ticket sales running $127,000 ahead of last year, festival
spokeswoman Ann Wilson said Thursday. Almost $1.2 million in
tickets have been sold compared to $1.32 million sold during the
entire festival last year.
   Even before this year's festival opened, three productions were
acknowledged hits.
   Tickets for ``The Marriage of Figaro'' _ directed by Menotti _
sold out two days after the box office opened in March.
   Only a handful of tickets remain for the return engagement of
the Colla Family Marionettes. The Italian puppets were one of the
highlights of the 1987 festival.
   The Young Conductors Concert featuring little-known works by
Mozart is also a sellout.
   ``Everything else has some tickets left on certain dates,'' said
Mrs. Wilson. ``There's plenty left, especially in the final week.''
   Other major events at the festival include Laurie Anderson
premiering her newest work, titled ``Empty Places'' in which 10,000
images will be juxtaposed to music on more than a dozen moveable
screens at the Gaillard Municipal Auditorium.
   The Boston Ballet and the Trisha Brown Company will also perform
and there will be a performance of Mozart's ``Requiem.''
   Menotti started a festival in Spoleto, Italy, in 1957 with the
aim of merging the cultural worlds of Europe and America. In 1977
he took the festival to Charleston, and in 1986 he expanded the
project to Melbourne, Australia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
