<DOCNO> AP890526-0111 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 1335EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Control Bjt   05-26 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Control, Bjt,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Gears Up Time-Tested Education &amp; Control Machinery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservatives who gained control of the Communist
Party leadership in a bitter power struggle activated time-tested
education mechanisms Friday for ensuring control at the grassroots
as well.
   The television news said party members and soldiers attended
lengthy meetings to study May 19 speeches in which Premier Li Peng
and President Yang Shangkun announced troops would ``restore
order'' after more than a month of student-led protests for
democracy.
   Political study sessions have been an important element of the
party's grassroots control during 40 years of rule. Once top
leaders set a new party line, meetings routinely are called at
every level to study it, from the Central Committee down to the
local cell.
   Party members then are expected to take the lead in educating
non-members at study sessions in workplaces and mass organizations.
   In the current power struggle, the meetings will be especially
important because so many party members, security forces and
Beijing residents took part in the demonstrations now being
denounced.
   Army cadets, soldiers of the logistics department, police, the
Communist Party's Youth League and employees of government
ministries were among the marchers.
   The party, never satisfied with simply issuing an order from
above, will be trying to win over as many people as possible and
frighten the rest into silent cooperation. Party members who
shouted, ``Down with Li Peng!'' in the anonymity of a crowd of
hundreds of thousands will be unlikely to dare speak out in a small
study session of their peers.
   Chinese sources said the main texts being studied Friday were
the speeches Li and Yang made on national TV just before declaring
martial law in parts of the capital; an internal report on the
protests by Beijing's party chief; and speeches made Thursday by
Yang and former President Li Xiannian at a Politburo meeting that
voted to back the hardliners.
   Party members praised the Li and Yang speeches as ``very
important'' and said they ``represented the will of the entire
party,'' the nationally televised evening news said.
   The television also showed troops who have been ordered to
impose martial law taking part in study sessions. The troops have
been quartered on the outskirts of Beijing since last weekend when
hundreds of thousands of citizens blocked their way into the
capital.
   The ``dare-to-die units'' of citizens who blockaded the troop
trucks administered their own kind of propaganda, lecturing the
soldiers for hours on end about the student protesters' goals of
increasing democracy and wiping out corruption. They gave the
soldiers food, water and cigarettes and urged them not to hurt the
students.
   In an apparent effort to counteract the people's propaganda,
army officers lectured the troops Friday on their martial law
mission.
   The television showed soldiers sitting in small groups in their
tents, their bedrolls neatly stashed behind them, studying a harsh
letter from the top army command that claimed a small group of
people were using the students to attack the party leadership.
   Education has yet to begin in earnest in ordinary workplaces,
where most efforts so far have been directed at keeping employees
from joining demonstrations. Some employers have threatened
dismissal or fines for anyone who marches, others have tried to
bribe workers with free food and drink to stay in.
   Some large workplaces also formed worker militias, ostensibly to
help keep order on the streets but in reality to keep workers
occupied at night.
</TEXT>
