<FIRST>u a AM-ShackPeople Bjt   05-26 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shack People, Bjt,0725</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shack People Cling to Vista, Ignore Bulldozers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Finding this room with a view was no problem for
Isaac, Sarah, Linda and Hector.
   But the bulldozers? They will definitely be a problem.
   All four live in a squalid yet sophisticated cluster of shacks
on the elevated West Side Highway, overlooking the Hudson River in
Manhattan. The 15-block stretch of highway, raised on rusting
girders, has been closed since a truck fell through the decaying
roadway in 1973.
   Workers started razing the highway 11 blocks up on Thursday and
will inch their way downtown. The shack residents vow to stay until
the last moment.
   ``We've moved them a few times and they just keep returning,''
said Samuel I. Schwartz, deputy transportation commissioner. ``They
like the vista and many are attached to the setting. But there'll
come a day when they can't return.''
   Once, the highway was dotted with dozens of trash-strewn huts of
plywood, nails, carpet remnants and blue plastic tarp. Just four
remain.
   Early Thursday, a police officer rapped his nightstick on the
hut that Linda, Hector, Sarah and Isaac share. ``You've got to get
out _ we're bringing dynamite,'' said the officer.
   This, though, is their home. They tap electricity from a light
pole to run their television, cooler, lights, heater, even a vacuum
cleaner. The women, both soap opera buffs, seldom miss ``Loving''
and ``General Hospital.''
   ``It's peaceful and it's calm up here. Sometimes, sightseers
come by and take pictures. I guess they think we're all maniacs,''
Isaac said, as tourists gawked from the deck of the Intrepid, an
aircraft carrier-turned-museum.
   Isaac, who described himself as an out-of-work carpenter,
plumber and electrician, said he once shared a girlfriend's
condominium. When that fizzled out, he moved onto the highway in
November. His friends joined him last winter.
   ``I'm not homeless,'' he says emphatically. ``People who are
homeless are living on the subway; they don't change their
clothes.''
   It took Isaac a day to build his hut after scavenging ``a piece
here, a piece there _ nails, wire, tape.'' The address, he says
with a grin, is ``Bridge, Apartment 221.''
   He sometimes visits his sister's home. Once he caught himself
walking hunched over _ conditioning from his own 4-foot-high
ceiling. ``I straightened up right away. If they knew where I
lived, they'd say, `You're 36 years old and you're embarrassing the
family. Are you crazy?'''
   ``I'm from Ohio. If my mother saw me living like this, she'd
kill me,'' agreed his girlfriend Sarah, 34, an unemployed factory
worker and waitress.
   ``I always wanted to come to New York and I finally did. People
know your business too much in a little town. But the rent here is
so high _ you can rent a whole house in Ohio for $400 a month,''
she said.
   ``Now,'' said Isaac, ``they're telling us to go to the shelter.
What are we supposed to do: She goes to one shelter and I go to
another?'' he said, pointing to Sarah, who is three months pregnant.
   ``The shelters are not safe. I'm not going to a shelter. We
leave our TV and our clothes here, with no locks, and all our stuff
is still here when we get back. Try that in an apartment in the
neighborhood where you live. We look out for one another. Kids
don't come up here and go wilding.''
   Linda, who asked that her last name be withheld because ``I have
kids in college and it would be embarrassing for them,'' said the
hut-dwellers were ``like one big, happy family. On the street, a
guy slammed me up against a wall and put a knife up to me. That's
never happened up here.''
   Sam, another hut dweller, makes money gathering cans and scrap
metal.
   ``Whatever we have, we share,'' he said. ``And the view is nice.
I've got my Intrepid right here. I've got my view of the skyline.
My boats, they come in and out. This is the best.''
   When the dozers arrive, Sam may search for a vacant lot.
   ``I don't know exactly what I'm going to do,'' he said. ``But
I'll be here until the bitter end.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
