<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 1421EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Ethiopia     05-26 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethiopia,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethiopian Leader Names New Armed Forces Chiefs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABEBE ANDUALEM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mengistu Haile Mariam has
named new armed forces commanders to replace those killed last week
in an abortive coup led by war-weary generals, Addis Ababa radio
announced.
   Mengistu also named new navy and police chiefs, but made no
mention of the fate of the former navy commander and police chief.
The appointments were made Wednesday.
   Diplomats say nearly the entire military high command was killed
in the three-day revolt crushed May 18 and subsequent purge in this
strategic nation that is the Soviet Union's strongest ally in
Africa.
   The new appointees will command the continent's largest and
best-equipped force of 325,000 troops, although many are unwilling
conscripts.
   All but two of the new military leaders are central committee
members of the Marxist Workers Party of Ethiopia, this Horn of
Africa nation's sole legal political party.
   Lt. Gen. Addis Tedla, the deputy prime minister and a Politburo
member, is the new chief of staff.
   Other appointees with their new titles are Maj. Gen. Seyoum
Mekonen and Maj. Gen. Mesfin Gebre Kal, deputy chiefs of staff; and
Maj. Gen. Embibel Ayele, commander of ground forces.
   Brig. Gen. Alemayehu Agonafir becomes air force commander while
Yfhuwal Ashet Girma was named navy commander with the rank of rear
admiral.
   Berhanu Jembere, a former ambassador to East Germany who has had
charge of the government agency dealing with drought and other
disasters, takes command of the 1st Army with the rank of major
general.
   Other appointments are: Maj. Gen. Gimar Neway, to head the
police; Maj. Gen. Wubishet Dessie, 2nd Army commander; and Brig.
Gen. Gebre Giorgis Berhanu, 2nd Army deputy commander and its
political commissar.
   No one was named defense minister to replace Maj. Gen. Haile
Giorgis Habte Mariam, who was killed by rebellious generals when he
tried to halt their coup attempt.
   The government made no mention of casualties in the mutiny.
   Initially it was announced that loyal troops killed three
generals: Maj. Gen. Merid Negussie, then chief of staff; Maj. Gen.
Amha Desta, air force commander; and Maj. Gen. Denissie Bulto, 2nd
Army commander. But Mengistu told a rally last week that the three
committed suicide rather than surrender.
   Mengistu has blamed the three dead generals for military defeats
in northern Eritrea and Tigre provinces, where it is fighting
rebels who want more power for their ethnic minorities.
   The Eritrean People's Liberation Front, waging a 28-year war for
secession, and the Tigrean People's Liberation Front, which seeks
more autonomy, recently have scored major victories and chased
government troops from most of the countryside and small towns.
   Many troops in the 150,000-strong 2nd Army, which has done most
of the fighting and has its headquarters in the Eritrean capital of
Asmara, backed the coup.
</TEXT>
