<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--RaccoonIndictment     05-26 0113</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Raccoon Indictment,0116</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indictment Charges Raccoons Shipped for Dog Training</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man has been accused of illegally
trying to ship 150 wild raccoons into Georgia to train hunting dogs.
   John Braswell, 44, of Okeechobee, was charged Thursday by a
federal grand jury with conspiracy and attempted interstate
transportation of the animals. An arrest warrant was issued.
   ``These are what you call unique cases that come through the
office from time to time, some of our less-used statutes,'' said
Curtis Fallgatter, the managing assistant U.S. attorney in
Jacksonville.
   Braswell was stopped with a pickup truck full of raccoons,
authorities said.
   Fallgatter said raccoons can carry rabies and parvo virus.
</TEXT>
