<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Lebanon     05-26 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Lebanon,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Watches Syrian Buildup, See No Immediate Threat</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli officials are keeping a close watch on
the Syrian military buildup in Lebanon but said Friday they see no
immediate danger to their northern border.
   The Cabinet met Thursday night about reports that a mechanized
brigade had joined the 40,000 Syrian soldiers already in Lebanon,
where a Syrian-Druse alliance has been been fighting Christian army
soldiers since early March.
   Most officials and observers said Syria's objective seemed to be
convincing the Arab summit in Morocco it would not leave Lebanon
rather than posing a threat to Israel.
   ``As long as we don't feel directly threatened, there is no way
Israel is going to intervene,'' said Foreign Ministry spokesman
Alon Liel.
   Col. Renaan Gissin, deputy army spokesman, said: ``Clearly any
change of forces on the ground is a concern to us. We are watching
to see if this presents any threat to Israel's northern border or
the security zone.''
   That zone is a strip of Lebanese territory just north of the
border, varying in depth from six to 10 miles, patrolled by Israeli
soldiers and a mainly Christian surrogate militia called the South
Lebanon Army.
   Military sources said privately the army had not raised the
alert status of its border units.
   Concern about a Syrian move southward or an expansion of the
Syrian-Christian fight in Lebanon was evident, however.
   ``Any war on our northern border is not good because of the
potential to spill over,'' a government official said, on condition
of anomyity.
   Zeev Eitan, an analyst at Tel Aviv University's Jaffee Center
for Strategic Studies, said Israeli reconnaissance flights could be
hampered if Syria moved anti-aircraft missiles into new areas of
Lebanon.
   Ron Ben-Ishai, military correspondent of the independent daily
Yediot Ahronot, noted that military actions sometimes go beyond the
planned scope and said on army radio: ``it's known that in the
Middle East, often without intention, things can escalate.''
</TEXT>
