<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 2049EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--DeadAir     05-26 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Dead Air,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radio Stations Use Silence to Deliver Message</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighty percent of the nation's commercial radio
stations gave their listeners dead air for 30 seconds Friday as a
taste of what it would mean not to have radio.
   The period of silence opened a $100 million national advertising
campaign, ``Radio: What Would Life be Like Without It.''
   ``Imagine if all your days sounded like this,'' the recorded
voice of actor James Earl Jones said at 7:42 a.m. EST. Then nothing
until Jones came on again saying: ``Thirty seconds seems like a
long time, doesn't it? Now think how radio fills that silence for
you.''
   The Radio Advertising Bureau, which said about 8,000 stations
participated, called the spot the biggest simultaneous promotion in
the history of radio.
   Over the next year the campaign will produce other broadcast
commercials as well as magazine and newspaper ads to attract
potential advertisers, said Daniel Flamberg, the bureau vice
president.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
