<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 1451EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     05-26 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>14 Blacks Sentenced to Death For Mob Killing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Friday sentenced 14
blacks to hang for the mob killing of a black policeman, in a
ruling likely to stir widespread protest.
   Only one of the group of 13 men and a 60-year-old woman was
found to have inflicted blows that caused the death of Lucas
Sethwala. He was stoned and set afire Nov. 13, 1985, because of his
work for South Africa's racist government.
   ``The Upington trial is an outrage that only the apartheid
system can produce,'' protested the South African Council of
Churches, which includes most of the country's leading Protestant
denominations.
   ``We cannot be convinced that justice has been done,'' it said.
   The Lawyers for Human Rights organization said the 14 are the
largest group ever condemned to death for a single crime in South
Africa.
   Altogether, 25 blacks have been convicted of murder in the
killing that took place at Paballelo black township outside
Upington, a remote northwestern city.
   Eleven remaining defendants are expected to be sentenced to
prison terms. On Friday, the 14 defendants sang an African hymn as
they marched into Upington courthouse, knowing they would get death
sentences because the judge ruled Thursday there was no excuse for
their actions.
   The death sentence is mandatory for people convicted of murder
in South Africa unless the judge finds mitigating circumstances.
   Most of those sentenced Friday proclaimed their innocence before
Supreme Court Judge Jan Basson.
   ``I am an elderly woman and have been found guilty for something
I have not done,'' said Evelina de Bruin. ``Other people committed
this crime.''
   Justice Bekebeke, the only defendant found to have inflicted
blows in the killing, did not maintain his innocence. But the
24-year-old told the court the case was ``based on racial
prejudice.''
   Lawyer Andy Durbach said the sentences will be appealed.
   The so-called Upington 25 were convicted in April 1988 under the
principle of common purpose, which holds a person responsible for
crowd actions if they were part of the group.
   The day of the killing, about 3,000 blacks gathered on a soccer
field to protest rent increases.
   Police dispersed the crowd, and most went home peacefully except
for about 300 who regrouped and attacked Sethwala.
   Prosecutors said the Upington 25 were in the crowd that pelted
Sethwala's house with stones. Sethwala fired a gun out the window,
wounding a small boy. Defense lawyers said this incited the crowd
to force the victim from his house, assault him and set him ablaze.
   The judge said the killing was politically motivated, part of a
conspiracy to attack authorities.
   Basson rejected arguments that individual defendants cannot be
held accountable for actions of a crowd. One of those convicted was
described by witnesses as a close friend of the victim.
   The principle of common purpose also was used against the
``Sharpeville Six,'' a group of black men and women convicted of
slaying a black town councilor. After an international campaign,
President P.W. Botha last year commuted their death sentences to
lengthy prison terms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
