<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Judge     05-26 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa-Judge,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Who Condemned Racist Killer Reportedly Gets Police Guard</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge who sentenced a
white racist to hang for killing seven blacks and an Indian man is
under police protection for fear of revenge attacks, newspapers
reported Friday.
   Police headquarters refused to confirm or deny reports that
Pretoria Supreme Court Justice Louis Harms, two assistants and two
prosecutors are under protective surveillance since Thursday's
sentencing of Barend Strydom.
   Strydom, 23, was convicted of killing seven people and wounding
15 blacks in a shooting spree in Pretoria on Nov. 15.
   ``There is concern that right-wing political agitators may
attack the judge and his associates,'' The Star newspaper said.
   The black taxi driver who disarmed Strydom said Friday he may
flee the area because of harassment by white extremists. Simon
Mkondeleli, 33, took refuge in a newspaper office Thursday when he
was chased by several whites after the sentencing.
   Strydom, a former policeman, belonged to the Afrikaner
Resistance Movement which seeks to establish a whites-only state.
He testified during his trial that he believes blacks are subhuman
and he wanted his attack to provoke a ``war of freedom'' to ensure
white dominance.
   The extreme Boerestaat Party has described Strydom as ``a
sensitive Afrikaner patriot'' and is campaigning for his clemency.
   In editorials Friday, pro-government newspapers said Strydom's
fanaticism is not unique.
   ``It was not just one misguided and confused young man,'' said
Beeld, the largest Afrikaans-language daily. ``The offensive
opinions of a fanatical minority were heard and found guilty.
   ``The fact that Strydom is hailed as a hero in these circles
leaves no doubt as to the viciousness of the right's sickness.''
   A more liberal newspaper, The Argus of Cape Town, said the
government's racist policies are partly to blame for Strydom's
views. It described him as ``a Frankenstein monster, lurching out
of a dark and bitter past.''
   In a separate case, the Justice Department confirmed Friday that
it has reprieved Henry Burt, a white facing execution for murdering
a black policeman. His sentence was commuted to 20 years in prison.
   Burt was convicted in 1987 of killing Sgt. Jacob Ndimande and
trying to make it appear black radicals had committed the crime by
using the ``necklace'' method. Numerous suspected government
collaborators were executed in 1984-86 by ``necklacing,'' in which
a gasoline-soaked tire is placed around a victim's neck and set
alight.
</TEXT>
