<DOCNO> AP890526-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 1539EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Yang     05-26 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Yang,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yang Shangkun Emerges as Key Player in Power Struggle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yang Shangkun, an elderly general and China's
ceremonial head of state, has emerged as a major player in the
struggle for control of the government.
   Yang, 81, has been a leading spokesman for the hardline policy
of imposing martial law on Beijing and crushing the student
uprising.
   Yang, on the night of May 19, appeared on national TV with
Premier Li Peng to announce that troops would be brought in to
restore order to the capital.
   Chinese sources said Yang also delivered a speech to party and
government leaders on Thursday that strongly condemned Communist
Party General Secretary Zhao Ziyang for being sympathetic to the
student cause.
   Zhao, one of China's leading reformers, has been stripped of his
post in connection with the recent disturbances, sources say.
   Students occupying Tiananmen Square have reacted in anger to
Yang's statements, demanding that he, along with Li and Deng, step
down.
   Yang, a jovial man who is quick to smile, seems out of place in
the role of the iron-fisted disciplinarian.
   Because of his long association with senior leader Deng Xiaoping
and his public statements, he has been regarded as a solid
supporter of economic reforms and China's opening to the world.
   When he became president, or head of state, in April 1988, he
spoke of the ``longing of the people of all our nationalities for a
dramatic change in the face of the country.''
   Yang, as ranking military man in the Central Military Commission
headed by Deng, has also worked closely with Deng to bring about
reform in China's oversized, technically backward army.
   He helped direct the 1985-87 effort to reduce the size of the
People's Liberation Army from 4.2 million to about 3.2 million
people, and led the campaign to abandon Mao's concept of a
revolutionary guerrilla force in favor of a modern, well-equipped
army.
   But like Deng, Yang suffered during the turmoil of the 1966-76
Cultural Revolution, and apparently shares his aversion to social
instability. When the student movement swelled beyond control, Yang
joined Deng and the forces of law and order.
   Yang, born in 1907 in Deng's home province of Sichuan, studied
for four years in the Soviet Union before returning to join the Red
Army in the Long March, the epic 1934-35 flight from Chiang
Kai-shek's pursuing Nationalist forces.
   Always an administrator rather than a military strategist, he
became secretary-general of the party's military commission in
1945. After the communist victory in 1949, he was given the key
administrative post of director of the general office of the party
Central Committee, a post he held until the Cultural Revolution
began in 1966.
   Imprisoned during the Cultural Revolution, he returned to become
deputy governor of Guangdong province in southern China in 1978,
and in 1981 rose to permanent vice chairman of the Central Military
Commission. The next year he gained a seat on the party Politburo.
   As president, his main function is to officially welcome
visiting dignitaries, and he has made a quick transition from
uniform to Western suit. But the current crisis has also shown the
personable president to be a hard military man ready to back his
superior Deng when duty calls.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
