<FIRST>u i PM-Britain-Czechs     05-26 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Czechs,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechoslovakia Expels 4 Britons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovakia today expelled three British
diplomats and a businessman in what the Foreign Office called an
unjustified retaliation for the recent expulsion of four
Czechoslovaks from Britain.
   A Foreign Office spokesman said Czechoslovak authorities told
the British ambassador to Prague, Laurence O'Keefe, the four
Britons must leave in two weeks because of ``unacceptable
activities,'' diplomatic jargon for spying.
   ``It's clearly an unjustified action,'' said the spokesman,
speaking anonymously in keeping with British custom. ``It's clearly
in retaliation.''
   He identified the four Britons as the embassy's First Secretary
of Administration Tony Arnold, First Secretary Counsellor Rick
Todd, Third Secretary Patricia Holland and a manager of Shell Oil,
Nick Brooks.
   Earlier today, the Czechoslovak Communist Party daily, Rude
Pravo, called the expulsion of its diplomats another case of
``British spymania, which certain British circles bring about from
time to time.''
   On May 19, Britain expelled eight Soviet diplomats and three
journalists and Moscow retaliated in kind a day later.
   The Soviets then demanded that Britain reduce to 205 the number
of Britons and their locally hired support staff in the Soviet
Union in order to match the quota of Soviets allowed in Britain.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher told the House of Commons on
Thursday that the expulsions of the Soviets and the Czechoslovaks
were vital ``regardless of the effect upon our relations.'' Before
the expulsions, Britain had been enjoying its best relations with
the Soviet Union since World War II.
   Britain also had been improving relations with Czechoslovakia,
partly because British authorities want help in detecting the
Czechoslovak-made explosive Semtex used by the Irish Republican
Army and other terrorist groups.
   Sir John Fretwell, Foreign Office politcal director, said
Czechoslovakia had ignored warnings to rein in its diplomats in
September 1988, when three others were expelled.
</TEXT>
