<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 1539EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan-Iran     05-26 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-Iran,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Say Iran and Afghanistan Making Progress Toward Peace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governments of Afghanistan and
Iran have made progress toward ending the fighting between Afghan
troops and Moslem guerrillas based in Iran, officials said Friday.
   ``Iran is becoming increasingly important. They oppose a
military solution,'' said one Afghan government official closely
involved in the negotiations.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Iran was
considering telling the guerrillas based there to make a deal with
Afghan President Najib and the Soviet Union, which supports Najib.
   He said Tehran is eager to begin repatriating an estimated 2
million Afghans who have sought exile in Iran during the
11-year-old war between Afghan forces and Moslem guerrillas.
   In addition, he said, Iran wants to establish closer ties with
the Kremlin.
   The guerrillas are split into factions based in both Pakistan
and Iran.
   The Tehran-based eight-party alliance represents the Shiite
Moslem minority of Afghanistan. It is at odds with the
Pakistan-based alliance of Sunni Moslems.
   ``Tehran has been making overtures to the Soviet Union and to
our government,'' said a close adviser to the Afghan president. The
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, refused to elaborate
on the talks.
   Soviet Ambassador Yuli Vorontsov held talks with the resistance
coalition during a four-day visit to Tehran recently.
   Senior Soviet diplomats in Kabul said Vorontsov called the talks
very good.
   The meetings were his first since the Soviet Union pulled the
last of its troops from Afghanistan on Feb. 15, ending a nine-year
military involvment.
   The Soviet officials said Vorontsov said the rebels opposed
foreign interference and wanted an Afghan government composed of
all groups. The Soviets have said they also want this.
   This week, Pakistani Foreign Minister Sahabzada Yaqub suggested
Moscow also resume talks with Afghan rebels in Pakistan.
   Moscow made contact with Afghan rebels based in Pakistan in
December, but the U.S.-backed guerrillas said they would not talk
to the Soviets until Moscow stopped aiding the Kabul government.
</TEXT>
