<FIRST>r i AM-China-Zhao     05-26 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Zhao,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zhao Advocated Both Economic and Political Reform</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zhao Ziyang wanted economic and political reform
to go hand-in-hand, but conservatives were determined to keep their
power and crush a student movement for democracy.
   Sources said Friday that Premier Li Peng and the old guard won
and Zhao lost his post as head of the 47 million-member Communist
Party, which had made him the most powerful man in China after
senior leader Deng Xiaoping.
   They said Zhao, 69, was under house arrest, accused of
encouraging student unrest by being conciliatory.
   Although Deng is Zhao's mentor in economic reforms, the two
differ on political reform. Zhao's sympathy for the students
apparently was unacceptable.
   Just two years ago, Deng dismissed another party chief for being
too sympathetic to pro-democracy students.
   Hu Yaobang was forced to resign in January 1987 after
accusations that he was soft on students seeking a freer China.
Hu's death April 15 inspired the current student movement, which
has a far grander scale.
   Zhao had been premier for seven years when he took over the
party in November 1987. He also was appointed first vice chairman
of the Central Military Commission, of which Deng is chairman.
   He became the target of criticism a year ago when the
government, faced with annual inflation of more than more than 30
percent and panic buying as a result, began worrying that it had
lost control of the economy.
   Li and other conservatives blamed the rapid pace of
market-oriented reforms associated with Zhao. They imposed a
two-year austerity program and postponed more reform.
   This spring, the renewed student unrest made Zhao's position
even more tenuous.
   While tens of thousands of students occupied Tiananmen Square
earlier this month, he told President Mikhail S. Gorbachev of the
Soviet Union political and economic reform should proceed together
and China should enjoy ``genuine democracy'' under the Communist
Party.
   He later expressed sympathy with the students demanding
democratic reforms and advocated negotiations to end the crisis. He
met with them in Tiananmen Square before martial law was imposed.
   Deng has permitted only token political liberalization and was
said to have given the order a week ago for martial law to be
declared in Beijing.
   Zhao has been a role model for the new-style Chinese leader. He
is suave and articulate, at ease in both the communist world and
the West. He wears immaculately tailored Western suits and
regularly plays golf, a sport once condemned in China as a
bourgeois luxury.
   He was born in October 1919 to a landowning family in central
China's Henan province, joined the Communist Party in 1938 and led
its committee in his native county during most of the 1937-45 war
with Japan.
   Unlike the previous generation of party leaders, he did not make
the Long March, the 7,700-mile trek northwest in 1934-35 to escape
the Nationalist government troops in eastern China.
   After the communist victory in 1949, Zhao served in regional
government and party posts. He was purged during the radical
Cultural Revolution of 1966-76, as was Deng, but was rehabilitated
long before it ended.
   Zhao gained national prominence as party secretary and governor
of Deng's home province, Sichuan, where he carried out the senior
leader's policies of dismantling farm communes and allowing private
plots and bonuses for extra work.
</TEXT>
