<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Protest     05-26 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Protest,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundrds Defy Ban on Unauthorized Meetings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several hundred Soviets defied a ban on
unauthorized meetings Friday and gathered in a downtown square to
criticize their new parliament hours after it defeated reformers'
attempts to sanction their gathering.
   Police with megaphones urged the crowd to disperse or go to an
approved meeting place in a giant parking lot away from the city
center, but only a handful showed up at the officially approved
meeting place.
   Authorities took no immediate action to break up the gathering
in Moscow's Pushkin Square, a frequent gathering spot for political
discussions and protests.
   ``The apparatus is still controlling everything,'' said one man
who identified himself only as a taxi driver as he discussed the
action at the Congress of People's Deputies. ``Everything is the
same as always.''
   ``You can compare the congress to an old cake,'' chimed in
another. ``They sprinkle some chocolate on the top, some democracy,
but at the bottom it's stale.''
   ``The only victory was that they managed to have some
discussion,'' said Alexander Khatov in a typical comment about
reformers at the Congress of People's Deputies convened Thursday.
   A anonymous leaflet distributed in the square said, ``A few
deputies truly elected by the people are trying to defend what has
been promised ... but everything is being done according to a
previously worked out scenario, just as it always was.
   ``What are we, the people, doing at this moment, which could
become the turning point in our history of slavery? We, the people,
are doing what we've been doing since 1917. We're looking for food
_ and now soap as well.''
   Friday's meeting followed police action to break up a similar
gathering called late Thursday by the Democratic Union, a
self-styled opposition group.
   The use of special anti-riot forces to disperse the crowd
triggered a heated quarrel Friday in the congress, where prominent
reformer Tatyana Zaslavskaya urged the parliament to ask Moscow
city authorities to lift their ban on unsanctioned political
meetings for the duration of the session.
   At the direction of President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who chaired
the televised proceedings, Interior Minister Vadim Bakatin said
meetings discussing actions at the congress had taken place without
incident across the Soviet Union. The Moscow meeting was different,
he said, because it had been banned in advance by the authorities.
   The top police official's statement touched off a furor on the
congress floor. Some deputies shouted at one another, while others,
from conservative Central Asia, applauded to drown out speeches by
liberal Moscow deputies Sergei Stankevich and Andrei D. Sakharov.
   Sakharov, 68, said that despite exhaustion from 13 hours of
congress proceedings Thursday, he went to the square after being
called at home by a weeping girl. He urged his fellow deputies to
meet with the young activists after each day of Congress debate.
   ``We must not surround these people with police units,'' he
said, recalling events in the Georgian capital of Tbilisi last
month, where at least 20 people died after security forces moved
against a pro-independence protest.
   Gorbachev stopped the debate by putting Zaslavskaya's call to a
vote.
   Her proposal was defeated, with 831 deputies supporting her,
1,261 against and 30 abstaining.
   Before the results were announced, Gorbachev said he had
received word from Moscow Communist Party boss Lev N. Zaikov that
city authorities would sanction a voters' meeting in Moscow _ but
in the stadium parking lot well away from Pushkin Square.
</TEXT>
