<FIRST>r a AM-VegasGasoline     05-26 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vegas Gasoline,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suppliers Say Gas Available Despite Pipeline Blast</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pipeline Explosion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suppliers promised plenty of gasoline for local
drivers and the thousands of tourists expected over the holiday
weekend, despite the loss of a pipeline providing 90 percent of the
city's supply.
   But industry officials warned that the situation could change if
motorists succumbed to panic buying in the wake of Thursday's
pipeline explosion in San Bernardino, Calif.
   ``The people of this town need to be responsible enough to not
go crazy, and not alter their purchasing habits,'' said Jack Greco,
chairman of the Nevada Gasoline Retailers Association.
   Reserves were being trucked into southern Nevada from California
refineries 300 miles away, officials said.
   The gasoline supply was disrupted by the blast at San Bernardino
knocked out the Calnev underground pipeline, the chief conduit for
gasoline and diesel fuel for the Las Vegas Valley.
   The explosion, which killed at least three people and shut the
pipeline indefinitely, was in the same place that a freight train
derailed two weeks ago and plowed into nearby houses, killing four.
Inspectors checked the pipeline after that accident and believed
that it had not been damaged.
   Holly Rea, a spokeswoman for GATX, the Chicago-based company
that owns the pipeline, said there were six days worth of gasoline
and a two-day supply of diesel fuel stored in tanks in Las Vegas.
   A spot check of some of the city's busiest stations revealed no
run on the pumps as of Friday morning.
   ``There are no long lines or anything like that,'' said P.J.
Johnson, an employee at a Texaco station at a busy intersection on
the city's east side. ``There's no big rush. Business is just
normal, I guess.''
   The concern over the pipeline disruption was heightened by the
fact that more than 100,000 visitors were expected here for the
three-day Memorial Day weekend, one of the busiest of the year in
Las Vegas. Nearly half of them were expected to come by car.
   Trucking fuel to southern Nevada will be more expensive but oil
company officials said that doesn't necessarily mean a rise in
prices at the pump. ``It will certainly increase our costs, but
we'll absorb that because we want to stay competitive,'' said
Chevron spokesman Mike Libbey.
</TEXT>
