<FIRST>r a AM-Iran-Contra     05-26 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Contra,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Grants Delay in Trial of Former CIA Agent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Friday moved back the
starting date of the Iran-Contra trial of a former CIA agent to
July 24.
   U.S. District Judge Claude Hilton granted the two-week delay
after lawyers for Joseph Fernandez said the government's case has
been tainted with testimony given under immunity from prosecution.
   Fernandez, the CIA's former station chief in Costa Rica, is
accused of covering up his ties to Oliver North's secret Contra
resupply operation. The network operated during a congressional ban
on military aid to the Nicaraguan rebel force.
   Fernandez is accused of obstructing and making false statements
to the CIA's inspector general and the presidentially appointed
Tower Commission early in 1987.
   At a court hearing, Fernandez's lawyer Thomas Wilson said that
Cole Black of the CIA's inspector general office had informed the
prosecution that he had read Fernandez's immunized congressional
testimony detailing many of the activities for which he is now
accused of crimes.
   Black told the prosecution ``he would be unable to ferret out
immunized testimony from non-immunized testimony,'' Wilson said.
Black was interviewed for three hours by the office of independent
counsel Lawrence Walsh and testified before a grand jury for two
hours.
   Prosecutor Robert Longstreth disputed Wilson's assertion, saying
Wilson had been able to come up with just a single example of
Black's testimony possibly being tainted.
   ``We think Black's testimony is clean,'' said Longstreth.
   Under a Supreme Court ruling, the government may not make any
use of a person's immunized testimony in building a case against
him.
   Another CIA employee, Louis Dupart, compliance officer for the
CIA's Central American Task Force, ``steeped himself in immunized
testimony,'' which he used to brief his superiors who also faced
questioning in the Iran-Contra affair, said Wilson.
   The lawyer said the government interviewed Dupart 12 times.
   Hilton said he might require the prosecution to demonstrate more
conclusively that its case wasn't tainted by immunized testimony.
   The judge set aside July 10 to hear any motions concerning the
use of classified information, the use of immunized testimony or
other matters.
   Hilton also directed the prosecution to turn over to Fernandez
for use in his defense a deposition of Lewis Tambs, a former U.S.
ambassador to Costa Rica.
   One of the charges is that Fernandez falsely told the CIA
inspector general that an airstrip in Costa Rica built by the North
network was initiated by the Costa Rican government.
   Prosecutor Laurence Shtasel said Tambs' deposition shows only
``why they (Costa Rican officials) agreed to it subsequently.''
</TEXT>
