<FIRST>r w AM-Veterans-MedicalCuts     05-26 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Veterans-Medical Cuts,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veterans Department Cuts Medical Services</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Veterans Affairs said Friday
that lack of funds is forcing it to curtail medical services.
   VA Secretary Edward Derwinski announced a freeze, except in
emergencies, on accepting new patients with non-service-connected
ailments whose incomes are above certain limits.
   Rep. G. V. ``Sonny'' Montgomery, D-Miss., chairman of the House
Veterans Affairs Committee, said the new limit essentially would
exclude such veterans with incomes greater than $16,476.
   ``This is just sad, that the veteran again is caught in the
squeeze play of politics,'' said Thomas A. Sherwood, director for
health policy and planning at the Vietnam Veterans of America.
   ``There is no question that this will affect a large number of
veterans,'' said Cooper T. Holt, executive director of the
Washington office of the Veterans of Foreign Wars.
   The VA also announced that vacant staff positions at VA
facilities will not be filled, the agency will stop spending for
the maintenance and purchase of certain equipment and the start-up
of several projects will be delayed.
   ``I must take these actions to keep the system functioning
within the limits of our resources,'' said Derwinski. He said the
cuts should allow the agency to contunue operating at a reduced
level until June 15.
   By then, he said, he hopes Congress will have resolved an
impasse that has prevented approval of a supplemental funding bill
for the department. If that does not occur, said Derwinski, more
drastic cuts may be needed.
   The House passed a supplemental appropriation bill last week
including $340 million to continue operations of VA health care
facilities through the remainder of the fiscal year.
   The Senate, however, passed a measure including money only
through June 15. The House balked at that limit and the dispute
remains unresolved.
   ``These folks just can't get together to do what is best for the
veterans that we are supposed to be serving,'' said Sherwood..
   ``Some vets have no choice but to rely on the VA'' for medical
care, he said.
   Montgomery said some alcohol and drug treatment service have
already been cut back and that nursing home and hospital beds will
have to be closed for lack of staff.
</TEXT>
