<FIRST>r a AM-VandalismVictims     05-26 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vandalism Victims,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Presentence Hearing Held in College Auditorium in School Vandalism
Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Aethan in 5th graf is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INVER GROVE HEIGHTS, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It took a college auditorium
to hold all the people who wanted to testify or sit in on a
presentence hearing for four teen-age vandals who damaged a high
school so badly it is still closed two months later.
   ``The first thing that crosses your mind is lock them up for 10
years,'' Dennis Thul, a high school parent testified at the
Thursday night hearing attended by more than 300 people. But after
reflecting, Thul said, ``What I would like to see is harsh
punishment in community service.''
   Other parents, along with teachers, classmates and taxpayers,
recommended community service, counseling, restitution, even some
jail time for that damage that ranges upwards of $6 million. But
none recommended extended prison sentences.
   One student handed in a petition he said was signed by 285
people urging that the four defendants not be sent to prison.
   ``I expected in some ways tonight to have a vigilante
atmosphere,'' said parent Aethan Hart, who expressed relief at what
he called a ``thoughtful process.''
   Many of the approximately 30 people who testified at Inver Hills
Community College expressed sympathy for the teen-agers' families
and pleaded with the judges to impose sentences that allow for
rehabilitation.
   But they also expressed anger and frustration over students'
projects that were destroyed and the disruption it caused.
   The 1,220-student Henry Sibley High School in the St. Paul
suburb of Mendota Heights has been closed since the March 23
damage. The vandals destroyed student projects and teaching
equipment and turned on fire hoses that soaked asbestos,
contaminating air in the building.
   Sibley students are attending another school during the repair
and cleanup.
   All four defendants, three of them 18 years old and one 17, have
pleaded guilty to felony first-degree criminal dmage to property,
third-degree burglary and theft. On June 12, Dakota County District
Judge Thomas Lacy is to sentence Jason Lasch and the juvenile,
while District Judge William Thuet is to sentence Edward Easton and
Matthew Klein.
   All four attended the presentence hearing, but said nothing.
Lasch was the only one who wasn't a student at Sibley at the time
of the vandalism and Klein was the only one unable to make his
$25,000 bail. He has been in jail since the end of March.
   State law requires the state Corrections Department to get from
crime victims a statement of the damage they suffered and their
opinions on sentencing. Because of the unusually large number of
victims in this case, the judges decided to hold the hearing in the
auditorium.
   Dakota County Attorney James Backstrom has said the case
justifies an upward departure from the sentencing guidelines, which
call for no more than a year in the county jail and 10 years of
probation for the 18-year-olds.
   The juvenile cannot be sentenced to community service or a
juvenile institution past his 19th birthday, which is 13 months
from now.
</TEXT>
