<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--NukeTest     05-26 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Nuke Test,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fifth Test of 1989 at Nevada Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YUCCA FLAT, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department conducted its
fifth nuclear weapons test of the year at the Nevada Test Site on
Friday, and it was deemed ``very successful.''
   Energy Department spokesman Jim Boyer said the test was weapons
related and carried an explosive force of less than 20 kilotons.
All tests are listed as having an explosive yield of less than 20
kilotons, or 20 to 150 kilotons.
   A kiloton is equivalent to one thousand tons of TNT.
   ``The test was very successful,'' Boyer said. ``There were no
problems.''
   The test, code-named Tulia, was the 692nd announced shot since
testing began in Nevada in January 1951.
   The device was detonated at 11:07 a.m. in a shaft 1,300 feet
beneath the surface of Yucca Flat, about 80 miles northwest of Las
Vegas. The blast was not felt in Las Vegas.
   Boyer said there were no protesters at the site at the time of
detonation.
</TEXT>
