<FIRST>u i AM-ArabSummit     05-26 0742</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arab Summit,0771</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arabs Agree on Six-Month Plan for Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CASABLANCA, Morocco (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Arab League summit closed two
days late Friday after adopting what Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq
Aziz called a ``gentleman's agreement'' for Syria to withdraw its
troops from Lebanon.
   Syrian intransigence prevented any resolution explicitly calling
for the Syrian army to leave Lebanon, the main Iraqi objective.
Several times the Syrian-Iraqi confrontation almost led to the
collapse of the summit.
   The Arab leaders appointed a three-member committee and gave it
six months to supervise a cease-fire, reconvene Lebanon's
Parliament, arrange the appointment of a president and amend the
constitution for more balanced power-sharing between the warring
Moslems and Christians.
   The negotiators are Morocco's King Hassan II, King Fahd of Saudi
Arabia and Algeria's President Chadli Bendjedid.
   In Beirut, surprising support for the peace plan came from
acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, the Moslem leader whose closest
ally is Syria.
   ``I welcome the resolutions of the Arab summit and hope they
will be implemented as soon as possible,'' Hoss said in a brief
statement.
   His Christian opponent, Gen. Michel Aoun, will not comment until
after an emergency meeting Saturday of his rival Cabinet, Aoun's
spokesman said.
   But the Christian Lebanese Broadcasting Corp. said the summit
``failed to offer anything more than lip service to help resolve
the Lebanon crisis.''
   ``The summit also has failed to devise a mechanism to monitor a
cease-fire and made no reference to the role of the Syrian army in
Lebanon,'' it said.
   Aoun has insisted on a Syrian pullout as a precondition for a
Moslem-Christian dialogue on political reforms to end the 14-year
civil war.
   In Casablanca, the war of words between arch foes Syria and Iraq
caused chaotic scenes and almost led the summit to collapse.
   As a result, the meeting continued for four days, longer than
any summit in the Arab League's 44-year history, Moroccan
television said.
   Iraq's Aziz told reporters that if Syria does not withdraw
within six months, his government will demand another summit.
   The conference resolution ``fell short of what must be done on
this important issue,'' Aziz said. But he added the leaders reached
``a gentleman's agreement for a pullout of Syrian troops,'' first
from Beirut then from other regions.
   Syria has 40,000 troops in Moslem west Beirut and Lebanon's
eastern and northern provinces under a 1976 league peacekeeping
mandate.
   Secretary-General Chedli Klibi read the final communique closing
the summit, called primarily to reinstate Egypt in the 22-nation
league after a 10-year suspension for making peace with Israel.
Delegates provided the text of other resolutions.
   The summit adopted a seven-point plan on Lebanon that stressed
the country's unity, Arab identity, territorial integrity and
independence. It asserted the fate of Lebanon is a ``general Arab
responsibility,'' and called on all Lebanese factions to respect
the much-fractured cease-fire called by the Arab League last April.
   King Hassan's committee was asked:
   _To invite Lebanese legislators to a conference to prepare a
political reform document that would form the basis for national
reconciliation.
   _To get Parliament to ratify the document.
   _To arrange for Parliament to elect a president who would form a
``government of national reconciliation'' that would amend the
constitution. A new constitution likely would reflect the wishes of
Lebanon's Moslem majority, shrinking the power of the minority
Christians who traditionally have dominated Lebanese politics.
   _To support the government in exercising full sovereignty over
all Lebanese territory.
   The last refers not only to Syrian troops, but also about 2,000
Iranian Revolutionary Guards in Lebanon at Syria's invitation and
about 1,000 Israeli troops that patrol the self-designated security
zone Israel carved out of southern Lebanon after its 1982-85
invasion.
   The summit communique condemned ``continued Israeli aggression
against Lebanon and its sovereignty.''
   Arab leaders agreed to pay a $120 million lump sum and provide
monthly payments of $43 million promised last year to support the
Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied territories. The
Palestine Liberation Organization complained to the meeting that
only Libya and Saudi Arabia had paid up.
   It supported PLO opposition to an Israeli proposal for elections
on the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip of Palestinians who would
negotiate with Israel for limited self-rule.
   The summit backed PLO demands that elections be held under
international supervision ``within the framework of a comprehensive
peace process, since the Israeli scheme aims at undermining the
uprising and sidestepping the PLO and the Palestinian people's
inalienable national rights.''
</TEXT>
