<FIRST>r w AM-Singer 1stLd-Writethru a0607 05-26 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Singer, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0607,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Bars Singer Company From Selling Assets, Paying Dividends</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 1 graf with appeal indicated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Singer Company has been barred from
selling any of its assets or paying stock dividends pending a
lawsuit over claims a former subsidiary defrauded the government.
   The company, named as a co-defendant in a civil suit against its
former Link Flight Simulation Division, was also ordered not to
incur any new debt or make any payments to investor Paul Bilzerian,
the Florida financier who acquired the company last year.
   The preliminary injunction, issued by a federal judge in
Baltimore, was sought by the Justice Department, which last March
joined the $231 million lawsuit that had originally been filed by a
former Link Flight pricing administrator.
   The complaint charges that the company cheated the Defense
Department out of $77 million by submitting false contract bid data
on flight simulation equipment to train pilots. It seeks triple
damages from Link Flight, which is now owned by CAE Industries Ltd.
of Toronto.
   Singer is named as a defendant in the False Claims Act suit
along with the Canadian company.
   In a brief order signed Thursday, U.S. District Judge Herbert F.
Murray said he granted the injunction because ``the continued
reduction of the assets of Singer Company could cause irreparable
harm to the ability of the United States to collect a judgment'' if
it wins the lawsuit.
   There was no immediate comment from the company, which has
headquarters in Tampa, Fla. But attorneys for Singer indicated they
planned to appeal Murray's decision by seeking a stay pending an
appeal. Murray has not ruled on the request.
</TEXT>
