<FIRST>u i AM-DiplomatKilled     05-26 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Diplomat Killed,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Diplomat Stabbed to Death in Her London Apartment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American diplomat was stabbed to death in her
ground-floor west London apartment, police said Friday.
   Scotland Yard said the body of Marie Burke, 63, a second
secretary who worked in the consular section of the U.S. Embassy,
was found Thursday afternoon after a colleague became concerned
when she failed to show up for work.
   She last seen about 10 p.m. Wednesday, heading home after dining
with friends, police said.
   Police said they found Mrs. Burke in bed, still in her
nightclothes, with what appeared to be a single stab wound in the
chest.
   Detective Superintendent Alan Lewis, leading the investigation,
said: ``There is no sign of forced entry, and it appears the
assailant may have got in through an insecure or open window.''
   Officers said her purse was missing but embassy-owned art
objects were left undisturbed. Scotland Yard said she did not
appear to have been sexually assaulted.
   A Yard spokesman, speaking anonymously, said the slaying was not
believed to have a political motive or diplomatic connection.
   Neither Scotland Yard nor the U.S. Embassy knew Mrs. Burke's
hometown, although the embassy said she was from New York state.
   Mrs. Burke, who was widowed in 1974, is survived by two
daughters and a son, police said. She had worked in the U.S.
Consular Service since the late 1970s and had been posted in London
for the last 18 months.
   A statement issued by U.S. Ambassador Henry E. Catto and the
embassy staff said: ``Marie Burke was a valued and beloved
colleague. We share the grief of her family and our prayers are
with them. We extend to them our heartfelt condolences.''
