<FIRST>r i AM-Turkey-Bulgaria     05-26 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey-Bulgaria,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethnic Turks Deported From Bulgaria Report Violent Clashes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMEL ANIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 160 ethnic Turks deported from
Bulgaria arrived in Turkey on Friday and said at least 30 people
have died in recent clashes between Turks and security forces in
Bulgaria.
   The deportees said growing resistance to an assimilation
campaign in Bulgaria led to the violence. The campaign includes
forcing ethnic Turks to change their Moslem names to Slavic ones.
   ``At least 30 are dead, 200 seriously injured and about 2,000
have been arrested,'' said Tahsin Haliloglu, one of 167 deported
ethnic Turks who arrived in Ankara. Officials said 90 other
deportees will arrive soon.
   Haliloglu said he was an organizer of the weekend demonstrations.
   ``We want our names back, education in Turkish in schools and
the right to carry on our traditions and our religious worship
which are all forbidden now,'' said Ali Ormanli, another deportee.
   Ormanli had been participating in a hunger strike in Bulgaria.
He said such strikes were spreading across Bulgaria.
   Ormanli said he was sent to a concentration camp in 1985 and
stayed there for two years and 10 months. After his release, he
said he was exiled to another part of Bulgaria. He said he was
deported May 9 without seeing his family.
   ``All this was because I refused to change my name,'' Ormanli
said in an interview at the airport.
   About 300 people from emigre communities in Turkey greeted the
deportees. There were tearful reunions as some people found family
members.
   Premier Turgut Ozal also went to the airport and said Turkey
will ask all countries that signed a Helsinki agreement on human
rights in January to pressure Bulgaria to change its policies on
its 900,000 ethnic Turks.
   After the start of the campaign, Turkey asked Bulgaria for
negotiations and said it was willing to accept the entire Turkish
minority.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
