<FIRST>u i AM-Missionaries     05-26 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missionaries,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Question Witnesses in US Missionary Killings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police questioned witnesses Friday who
saw a yellow vehicle speed away after two young American
missionaries were cut down by machine-gun fire. A guerrilla group
has claimed responsibility.
   The bodies of Todd Ray Wilson and Jeffrey Brent Ball, both
20-year-old Mormons from Utah, were taken to the La Paz airport for
return to the United States. Wilson's hometown was Wellington and
Ball was from Coalville.
   They were killed as they returned home Wednesday night.
   A statement distributed to La Paz newspapers claimed
responsibility on behalf of the Zarate Willka Armed Liberation
Front.
   It said, in part: ``The violation of our sovereignty cannot go
unpunished. The Yankee invaders who come to massacre our fellow
farmers are warned, as are their local slaves. We the poor have no
other road than to rise up in arms. Our hatred is implacable and
our war is to the death.''
   Zarate Willka was a 19th century Indian revolutionary in Bolivia.
   The group using his name also claimed responsibility for a bomb
that exploded in August near a motorcade carrying George P. Shultz,
then secretary of state. Several vehicles were damaged but no
injuries were reported.
   Interior Minister Eduardo Perez Beltran said the group ``does
not have a political affilitation and one cannot therefore speak of
the existence of guerillas in the country. We are facing something
that could also come from ... the cocaine trade.''
   U.S. Embassy officials, who are cooperating in the
investigation, say the responsibility is not yet clear.
   The two missionaries of the Church of Latter Day Saints lived
near a Mormon church that was seriously damaged by a bomb in 1988.
They arrived a year ago and were working in the Villa Victoria
neighborhood near downtown La Paz.
   About 400 Mormon missionaries are assigned to Bolivia, church
officials said.
   American officials said security had been strengthened for the
embassy and its personnel. They said it this was the first case of
U.S. citizens being killed by a terrorist or guerrilla group in
Bolivia.
</TEXT>
