<FIRST>r i AM-Premier'sStroll     05-26 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Premier's Stroll,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Premier Wanders Among Deputies, Press Outside Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a break with Kremlin leaders' traditional
isolation, Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov waded into a crowd of
reporters and parliamentarians outside the Congress on Friday.
   It was the second night in a row such a thing had happened. On
Thursday, Defense Minister Dmitri T. Yazov traded World War II
stories with deputies and Politburo member Vadim A. Medvedev
chatted with foreign reporters.
   Ryzhkov is No. 2 man in the Soviet government.
   After he genially answered questions on everything from housing
loans to private film-making in the dusk of a northern summer,
security men built like boxers lectured Soviet reporters for
snagging the boss for a second round of questioning before the
premier strode off under the Kremlin's blooming chestnuts and
lilacs.
   ``Hey, we're journalists, it's our job,'' said Mikhail Sokorov,
a local newspaper reporter.
   The security men had little to fear, however, as all the
deputies and news media people had passed a gauntlet of guards to
enter the brick-walled fortress in the center of Moscow during the
Congress.
   Still, it was a thrill for the mass of newly elected deputies
from ordinary walks of life to find their previously remote leaders
within touching distance. At least 50 crowded around Ryzhkov Friday
night, until the pack became so thick it was impossible to identify
the attraction in the middle.
   Ryzhkov's appearances carried a slight air of campaigning, since
he faces the Congress in his first election test possibly on
Saturday. The political reform that created the Congress also gave
it the power to confirm the premier, and he has come under fire
from a few deputies in the past week for his work on the economy
and the environment.
   ``My soul hurts when I think about pensions,'' Ryzhkov said
Friday in response to a question about a deputy's demand for
increases in payments as low as $36 a month to retirees.
   ``He says we must find the money. But how?''
   Ryzhkov said he is convinced that ``individual plots and the
construction of individual houses'' must be permitted to solve a
housing crunch, but left Moscow out of that possibility without
explaining.
   Development of the Soviet space shuttle led to creation of 100
new industrial materials, he boasted. But dragging those ideas into
the domestic economy is proving far harder.
   ``We should create such economic conditions that people chase
after them,'' he said.
   Private cooperatives may be controversial but they're an
explosive success in the government's economic reform program, he
said. In the 2{ years since the small businesses were legalized,
100,000 have cropped up. They contributed about $6.75 billion to
the economy in just the first three months of this year, he said.
</TEXT>
