<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 2026EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TeenAssault     05-26 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teen Assault,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>School Is Out, But Tension Continues After Sex Assault Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McMAHON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLEN RIDGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Glen Ridge High School welcomed a
scheduled holiday Friday but the baseball team took the field
without its captain, a reminder of the upheaval over the arrests of
five students on sexual assault charges.
   Law enforcement officials, meanwhile, would not comment on a
newspaper report Friday that the students charged in the March 1
incident asked another student to videotape them having sex with
the mentally retarded girl on another occasion.
   The student, Charles Figueroa, a football teammate of some of
the boys charged, told the New York Post he refused to make the
tape and eventually informed authorities about the incident. There
was no answer Friday in repeated attempts to call Figueroa.
   Glen Ridge Superintendent of Schools Rose McCaffrey said
Figueroa's comments are suspect. ``Charlie has a knack of
fantasizing and takes off and starts discussing things,'' Ms.
McCaffrey said.
   ``I'm not saying this is not true at all,'' she said. ``Because
of the statements he made, we immediately notified police.''
   Ms. McCaffrey said Figueroa told a teacher what the other
students had told him about the sexual assault, and was kept out of
school for several days on the request of his mother, Mary, who
feared retaliation from students.
   Ray Weiss, a spokesman for the Essex County prosecutor's office,
would not comment on the report, but said, ``We are pursuing all
angles of the investigation.''
   There was no indication a second episode took place.
   The five students were arrested Wednesday and charged with
sexually assaulting a 17-year-old girl with a broomstick and
miniature baseball bat. Eight other male teens cheered the attack
without intervening, investigators said.
   Two of those charged, twin brothers Kyle and Kevin Scherzer, are
captains of the football team and Kyle is captain of the baseball
team, which played a game without him Friday.
   All five have been suspended from school for 10 days.
   ``The student body is divided but this is, I guess, to be
expected,'' said Ms. McCaffrey. ``There are feelings of friendship
and antagonism.''
   Some students friendly with those charged said the young woman,
who has since turned 18, willingly participated in the incident.
Friends of the young woman said she did not fully understand what
was happening.
   Officials have said she attends special education classes but
have not elaborated on the extent of her mental impairment.
   Attorneys for some of the boys charged Friday criticized the
media attention and the prosecutor's handling of the case.
   ``I think it's awful because, first of all, whether you're a
parent, victim or alleged defendant, it's a tragedy and there is a
presumption of innocence,'' said Donald W. Merkelbach, attorney for
the Scherzers.
   ``I understand the media's job but I think they have infringed
upon the presumption of innocence.''
</TEXT>
