<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-MassGrave     05-26 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Mass Grave,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>600 Bodies Found In Post-War Mass Grave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mass grave discovered near the capital
last month contains the remains of more than 600 men, women and
children buried between 1944 and 1947 by Soviet and Polish secret
police, official and independent reports said Thursday.
   The bodies appear to include both German POWs and Polish
resistance fighters who were arrested by the Soviet secret police
after the war, according to Gazeta Wyborcza, an independent
Solidarity newspaper, and the officially published daily Express
Wieczorny.
   The investigation comes during increasing efforts, backed by the
communist government, to acknowledge repressions of the postwar
years.
   The chairman of the Council for Preserving the Memory of
Struggle and Martyrdom, Gen. Roman Paszkowski, told the state PAP
news agency Thursday that searches were in progress for graves of
Polish officers and other victims of ``reprisals of the Stalinist
period.''
   An unknown number of Poles, many of whom fought with the
underground Home Army against the Nazi occupiers during World War
II, were executed by Soviet secret police after the war.
   The Home Army remained loyal to the Polish government-in-exile
during the war, and the Soviets considered its officers suspect
when communists came to power in Poland after 1944. Some were
believed to have been executed in secret and others were deported
to Siberian prisons.
   ``We will do our best to commemorate events, places and figures
in our history in tune with historical truth,'' Paszkowski said.
   In Otwock, the bodies were found piled in five layers after a
journalist decided to follow up on rumors circulating in the area.
When bones and skulls were unearthed, the mayor named a priest and
two representatives of the independent Solidarity movement to an
investigatory commission.
   The commission examined about 400 bodies, and found 50 percent
had some signs of postmortem dissection. None had been victims of
shooting, according to PAP.
   The bodies were unclothed and no objects that could lead to
identification have been found in the grave, which is in a wooded
area, Gazeta Wyborcza said.
   Longtime residents told investigators about seeing the burial of
bodies of German POWs who died of disease and starvation at a
Soviet prison camp in the town, the newspaper said. The German
prisoners were pitifully thin and would plead through a fence for
scraps of bread, residents recalled.
   One witness recounted being told to bury his wife, a Polish Home
Army officer arrested on charges of anti-Soviet activities by the
Polish secret police. She died at the Soviet prison hospital in
Otwock in 1947, he said.
   Maria Grzeskowiak, interviewed in Express Wieczorny, said she
was a nurse at the hospital and tended to dying German POWs and
Home Army prisoners whose bodies were taken to be buried.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
