<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Students     05-26 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Students,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Vote To Keep Striking for Independent Association</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   University students decided Friday to keep
striking nationwide until they win ``final victory'' and receive
permission to register a pro-Solidarity association, spokesmen said.
   Members of the banned Independent Students Association, or NZS,
said they formed an interschool strike committee to coordinate
protest activities.
   Students stressed at a news conference that they did not want
their strike to disturb election campaigning now going on in Poland
and would not call for a boycott of the voting June 4.
   The annual exam period is scheduled to begin Monday, and strike
organizers said students should take their examinations. Strikers,
however, planned to continue to occupy academic buildings.
   ``The national strike committee created today has decided to
continue the strikes until final victory,'' a statement read at a
student rally said.
   The strikes began Tuesday after a Warsaw court rejected the
application to register NZS. The court said the group illegally
claimed the right to hold strikes.
   Banners saying, ``We demand registration of NZS'' hung from the
gates of Warsaw University and Warsaw Polytechnic, an engineering
school.
   NZS spokesman Slawomir Gorecki reported student strikes in
Wroclaw, Lodz, Poznan and Plock, and strike alerts in other cities.
Authorities made no attempt to evict the strikers.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa and Poland's Roman Catholic
primate, Cardinal Jozef Glemp, endorsed NZS's right to be
registered and offered their help.
   Actor Andrzej Lapicki, a Solidarity parliamentary candidate,
appeared with French movie star Yves Montand on Friday at a rally
of about 750 students at Warsaw University and both voiced support
for the students' cause.
   Montand told the crowd through an interpreter, ``To defend
Solidarity means to defend democracy and freedom in Europe and in
the world. And today, I feel united with Solidarity and with Warsaw
students. I also feel united with students in Beijing and in
China.''
   After the rally, about 100 of the students blocked a main street
in front of the university for about one hour before giving up the
blockade peacefully.
</TEXT>
