<FIRST>r p AM-Mondale-Senate     05-26 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mondale-Senate,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mondale Won't Challenge Boschwitz; Rules Out Other Campaigns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY R. SANDOK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Minnesota political era ended Friday when
former Vice President Walter F. Mondale said he will not challenge
Republican U.S. Sen. Rudy Boschwitz in 1990 or seek any other
elective office in the future.
   ``I believe it's time for other candidates to step forward,''
said Mondale, a former senator who was the Democratic Party's
presidential nominee in 1984. ``It was a very difficult choice for
us.''
   Mondale and his mentor, the late Hubert H. Humphrey, dominated
Minnesota politics from 1948, when Humphrey was elected to the U.S.
Senate, to 1980, when the Carter-Mondale ticket lost the
presidential race. Both Mondale and Humphrey, who died in 1978,
represented Minnesota in the Senate, served as vice president and
were unsuccessful Democratic presidential nominees.
   ``A lot of the people I worked for have been dead for a long
time and at some point, even Mondale has to get out,'' said
Mondale, 61. ``One of the requirements of a healthy party is that
it renews itself. You can't keep running Walter Mondale for
everything.''
   Mondale said he and his wife, Joan, have enjoyed his life out of
political office and has seen too many colleagues remain in the
Senate for too long.
   ``I'm at peace with myself,'' Mondale said. ``We took a lot of
time making this decision and it's a basic one. It's a lot easier
deciding when to get into politics as opposed to when to leave.''
   U.S. Rep. Tim Penny, D-Minn., said Mondale has positioned
himself to play the role of elder statesman.
   ``I grew up during the Humphrey-Mondale era in Minnesota,'' said
Penny, 37. ``I guess this kind of closes the chapter on this book.''
   Mondale generally had been considered the most formidable
candidate Democrats could field against Boschwitz, a two-term
senator. His announcement was expected to result in an immediate
scramble among Minnesota Democrats for their party's 1990 U.S.
Senate endorsement.
   Boschwitz, 58, said he was relieved that Mondale had decided not
to run. But Boschwitz said the race could be tough no matter who
his challenger is because of Minnesota's tendency to favor
Democrats.
   ``I'm not breathing easy,'' he said. ``I'm going to keep going.''
   Democratic National Committee member Paul Wellstone, a political
science professor at Carleton College and a leader of the Rev.
Jesse Jackson's 1988 presidential campaign in Minnesota, is the
only announced challenger.
   Other Democrats who on Friday said they were considering bids
now that Mondale is out of the race included department store heir
Mark Dayton, who unsuccessfully challenged Republican Sen. Dave
Durenberger in 1982; Hennepin County Commissioner John Derus, who
unsuccessfully sought the Democratic endorsement to challenge
Boschwitz in 1984; and Minneapolis attorney Tom Berg, a former U.S.
attorney and head of Gov. Rudy Perpich's fund-raising committee.
   Mondale, a lawyer, represented Minnesota in the Senate from 1965
until 1976, when he left to be Jimmy Carter's vice president. He
lost to Ronald Reagan in the 1984 presidential campaign.
</TEXT>
