<HEAD>Leftist Organizations Searched Following Combat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers searched the offices
of four labor, peasant and human rights organizations Friday and
cordoned off others after a night of guerrilla attacks on the
capital.
   The U.S.-supported government and the armed forces suspect the
organizations of being fronts for the leftist rebels who began a
civil war nine years ago.
   Troops from the 1st Army Brigade, the National Police and
Treasury Police took part in the operation.
   One union organization said two of its leaders had been
arrested. Police spokesmen consulted by telephone said they had no
information on the matter.
   Col. Orlando Zepeda, commander of the 1st Army Brigade, accused
the organizations Thursday night of harboring guerrillas who had
attacked his men at dusk. Fighting continued in much of northern
San Salvador for more than an hour.
   Several guerrilla attack were reported, and fighting in the
capital was the heaviest in years. Officials reported seven people
killed and 20 wounded.
   Security in and around San Salvador was noticeably stronger
Friday morning. Soldiers and police stopped and searched vehicles
at roadblocks.
   Attacks on the capital have increased recently in a campaign the
Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front calls ``All Against
Arena. We're going to Win.''
   Arena is the Spanish acronym for Republican Nationalist
Alliance, the rightist party of President-elect Alfredo Cristiani,
who will be inaugurated June 1.
