<SECOND>AM-Nazi Convicted,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Head of Nazi POW Camp Convicted Of Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUENEBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 66-year-old former commandant
of a Nazi prisoner of war camp was convicted Friday of the 1944
murder of two inmates and sentenced to life in prison.
   Horst Czerwinski had been accused of shooting to death eight
Russian prisoners at Lagischa camp near Auschwitz, in what is now
Poland. Lagischa was a Nazi labor camp for captured Russian,
French, Polish and Hungarian soldiers. In a trial in Lueneburg that
lasted for years and included testimony from 204 witnesses,
Czerwinski was convicted of killing two of the inmates.
   Czerwinski insisted he did not carry out any of the murders, but
the court ruled former inmates provided irrefutable testimony that
he executed two Russian prisoners in the camp's laundry barracks
after they tried to escape.
   Until his arrest in 1985 on new evidence, Czerwinski was a
butcher in Celle, about 25 miles northwest of Hanover.
