<FIRST>r i AM-BritonsExpelled 1stLd-Writethru a0668 05-26 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britons Expelled, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0668,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechoslovakia Expels Britons in Retaliation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs on Tass chief protesting.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government responded Friday to
Britain's expulsion of four Czechoslovaks by ordering four Britons
out of the country for ``activities incompatible with their
status,'' the standard term for spying.
   Three British diplomats and a businessman were ordered to leave
within two weeks, the official news agency CTK reported.
   The British Foreign Office described the action as unjustified
retaliation for the order Thursday that four Czechoslovak diplomats
leave Britain for the same reason.
   CTK said the Foreign Ministry summoned Laurence O'Keefe, the
British ambassador, to receive a ``resolute protest of groundless
charges'' against the four Czechoslovaks.
   Britain's decision is in conflicts with ``the process of
strengthening confidence and security in Europe,'' the agency
declared in its report.
   In London, a Foreign Office spokesman identified the Britons as
Tony Arnold, first secretary of administration; Rick Todd, first
secretary counselor; Patricia Holland, third secretary; and Nick
Brooks, manager for Shell Oil.
   ``It's clearly an unjustified action,'' said the spokesman,
speaking anonymously in keeping with British custom. ``It's clearly
in retaliation,'' he added, and the government will ``consider what
our response will be.''
   After Britain ordered the Czechslovaks to leave, the Communist
Party daily Rude Pravo said it was another case of ``British
spymania, which certain British circles bring about from time to
time.''
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher told the House of Commons on
Thursday the expulsions of the Czechoslovaks and of 11 Soviets a
week ago were necessary ``regardless of the effect upon our
relations.''
   Britain had enjoyed its best relations with the Soviet Union
since World War II before the exchange last week, and relations
with Czechoslovakia were improving.
   Sir John Fretwell, Foreign Office political director, said
Czechoslovakia ignored warnings about in its diplomats given last
September, when three others were expelled.
   The exchange with Moscow began May 19 when Britain ordered eight
Soviet diplomats and three journalists out. Moscow retaliated a day
later with expulsions of like number and kind.
   Britain and the Soviets now are discussing Kremlin demands that
Britain reduce to 205 the number of Britons and local employees in
the Soviet Union. Moscow says that matches the number of Soviets
allowed in Britain.
   Director General Leonid Kravchenko, head of the Soviet news
agency Tass, protested in a letter to Foreign Secretary Sir
Geoffrey Howe on Friday over the expulsion of London-based Tass
correspondent Igor Peskov.
   Kravchenko said Peskov, 35, was a man of ``impeccable honesty''
and had done nothing to contravene British or international law.
   British newspaper reports, quoting government sources in London,
said Peskov headed a spy ring offering bribes in return for
industrial secrets. Peskov denied it. Britain disclosed no specific
reason for the expulsions.
   Howe said in Birmingham Friday that Britain will continue to
take a tough line to defend national security.
</TEXT>
