<SECOND>AM-Nigeria-Riots,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Student Protests Continue Despite Military Clampdown, One Death Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students blocked streets and set tires on
fire Friday and a boy was reported killed during a third straight
day of clashes between protesters and security forces in a
midwestern city.
   The protesters are demonstrating against sharp rises in the
price of some basic foods and services, resulting from the
government's strict adherence to an austerity program demanded by
Western creditors.
   The state-controlled News Agency of Nigeria said an order by the
military governor to shoot rioters on sight and a dusk-to-dawn
curfew failed to quell the disturbances in Benin, 165 miles east of
Lagos.
   At least 100 people have been reported injured, 15 serious
enough to require hospitalization, Lagos newspapers said. The
University of Benin was ordered closed, the news agency said.
   At one stage, rioters stormed Radio Nigeria's local broadcast
station and forced workers to flee, the news agency reported. The
dead youth's body was found in front of the station, it said.
   Lagos newspapers said police had avoided confronting the rioters
during the first two days of demonstrations.
   The students, joined by some local street traders, market women,
taxi drivers and unemployed men, also broke into a local jail and
freed 600 prisoners.
   Disturbances were reported earlier in the week in several other
university cities, including Lagos, but they died out quickly.
