<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-26 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Cross Appalachians; Rivers Overflow in Ohio, Indiana</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms on Friday brought hail and damaging winds from
Missouri and Arkansas into the central Appalachians, and flooding
from heavy rain continued in Ohio and Indiana.
   Flooding in southwest Ohio left at least three people missing. A
20-month-old boy was swept away after he fell into a rain-swollen
creek northeast of Dayton, Ohio, authorities said. At Miamitown, a
one-lane temporary bridge washed away, sending a car and a pickup
truck into the Great Miami River. Floods also forced the evacuation
of about 200 people in Camden.
   Rivers continued to rise in parts of Indiana and Ohio as a
result of heavy rains Thursday. The White River was expected to
crest 2 feet above flood stage on Saturday at Noblesville, Ind.,
and at Ravenswood, Ind., flooding homes.
   Thunderstorms dropped golf-ball-size hail near Batesville, Ark.,
and one-inch-diameter hail near Senath, Mo., and in Simpson County,
Ky.
   The storms extended from southeast Missouri and northeast
Arkansas across parts of Kentucky and Tennessee into West Virginia,
which experienced damaging winds Friday night.
   Showers fell and some thunderstorms occurred across eastern
Pennsylvania and eastern New York.
   A stationary thunderstorm dumped more than three-quarters of an
inch of rain on Key West, Fla., in an hour and a half.
   Key West also had a record-tying high temperature of 91 degrees.
San Antonio had a record high of 97.
   Rain showers were scattered over northern Kansas and along the
Washington state coast.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included
nearly an inch and a quarter at Fayetteville, Ark., almost
three-quarters of an inch at Jackson, Ky., and more than one-third
inch at Elkins, W.Va., and Albany, N.Y.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 46
degrees at Sault Saint Marie, Mich., and Goodland, Kan., to 99
degrees at Cotulla, Texas, and Laredo, Texas. The nation's low
Friday morning was 15 degrees at Jackson, Wyo.
   The forecast for Saturday called for showers and thunderstorms
scattered from the Texas Gulf Coast across the lower Mississippi
Valley to much of the Atlantic Coast. Rain showers were predicted
from the northern Pacific Coast into the northern Rockies. Clear
skies were expected over much of the rest of the nation.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 50s and 60s along much of
the Pacific Coast and into the northern Rockies; the 60s from
eastern Minnesota and eastern Iowa across the Great Lakes into
northern New England; and the 90s from along the southern Atlantic
Coast across Florida, along the Gulf Coast, across the southern
half of Texas into inland valleys of Southern California. Readings
were expected to climb above 100 degrees in the desert Southwest
and Rio Grande Valley. Highs in the rest of the nation were
forecast generally in the 70s and 80s.
</TEXT>
