<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Newspaper     05-26 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Newspaper,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Asahi President Quits After Cameraman Damages Rare Coral Reef</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Japan's second-largest newspaper
said Friday he will resign to take responsibility for an incident
in which a staff photographer damaged a rare coral reef to
illustrate a story on environmental destruction.
   Asahi Shimbun President Toichiro Hitotsuyanagi told a news
conference he will be succeeded by Toshitada Nakae, currently a
managing director, on June 24. Hitotsuyanagi has served as Asahi
president since December 1984.
   The newspaper said it has received ``bitter and growing''
complaints from readers about the incident last month, when its
cameraman reportedly carved the initials ``KY'' in the surface of a
rare underwater coral for a photograph of damage to the reef
allegedly caused by private divers.
   An article accompanying a front-page color photograph of the
carved initials in the newspaper's April 20 edition criticized the
``spiritual poverty'' of Japanese who damage the environment.
   The incident has since received wide coverage in the Japanese
press, with several newspapers condemning the Asahi.
   The Asahi has apologized twice editorially for the incident.
   The reef, 13 feet in height and 66 feet in circumference, is
said to be the largest in the world of its species, Galaxea
Fascicularis.
   Located in the southern islands of Okinawa, it is designated a
protected area by Japan's Environment Agency, but some pieces of
coral have been broken off by the air tanks of divers, the Asahi
article said.
   Violaters of the Nature Conservation Law are liable for up to
six months in jail and a fine of up to $714.
   After a series of protests by local divers, the Asahi admitted
its photographer intentionally damaged the coral reef.
   Earlier this month, the newspaper demoted its managing editor
and photo department chief in connection with the incident. The
photographer has been dismissed.
</TEXT>
