<FIRST>r a AM-ElPasoMayor     05-26 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-El Paso Mayor,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>El Paso Mayoral Runoff Campaign Turns Personal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The race between El Paso mayoral
candidates Suzie Azar and Ed Elsey, which once turned on issues
such as economic development and crime, became personal as
Saturday's runoff neared.
   The two city council members achieved a runoff by defeating four
other mayoral candidates in the general election May 6.
   Mrs. Azar outpolled Elsey 31 percent to 23 percent, but Elsey
since has refused to make a public appearance with Mrs. Azar until
she reveals how much her family makes from businesses on property
they lease from the city near the El Paso International Airport.
   Elsey says Mrs. Azar could face a conflict of interest in votes
on airport matters.
   Under Elsey's prodding, Mrs. Azar issued a statement saying she
and her husband had a net worth of about $3.7 million. But she has
not revealed how much she and her husband earn from property near
the airport, calling Elsey's questions a smoke screen.
   Elsey, owner of a medical supply business, lists his net worth
at $378,875.
   Since Elsey brought up the income topic two weeks ago, both
candidates have ignored issues such as what kinds of businesses to
attract, how to reduce crime, whether to raise taxes and how to
deal with rapid population growth.
   Both newspapers have endorsed Mrs. Azar, a Democrat, while
outgoing Mayor Jonathan Rogers supports Elsey. By law, Rogers had
to step down this time after four consecutive two-year terms.
   If Mrs. Azar wins, El Paso will become the fourth of Texas' five
largest cities to elect a woman mayor. Houston, Dallas and San
Antonio are all led by women.
   Unlike most major Texas cities, El Paso has a strong mayor and
no city manager. The mayor appoints members of city boards and
supervises department heads and thus holds the most powerful
position in city government.
</TEXT>
