<FIRST>r a AM-PlaneCrash     05-26 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane Crash,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Dead, Three Injured In Plane Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH HARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENWOOD, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An airplane carrying race fans from South
Dakota to the Indianapolis 500 crashed in a softball field Friday,
killing two aboard and injuring three others.
   The plane, a twin-engine Beechcraft Baron, crashed at about 2:30
p.m. after the pilot notified the Indianapolis International
Airport he was having ``serious fuel problems,'' said Barbara
Dettmer, a spokeswoman for the Federal Aviation Administration in
Chicago.
   FAA and National Transportation Safety Board officials were at
the scene investigating the cause of the crash.
   Johnson County Sheriff Doran Miller said the plane was heading
for Indianapolis, 11 miles north of Greenwood, for the Indianapolis
500 on Sunday. The flight originated in Sioux Falls, S.D.
   The two victims were identified as Robert Best, 69, and Warren
E. Schoon, 68, both of Sioux Falls, S.D. Miller said both men were
thrown from the plane.
   Two other passengers, Arnold Tofteland, 60, of Luverne, Minn.,
and Ross Fenn, 62, of Sioux Falls, S.D., were taken to Indianapolis
hospitals in critical condition. The pilot, Larry Larson, 29, of
Sioux Falls, was in serious but stable condition at University
Heights Hospital, a spokesman said.
   One witness, Max Maddox, said he was on a nearby golf course and
watched the plane crash in a softball field behind the Community
Church of Greenwood.
   ``It had no power. The propellers were just fanning in the wind.
I kept watching him drop and drop, and then I saw some smoke,''
Maddox said.
   The plane was attempting to make an emergency landing at the
Greenwood Municipal Airport when it crashed about four miles away,
said airport spokesman Aaron Pietras.
</TEXT>
