<FIRST>r a AM-Eastern-Outlook     05-26 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Outlook,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>With Shuttle Sale Approved, Attention Shifts to Rest of Eastern</HEAD>
<HEAD>A longer version moved on the financial wire.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Now that Eastern Airlines has won court approval
to sell its profitable Northeast shuttle to developer Donald Trump,
attention is shifting to the rest of the strikebound carrier.
   The coming week could be critical in Eastern's 2{-month-old
Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceeding and how it emerges from one of the
most contentious labor disputes in the commercial airline business.
   The committee representing the airline's major creditors is
expected to meet during the week, and a hearing is scheduled for
Thursday in federal bankruptcy court on the issue of appointing a
special trustee to run Eastern.
   ``Next week could be a very significant decision point,''
Eastern spokesman Jim Ashlock said Friday from the airline's Miami
headquarters.
   Two investor groups had submitted formal buyout proposals for
Eastern before U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland approved the
$365 million shuttle sale to Trump on Thursday.
   The groups, one headed by former Piedmont Airlines chairman
William Howard and the other by Chicago commodities trader Joseph
Ritchie, are expected to present new financing plans in the coming
week for Eastern minus the shuttle, union representatives say.
   Even before the shuttle sale, David I. Shapiro, court-appointed
examiner for Eastern, had said the Howard and Ritchie groups would
have to put up more cash in their purchase proposals.
   Discussions between the investor groups and union
representatives were planned for the Memorial Day holiday weekend.
The unions' goal is for Eastern to be sold to a new owner and
resume operations by July 1, said Dan Ashby, a spokesman for the
Eastern pilots union.
   Eastern sought bankruptcy court refuge March 9, five days after
the start of a strike that grounded most of its flights.
   Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's parent Texas Air Corp.,
plans to rebuild Eastern as a smaller carrier and sell another $1.4
billion worth of Eastern assets besides the shuttle.
   The bankruptcy court, which must sanction any plan, has not
passed judgment on Lorenzo's strategy, although Eastern has been
making deals for the sale of aircraft, landing slots and other
assets in the event the plan is approved.
   At its meeting, the creditors' committee is expected to evaluate
Lorenzo's plan and, possibly, the revised Howard and Ritchie
proposals, sources close to the situation said.
   On Thursday, Lifland is scheduled to hear arguments on the
unions' request that a powerful trustee be appointed to run
Eastern, which would remove the airline from Lorenzo's control. The
company has opposed such a move.
</TEXT>
