<FIRST>u a AM-OhioFlooding 1stLd-Writethru a0659 05-26 0834</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ohio Flooding, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0659,0855</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede CAMDEN</HEAD>
<HEAD>Child Dead, Motorists Missing in Flooding, Bridge Collapse</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 20 grafs to UPDATE with bridge collapse, child death.
Picks up 4th graf, `It was.... DELETES outdated grafs 11-12 bgng, `She
said rescuers.... Changes byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A temporary bridge collapsed Friday, plunging
as many as four autos into the swollen Great Miami River, and the
people inside were feared dead. A child was found dead in a creek
flooded by the same heavy rains.
   Widespread flooding in southwestern Ohio sent people scurrying
to rooftops and high ground. One couple and their 10-year-old son
were stranded on the roof of their house from morning until 5:30
p.m. when rescuers reached them by boat, the Butler County
Sheriff's Department said.
   In Camden, rescuers used lifelines and boats to lead 30
occupants of a trailer park through chest-high water to safety. A
total of 200 people were forced from their homes in the town of
about 1,900 people southwest of Dayton.
   Divers recovered the body of 20-month-old Brandon K. Irwin of
Springfield in Donnels Creek, northeast of Dayton, about 7:30 p.m.,
the sheriff's department said.
   Four hours earlier, authorities received a report that Brandon
wandered away from his grandmother, fell into the creek from a
bridge and was swept out of her reach. Sheriff's Lt. Vaughn
McKenney said two helicopters helped rescuers search for the boy.
   Swift currents and the danger of floating debris prevented
rescuers from going into the river where the bridge collapsed near
Miamitown, about seven miles east of Cincinnati, authorities said.
   Witnesses gave varying accounts of two to four vehicles falling
into the river, said Bruce Smith, chief of the Colerain Township
Fire Department.
   Radio station WCKY reported at least six people were missing. An
adult and four children were seen in a yellow pickup truck and at
least one person in a car which went under the water, WCKY reported.
   Hamilton County Sheriff's Lt. Col. Ramon Hoffbauer, when asked
if anyone could have survived a plunge into the river said, ``I
wouldn't think so.''
   ``The current is moving pretty fast. I can't tell you how fast,
but the rescue crews didn't go into the water at all,'' Hoffbauer
said.
   A 100-foot section of the center of the one-lane bridge fell
about 10 feet into the river at 5:27 p.m., Smith said. The bridge
was about 300 feet long.
   Tires, tree tops and barrels could be seen floating in the
river, but no vehicles were sighted, and they were presumed to have
floated downstream, Smith said.
   The river was at 19 feet, three feet above flood stage, and was
expected to crest at 23 feet Saturday morning, said Gary Miller,
director of disaster services for the Cincinnati chapter of the
American Red Cross.
   The Red Cross heard from several people who said relatives had
not arrived home on schedule Friday night, he said.
   The temporary bridge, built to carry traffic on U.S. 52 during
construction of a permanent span, collapsed when wooden supports
that held the roadway deck failed, said Hamilton County Engineer
Donald Schramm.
   Schramm said the contractor that built the bridge called the
engineer's office about 10 minutes before the collapse and
suggested closing the span because of debris in the water.
   Schramm said an order was issued immediately, but the collapse
occurred before barricades could be set up.
   Ron Wells said he crossed the bridge just before it collapsed.
   ``I turned around and looked. I saw the back of a car going in.
A couple more sections of the bridge fell after that,'' he said.
   The flooding in Camden was caused when a two-hour downpour
pushed the Sevenmile Creek beyond its banks and into low-lying
areas.
   ``It was scary,'' said Assistant Fire Chief Dave Steele. ``To
some individuals, they have lost everything. We do have trailers
that have been washed off their foundations.''
   He said water was 5 feet deep in some houses.
   Firefighter Joseph Ball said he and others rescued about 30
people in a trailer park near the creek by trying rope from the
trailers to trees. Evacuees clung to the rope as they waded through
the floodwaters to boats.
   Chuck Weinstiger, one of the people rescued from the trailer
park, said the water was chest-deep as he made his way to safety
with the rope. A firefighter carried his 1-year-old daughter in his
jacket.
   ``It's kind of scary when you have a baby,'' Weinstiger said.
   Another resident, Charlie Spencer, said he carried an elderly
woman from her house. He said he chained his car to a tree to keep
it from floating away.
   Six families were flooded out of their homes in Butler County,
also in southwestern Ohio, said sheriff's dispatcher Diana Dunn.
   The Butler evacuees stayed with friends and relatives, Ms. Dunn
said. Most of the Camden evacuees were sent to an elementary
school, but all had left by late morning when floodwaters began to
recede.
</TEXT>
