<DOCNO> AP890526-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 0007EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MagnusonFuneral     05-26 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Magnuson Funeral,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magnuson Remembered with Stories About His Political Skill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Sen. Warren G. Magnuson was eulogized
Thursday as a good friend, skilled politician and powerful leader
who never forgot to represent the powerless.
   About 1,000 mourners filled St. Mark's Episcopal Cathedral here
to speak kind words and swap stories about ``Maggie,'' the low-key,
personable workhorse who was among the century's most powerful
senators.
   ``He was a marvelous example of how public power can be linked
to public good,'' House Majority Leader Tom Foley, D-Wash., said in
a reflection on Magnuson's life.
   Magnuson, a Democrat whose congressional career spanned 44
years, died Saturday at his Seattle home of congestive heart
failure, brought on by his long fight with diabetes. He was 84.
   In addition to Foley, those who spoke at the service included
Rep. Norm Dicks, D-Wash., and Sens. Brock Adams, D-Wash., Daniel
Inouye, D-Hawaii, and Mark Hatfield, R-Ore.
   Mourners were led by Magnuson's wife of 25 years, Jermaine; his
daughter, Juanita Garrison; and his two grandchildren. They were
joined by virtually every Democrat in public office from the state,
including Gov. Booth Gardner, and Republican friends such as Sens.
Slade Gorton of Washington and Ted Stevens of Alaska.
   The ceremony was a celebration of Magnuson's life; there were
few tears, and more than a few laughs as speakers told anecdotes
about Magnuson's political skill.
   Inouye recalled Magnuson's request for $950 million in state aid
after the May 1980 eruption of Mount St. Helens, ``a sum unheard
of.''
   ``I turned to him and said, `Mr. Chairman, we have volcanoes in
Hawaii that erupt every day,''' Inouye said. ``He turned to me with
a twinkle in his eye and said, `Your turn will come.'''
   Magnuson, who served eight years in the House and 36 in the
Senate, rose to president pro tem of the Senate and was
Appropriations Committee chairman and the body's senior member when
he was defeated by Gorton in 1980, his only election loss.
   ``Maggie was powerful, incredibly powerful,'' Hatfield told the
gathering, ``but never because he lost touch with the powerless.''
   Magnuson's polished wood coffin, draped by an American flag, was
escorted by pallbearers made up of some of the former staff members
that Magnuson fondly referred to as his ``bumblebees.''
   The Rev. Lowell E. Knutson, bishop of the Northwest Synod of the
Evangelical Lutheran Church in America, said that the
plain-speaking, cigar-loving Magnuson evidenced ``a hidden piety''
in his stewardship for the poor, the disenfranchised and the sick.
   Among his achievements, Magnuson counted the public
accommodations section of the Civil Rights Act of 1964,
establishment of public television and the Amtrak passenger
railroad, oil tanker safety laws, marine mammal protection and
consumer laws involving flammable fabrics, toy safety, truth in
lending, poison prevention packaging, truth in packaging and
labeling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
