<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 0011EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SwindallTrial     05-26 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Swindall Trial,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opening Arguments Begin in Former Congressman's Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Rep. Pat Swindall negotiated for a month
or more to borrow what he thought was drug money and later lied
about it to a federal grand jury, a prosecutor said Thursday.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Craig Gillen said during opening
arguments in Swindall's perjury trial that videotapes and other
evidence will show that Swindall, seeking an $850,000 loan, was
told the deal violated banking laws, was told narcotics money was
involved and was urged to walk away by the undercover agent but
``never terminated the deal.''
   Swindall's attorneys argued that Swindall and the government
were both duped by a manipulative associate of the former
Republican congressman.
   Swindall is accused of lying under oath in early 1988 to a
federal grand jury investigating his dealings with Charles
LeChasney, an associate and convicted money launderer, and with
federal agent Mike Mullaney, who was posing as ``Mike Martinez,'' a
money broker for probable drug dealers.
   Gillen told jurors that the agent more than once told Swindall
that if he were troubled by the illegal nature of the proposed deal
he could walk away. ``The agent is almost beating him off with a
stick,'' the prosecutor said.
   Still, Swindall sought the money and even turned over to his
contractor a check for $150,000 before later canceling the loan
deal, Gillen said.
   Swindall ``did not give a damn where the money came from,''
Gillen said.
   In his opening argument, defense attorney Richard Hendrix said
LeChasney tried to fool Swindall into believing the deal was
legitimate.
   Hendrix said LeChasney repeatedly told Swindall that the deal
involved legitimate money coming from foreign investors while he
told Mullaney that Swindall was ``a crook.''
   Mullaney, the first witness called by the prosecution Thursday
afternoon, testified that LeChasney told him that the congressman
``didn't care where the money came from; he wanted at least
$750,000.''
   Mullaney also said he was interested in meeting Swindall to
investigate whether Swindall's plans to sell a $1 million note at a
discount for cash ``would lead to an evasion of his income taxes''
and violations of currency laws.
   Hendrix, however, told the jury that Swindall never agreed to
the deal, that he continued to shop for and ultimately acquired
other financing for his luxurious suburban home in Stone Mountain
and that the check he received from LeChasney was a separate
transaction he canceled after becoming suspicious.
   Swindall was indicted Oct. 17 on 10 counts of lying to a federal
grand jury, each of which carries a penalty of 10 months to five
years in prison.
   The two-term congressman lost his 4th District seat in Atlanta's
eastern suburbs to Democrat Ben Jones last November. An attempt at
a speedy trial before Election Day was aborted after two jurors
received Swindall campaign material in the mail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890526-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 0013EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-EvergladesFire     05-26 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Everglades Fire,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Consumes 81,100 Acres in Heart of Park</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with more flare-ups, picks up 6th
graf pvs, `The blaze...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain that fell Thursday in southern Florida missed
a grass fire that has burned 81,100 acres of Everglades National
Park, and more flare-ups were reported, dashing firefighters' hopes
they could confine the blaze.
   ``The southwest corner is giving us problems this evening,''
said park spokeswoman Pat Tolle. ``There was rain, and a little bit
of hail, but also lightning.''
   About 250 firefighters from as far away as California have
fought the blaze, which was started by lightning May 16 in the
region's worst fire season in a decade, she said. About 60
firefighters returned to fire lines Thursday to tend hot spots and
secure fire lines.
   Officials earlier predicted the fire would move toward a sparse
area with poor fuel, and had not expected any lightning.
   ``The direction it's going is very sparse and poor fuel, and
it's also wetter in that area so we're very optimistic we're just
going to be able to put a circle around it,'' Ms. Tolle said.
   While showers fell 30 miles to the northeast in the Miami area,
no rain fell on the fire, which is located in marshy sawgrass and
isolated hardwood hammocks that hadn't burned in more than 30 years.
   The blaze is typical of fires before the rainy season in the
vast park and has caused only limited damage, Ms. Tolle said.
   ``It's burning off the top of the grass,'' she said. ``We'll
see, as soon as the summer rains begin, there'll be a lush regrowth
of the sawgrass.''
   The fire briefly threatened the Miccosukee Indian village at the
northern edge of the park Tuesday before shifting direction, but
the park's nearby Shark Valley visitor center was closed until
Thursday morning because of heavy smoke.
   State officials estimate about 400 wildfires have consumed
350,000 acres of grass and brush in South Florida since October.
   ``Probably as far as acreage lost, this will end up topping the
others'' in this decade, said David Utley, state Forestry Division
district administrator. He estimated two-thirds of the fires have
been caused by man.
</TEXT>
