<FIRST>r p AM-Mondale-Senate     05-26 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mondale-Senate,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mondale Schedules News Conference to Discuss 1990 Senate Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY R. SANDOK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Vice President Walter F. Mondale
has scheduled a news conference Friday to discuss the 1990 race for
the U.S. Senate seat in Minnesota, his son said Thursday.
   Mondale aides would not disclose whether the former senator from
Minnesota and 1984 Democratic presidential nominee will indicate
whether he plans to seek the seat now held by Republican Rudy
Boschwitz.
   The 7:15 a.m. news conference ``will have something to do with
the U.S. Senate race,'' said Ted Mondale. ``It will be worth
covering.''
   Mondale, a protege of the late Hubert H. Humphrey, generally is
considered the most formidable candidate Democrats could field
against Boschwitz.
   Prominent Minnesota Democrats said they did not know what
Mondale would announce.
   DFL Gov. Rudy Perpich, who a few weeks ago publicly urged
Mondale to decide soon on the Senate race, said Mondale has not
told him whether he will run.
   ``I don't have any idea, I really don't,'' Perpich said.
   He said he discussed the Senate race privately with Mondale two
days ago.
   Mondale, 61, represented Minnesota in the Senate from 1965 until
1976, when he gave up his seat to become vice president under
President Carter.
   Speculation that Mondale might run for the Senate again began in
June 1987, when he moved back to Minnesota from Washington. He is
an attorney with a Minneapolis law firm.
   Boschwitz, 58, was elected to the Senate in 1978.
   The only Democratic Senate candidate to date is Paul Wellstone,
a political science professor at Carleton College in Northfield and
a member of the Democratic National Committee.
</TEXT>
