<DOCNO> AP890526-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 0046EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Seabrook-Reax     05-26 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seabrook-Reax,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plant Officials Elated, Foes Dejected By Low-Power Approval</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seabrook nuclear power plant officials
expressed joy Thursday on winning approval to split their first
atoms within two weeks, after a decade of delays and billions of
dollars in cost overruns.
   Plant foes, who lost a three-year battle to block low-power
testing, promised to press their legal battle against commercial
operation of the $6 billion plant.
   ``We still have a long fight ahead of us,'' said Massachusetts
Attorney General James Shannon, whose state played a key role in
stalling Seabrook by refusing to cooperate in evacuation planning
for it.
   The anti-nuclear Clamshell Alliance, which has organized
demonstrations against Seabrook since the first trees were cleared
in 1976, continued preparing for a major rally the first weekend in
June, possibly coinciding with the first atomic chain reaction at
the reactor.
   A federal appeals court in Washington on Thursday rejected
Seabrook foes' request to delay the tests, and the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission said it would issue the low-power license
Friday morning.
   Seabrook officials said they would start preparing for the tests
as soon as they got the license, and could be ready to start
nuclear fission about 10 days later.
   Edward Brown, president of Seabrook operator New Hampshire
Yankee, said the low-power license ``marks a milestone for Seabrook
Station and forecasts a promising energy future for all of New
England.''
   Most of the plant's 1,400 workers had already gone home by the
time the court ruled, Seabrook spokesman Ron Sher said, ``but for
those people seen here there were certainly a lot of smiles and
congratulations.''
   New Hampshire Gov. Judd Gregg, who conditionally supports
Seabrook, reiterated his belief that starting low-power tests
before commercial operation is assured ``is probably not a good
business decision.''
   ``They should wait until they're closer to a final disposition
on the full-power license,'' Gregg said in a telephone interview.
``There are still a lot of legal challenges still lying in the road
as well as some major decisions to be made by the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission'' and its licensing board.
   But Gregg said he did not take legal action to try to block the
tests because lead Seabrook owner Public Service Company of New
Hampshire has agreed not to charge ratepayers any costs associated
with the tests.
   In a statement, the Clamshell Alliance said Gregg ``does not yet
fully realize the political burden he must now carry for his
complicit silence in allowing this radioactive testing to occur,
nor do any of us fully realize the environmental burden we will
pass on to future generations with the radioactive waste, for which
there is no known disposal.''
   About 10 Clamshell members, holding signs saying ``Stop Seabrook
Now,'' gathered outside Seabrook's gates as the court issued its
ruling.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis complained that ``the plant
will now be contaminated even though the NRC has made no final
decision on the adequacy of the Seabrook evacuation plan.''
   ``There is still no adequate plan to evacuate people in the
event of an accident, nor is there any evidence that such a plan
can even be produced,'' Dukakis said in a statement in Boston.
</TEXT>
