<FIRST>a i PM-IberianNeighbors Adv31   05-26 0864</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iberian Neighbors, Adv 31,0895</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv31</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs May 31 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Portugal Still Wary of Spain, Although Ties Are Stronger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spain and Portugal. The names often are
said in one breath, and today there are even more reasons to group
the Iberian neighbors together.
   But many Portuguese dislike it.
   Feeling overshadowed by bigger, richer Spain, the Portuguese
point to the differences between them.
   ``There is a division, a looking at Spain as the enemy,'' said
Fernando Brito Soares, an economics professor at Lisbon's New
University. ``It's in the cultural background.''
   He cites an old Portuguese saying: ``De Espanha ni bom vento, ni
bom casamento'' _ From Spain, neither good wind nor good marriage.
   Said Nicholas Racich, an American banker who has lived in both
countries: ``There is always a sense of competition and wariness
among the Portuguese toward Spaniards.''
   Spaniard Jorge Hay, a director of Banco Hispano Americano in
Madrid, said: ``Portugal was always a bit obsessed with Spain. The
Portuguese always define themselves as something different than
Spain.''
   Spaniards don't seem to spend much time thinking about the
Portuguese, and Luis Campos e Cunha, another New University
professor, agrees.
   ``We talk much more about them than they talk about us.''
   The prejudices are typical of large and small neighbors: many
Portuguese think Spaniards are loud and overbearing; many Spaniards
think Portuguese are insecure and backward.
   Seafaring nations, Spain and Portugal traditionally have had
little to do with each other, although they share the Iberian
Peninsula, aren't divided by mountains or rivers, and don't need
passports to cross the border.
   ``Portugal was always a little country against a big one. During
centuries Portugal had to defend itself against the Spanish desire
to annex Portugal,'' said Fernando Barciela, a Madrid-based
correspondent for Portugal's main newspaper, Diaro de Noticias.
   Spain ruled Portugal for only 60 years, until 1640, but the
Portuguese have ``never gotten over that,'' Racich said.
   The Portuguese still boast that their country was the only
Iberian region ultimately to escape Castilian control.
   To escape Spanish domination, Portugal formed a strong bond with
England, and created a culture so independent of Spain that today
it remains almost impervious to its neighbor's influence, Barciela
said.
   But the relationship changed dramatically when the two joined
the European Economic Community in 1986.
   It forced traditionally protectionist Spain to start dropping
its trade barriers. That means Spain now buys more products from
others countries, including Portugal, whose trade-based economy
traditionally has been more open.
   With the approach of 1992, when the 12 nations of the EEC open
up trade among themselves, Spain has been investing more in
Portugal. It invested $119 million in Portugal in 1988, five times
the 1985 amount. Portuguese investment in Spain is still
insignificant.
   ``In five years' time, there will exist an Iberian economy, not
just a Spanish economy,'' said Francisco Capelo, director of
capital markets for Banco International do Funchal SA in Lisbon.
``I believe Iberia will be much more integrated.''
   Portuguese exports to Spain almost quadrupled to $1.3 billion in
1988 from 1985, while Spanish exports to Portugal almost trebled to
$2.2 billion, according to the Spanish government.
   Tourism has grown, with millions of travelers going in both
directions each year.
   But there are problems.
   It's still ``very difficult for any Portuguese product to get
into Spain,'' said Jaime de Lacerda, director of the Confederation
of Portuguese Industry.
   ``There are some fears that the Portuguese economy can be
swallowed by Spanish enterprises,'' he added. ``In Portugal, all
this Spanish investment is seen as dangerous from a point of view
of its identity.''
   Some Portuguese are worried that their government's new
privatization program will result in Spaniards buying up the
maximum foreign holdings allowed in the sales of state-owned
companies.
   Spain is about five times the size of Portugal. Its population
of 38.8 million is more than triple Portugal's. With per capita
gross domestic product of about $7,400, Spain is twice as
prosperous.
   ``In Spain, economically and in terms of mindset, they are 10
years ahead of Portugal,'' said Racich, the American banker.
``Madrid is a gleaming modern capital, Lisbon is a very large
village.''
   They also keep different hours. Both take long lunches but at
different times, which could be an annoyance in an intermeshed
economy. The Portuguese start theirs at 1 p.m. and return around
2:30 or 3. The Spaniards start at 2:30 and return at 4:30 or 5. The
Portuguese end the work day at 6 p.m. and the Spaniards around 7 or
8 p.m.
   The languages are very different. The Portuguese generally can
understand spoken Spanish, but most Spaniards can't understand
Portuguese.
   Portuguese radio plays Spanish music and the Portuguese who can
afford it have dishes that receive Spanish TV. But the fare of
Portuguese-speaking Brazil in South America is more popular.
   ``People have a misconception that Portugal is a macho
country,'' says Cunha.
   Portuguese women's participation in the work force is one of
Europe's highest, although primarily through menial agricultural
jobs, while Spanish women's is the lowest.
   A woman, Maria Pintasilgo, was briefly Portugal's prime minister
in 1979-1980.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs May 31</NOTE>
</DOC>
