<DOCNO> AP890526-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 0642EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-Abortion-Consent Adv30   05-26 1080</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-Consent, Adv 30,1112</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tuesday AMs, May 30, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Florida Abortion-Consent Law Collides With Growing Problem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAVARES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 15-year-old girl was defiant.
   ``Just because you tell me I can't have an abortion doesn't mean
I'm going to go home and tell my mom,'' she told the judge. ``I'm
going to another court.''
   The teen-ager was preparing an appeal with a legal services
lawyer but was spared the fight when an appeals court overturned
the state's abortion-consent law in a case involving another
central Florida girl, identified only as T.W.
   After hopscotching up to the U.S. Supreme Court and back, T.W.'s
case is now before Florida's highest court for a June 27 hearing on
whether the state can constitutionally require unmarried minors to
get parental or judicial consent for an abortion.
   T.W. is believed to have received an abortion after the law was
put on hold, but neither she nor her lawyer, Jerri Blair, would
discuss her condition.
   The new Florida law has focused attention on teen-age pregnancy
and on the difficulties in adding legal restrictions for minors'
abortions.
   Ruth Arick, director of the Birth Control Center in Orlando,
used the case of the defiant 15-year-old girl to illustrate those
difficulties.
   That girl and a 16-year-old who got an abortion the same day had
been denied under-age ``waivers'' by judges, Ms. Arick said.
   ``We had told them that with all the ups and downs in the
courtrooms to just hang in there,'' said Ms. Arick, who described
the younger girl as ``very persistent,'' an only daughter whose
parents had considered her a perfect child who could do no wrong.
   ``She felt that if they found out about her pregnancy, they
would not trust her ever again and limit her activities the rest of
the time she was in that house,'' Ms. Arick said.
   Dr. Alfred H. Moffett, who delivered babies in nearby Leesburg
for 16 years until quitting obstetrics earlier this year, said
teen-age pregnancy is ``a major problem, both here in Lake County
and in many areas of the state. ... Everyone who practices
obstetrics sees 12-, 13- and 14-year-olds having babies.''
   Moffett said 25 percent to 30 percent of the indigent patients
he treated at Leesburg Regional Medical Center were minor,
unmarried girls.
   That is in line with estimates from abortion-rights activists,
who say minors received about a third of the 75,000 abortions
performed in Florida last year.
   ``Teen-age pregnancies are on the rise,'' Moffett said. ``We
don't need all kinds of statistics to know that. We need to teach
these young ladies what to do. That's why sex education in the
schools is so terribly important.''
   The primary reason for young pregnancies, Moffett believes, is a
lack of guidance at home, church and school.
   ``They don't know how or what to do and how to keep from getting
pregnant,'' he said. ``The moral implications are up to the family
and the church. But someone needs to teach them the mechanics.''
   In a report released May 24, the Southern Regional Project on
Infant Mortality said the South has a higher rate of teen-age
pregnancy than the rest of the nation and called for an intensified
education campaign aimed at boys as well as young girls.
   ``When our children have children, we all lose,'' said
Mississippi Gov. Ray Mabus, co-chairman of the group.
   The report said Southern girls under age 17 accounted for 47
percent of the nation's 178,000 teen-age births in 1985 although
the region was home to just 37 percent of the girls in that age
group.
   Florida's consent law, which was enacted in February, required a
girl under 18 who did not have her parents' consent for an abortion
to go before a judge and convince him that her parents were
unreasonable in withholding consent or that she feared physical or
emotional abuse if she requested help from parents or a guardian.
Before that, a girl legally did not need anyone's permission,
although many hospitals, clinics and doctors required some type of
parental authorization.
   The consent law might have little effect from a practical
standpoint, said Dr. Samuel Barr, a gynecologist who is director of
the EPOC Clinic in the Orlando suburb of Maitland.
   ``Contrary to the right-to-life propaganda, most minors come
with their parents,'' Barr said. ``And the parents are as anxious,
if not more anxious, than their 12- or 13- or 15-year-old
daughter'' for an abortion.
   A 15-year-old who identified herself only as Sarah had an
abortion at the Birth Control Center in Orlando recently with her
mother's consent.
   ``It wouldn't have been as easy for some of my friends as it was
for me,'' because their parents would not have been as supportive,
she said.
   However, if her mother had not agreed, Sarah said, ``I don't
think it would have been worth going to the court or whatever I had
to do. Besides, it would have been like going behind my mother's
back.''
   At the BETA Center in Orlando, another 15-year-old, Cathy, spoke
fearfully about her problems.
   Seven months pregnant, she is saddened at having been
``disowned'' by her father although her mother would have agreed to
an abortion. She says she and her boyfriend will put the baby up
for adoption.
   ``I never thought of an abortion. ... The law didn't matter to
me,'' she said.
   But, she added, the pair never considered the consequences of
having a baby. They ``never thought about finishing school or the
money or anything,'' she said. ``That was just being selfish. We
probably would be living off welfare or something,'' if they had
decided to keep the child.
   That lack of knowledge and thought is why Moffett gives sex
education lectures at schools, church fellowships and youth
organizations.
   ``I just spoke to about 90 fifth-grade girls at Fruitland Park
about contraception, and the questions from the 10-, 11- and
12-year-old kids would just blow your socks off,'' he said.
   ``They ask about condoms and intercourse and the pill. ... These
children are getting the information, but they're getting it off
the playground.''
   Moffett said he feared the consequences of restrictive abortion
laws.
   ``What we're seeing are efforts to legislate away abortions,''
he said. ``They may be made legal or illegal, but they won't go
away. They may have to go underground again, and that's a bigger
tragedy. Then we will lose mothers as well as fetuses.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tuesday AMs May 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
