<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 2256EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Hartford-Tony Adv29   05-26 0871</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Hartford-Tony, Adv 29,0891</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, May 29 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Nation's Outstanding Regional Theater</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LIGHTFOOT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four years ago, the Hartford Stage
Company was struggling with a huge deficit and a drastic decline in
ticket subscriptions.
   Today, thanks to some brilliant management and artistic
performances, the theater has not only rebounded with budget
surpluses and sold-out shows, but will receive a coveted Tony Award
as the outstanding regional theater in the country, when the
theater honors its own on June 4.
   Mark Lamos, Hartford Stage's 43-year-old artistic director now
in his ninth year at the theater, says the award recognizes a
quarter-century of theatrical achievement. But he admits that four
years ago, no matter how laudable the productions, the critics'
accolades probably would have gone unheard.
   ``I think when the theater began, the first two regimes of
artists and managers were not at all concerned about getting the
word out,'' Lamos said. ``There was a sense that we disdain any
sort of national opportunity, any sort of national recognition.
   ``That began to seem a little bit unrealistic to me. I thought,
`Here we have this beautiful new theater, we're doing work on a big
scale, we're ... in a highly competitive, charged atmosphere of
theater excellence. Well, let's be a part of that.'''
   Hartford Stage captured critics' attention with its modern
adaptations of classical works.
   Its current triumph is a monumental, two-part, five-hour
production of ``Peer Gynt,'' which played to sold-out crowds from
all over the country before closing a week ago. Michael Kuchwara,
drama critic for the Associated Press, called it ``a glorious
theatrical adventure, a journey that Lamos manages to make both
epic and intimate.''
   Last year, Lamos staged a modern-dress production of ``Hamlet''
set in a banana republic in turmoil.
   Lamos, whose six-play repertoire each season includes at least
half new plays, admits he prefers classics for their ability ``to
be inflamed again by living actors _ and with passion _ and speak
right to us.''
   ``The large plays from a century or two or longer ago have such
a tremendous scope I feel they exist for us now so that we can get
in touch with something that we lost, both spiritually and as a
society,'' he said. ``Whether it's a play by Aeschylus about the
murder of Agamemnon, or whether it's a Shakespearean comedy about
the possibility of forgiveness in an imperfect world, no matter
what it is, it's going to be something that widens you're ideas
about the world.
   ``It (theater) is a place for real spectacle, real wonder,
mystery, ambiguity _ all the reasons you go to church, all the
reasons the Greeks initially went to the theater _ to be sort of
blown away by the mystery of it.''
   But Lamos, looking youthful in blue jeans and high-top sneakers,
says those lofty thoughts have little to do with Hartford Stage's
rise to national prominence. Instead, he credits David Hawkanson,
his managerial counterpart in a business suit and glasses.
   Hawkanson was lured from the Arizona Theatre Company in Tucson.
He inherited an accumulated deficit of $440,000 and 7,900
subscribers _ down from 17,000 in 1977, when he arrived in
Connecticut in 1985. He hired marketing and public relations teams,
began a telemarketing campaign and went after the national press.
   Each year since Hawkanson's arrival, the company has posted
operating surpluses, reducing the overall deficit to $110,000.
Hawkanson expects it to be completely wiped out by next year.
   In 1989, the theater's 25th anniversary, subscriptions are back
up to 15,000, and attendance this year is expected to total
120,000, or about 95 percent of capacity.
   ``We worked very hard to get national criticism,'' Hawkanson
said. ``An actor will give up nine weeks to work here if they think
it will not get lost. Our ability to attract those people is
directly related to their perception about what is being done
here.''
   The decision of Emmy-award winning actor Richard Thomas (``The
Waltons'') to return for a second production in Hartford, is proof
of the strategy's success. Last year, he played the title role in
``Hamlet.'' This year, eager to tackle another difficult role and
to work again with Lamos, he returned for ``Peer Gynt,'' and he
looks forward to returning a third time.
   ``It's a great thing to find someone with whom one wants to work
and get satisfaction,'' Thomas said. ``An actor of my caliber
should be pleased to work at a theater like Hartford.
   ``They do interesting new plays and revivals of older ones.
Because it's in Hartford and one doesn't earn a lot of money,
people seem to think it's a sacrifice to work here. It isn't at
all.''
   The special Tony, based on recommendations by the American
Theater Critics Association, is presented by the League of American
Theater Producers and the American Theater Wing. Lamos and
Hawkanson will accept it during televised Tony ceremonies on June
4, making Hartford the second Connecticut theater to receive a Tony
for outstanding regional theater in the award's 14-year history.
Long Wharf Theatre in New Haven received the award in 1978.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, May 29</NOTE>
