<FIRST>a w AM-Bush'sVacancies Adv30   05-26 1022</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush's Vacancies, Adv 30,1045</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tue AMs, May 30 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>One Twelfth of The Term Over, Bush Still Looks for His Team</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lacking an assistant secretary for
inter-American affairs, Secretary of State James A. Baker III had
to put in 40 hours negotiating with leaders of Congress on U.S. aid
to the Nicaraguan Contras.
   Lacking presidential appointees to 33 key jobs in the Defense
Department, the Pentagon had to tell Congress it couldn't meet
deadlines for decisions on mobile missiles, a scaled-down Star
Wars, the cost of the new B-2 stealth bomber or the impact of a
prospective arms treaty.
   Lacking experts to run the huge Savannah River nuclear weapons
plant in South Carolina, Energy Secretary James Watkins fears that
the nation will run out of tritium, a key component for nuclear
warheads, and frets ``this is unilateral disarmament we're talking
about.''
   One twelfth of the way into George Bush's four-year term of
office, the government still lacks key players in key places.
   By the White House's count, Bush appointees are confirmed and on
the job in only 25 percent of the 447 key policy-making posts
requiring Senate confirmation.
   Charles G. Untermeyer, the White House personnel chief,
acknowledges, ``It is certainly taking longer than we would like.''
   But Untermeyer waves away the concerns expressed all over
Washington that Bush's slowness in fielding his own team is keeping
alive an image of a presidency that lacks mission, purpose and
vision.
   He offers an array of defenses and explanations:
   _It is a ``friendly takeover,'' so no harm is done if some
Reagan holdovers remain aboard for a few more months. ``We look
upon them as people who are carrying on the policy that George Bush
embraced,'' he says.
   _Better slow than sorry. Untermeyer says he'd rather explain now
why a job is still vacant than explain months for now that a bad
apple was shoved in ``because we were being pressured to name
someone.''
   _It takes longer to find qualified women and minorities. The
administration is pleased that so far 20 percent of presidential
appointments have gone to people in those categories. To date,
according to Ross Starek, deputy to Untermeyer, important jobs have
gone to 36 women, 13 blacks, seven Hispanics and three people of
Asian heritage.
   _Some of the still unfilled jobs have unusual technical
requirements, such as the assistant secretary of commerce who
serves as commissioiner of patents and trademarks. Untermeyer
wonders aloud why such posts are political appointments in the
first place.
   _Background checks by the FBI are vital, but slow down the
process. Untermeyer says they take take one to two months; the
bureau disagrees, saying it does the job in 22 days on average.
   _The first months of a new administration are spent in making
policy and the rest of the time in carrying it out. For
policymaking, the key players _ chiefly the Cabinet _ are in place.
   So, says Untermeyer: ``The lack of an assistant secretary here
or there has not kept George Bush from getting a budget compromise,
settling the FSX (the joint U.S.-Japan jet fighter), working out
the S&amp;L bailout or developing proposals on child care, education
and gun control. These are the hallmarks of an administration that
is up and running.''
   Others dispute that view as rosy. At an agency where only four
of 20 key positions have been filled, an official, who spoke on
condition he would not be identified, said: ``My sense is that the
secretary has got to be frustrated. He has half a dozen major
things on his plate and for the moment has only a few people to
deal with them.''
   Other facts complicate the situation.
   During a Senate Armed Services Committee hearing, Sen. John
Warner, R-Va., had an aide read off some data Warner had assembled:
18 to 24 people had turned down the job of undersecretary of
defense for acquisition. Most cited the pay level or a new ethics
law with a stiff revolving door provision that keeps people who
leave government from taking a job in an industry they dealt with
while in government.
   But Untermeyer says Bush is moving as fast as predecessors.
   He says: ``George Bush has nominated 156 people vs. 184 at this
time for Ronald Reagan. He has announced his intention to nominate
another 45 and has retained 13 Reagan appointees for a total of
214. So he's practically at the same level as President Reagan was
eight years ago. The notion that we are `slow' is with no fixed
point of reference.''
   For all that, those in charge of running pieces of the
government are not so patient.
   In almost every executive agency, key decisions are postponed
because those who will make them _ or live with them _ are not in
place. Key jobs are occupied by Reagan holdovers who are unsure
whether they're going to be retained and unlikely to sign off on
any new initiatives.
   At the Energy Department, slowness in filling key posts ``is
delaying getting the admiral's agenda off the ground,'' said Joseph
W. Easton, executive assistant to Watkins, the retired naval
officer named by Bush to run the department. ``If you don't have
your team together, how can you play the game?''
   At the Pentagon, the long battle over the nomination of John G.
Tower to be defense secretary stalled action on issues requiring
political or policy judgments. Some people who were hired and
started working when it appeared Tower would be in charge have been
told they're out of work under Defense Secretary Richard B. Cheney.
   The Federal Aviation Administration hasn't had an administrator
since Allan McArtor left on Feb. 17. Critical issues are piling up
_ the need to deal with aging airliners, international terrorism, a
crunch in airport capacity and a continuing shortage of air traffic
controllers. Bush has chosen an admiral, James B. Busey IV, to take
over the FAA, but that will require a law exempting him from a
requirement that the job go to a civilian.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, May 29</NOTE>
