<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 1345EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-PersonalFile-Preston Adv28 1stLd-Writethru 05-26 1118</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Preston, Adv 28, 1st Ld-Writethru, b0533,1147</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release weekend editions May 28</HEAD>
<HEAD>Preston Pressed Into Speeding Avon's Turnaround</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 25th graf to delete word `reportedly.' Mary K formally
announced Thursday that it's interested in a possible takeover of Avon.
Also on the financial circuits.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY304 of March 24</HEAD>
<HEAD>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</HEAD>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Avon Products Inc. Chairman James E. Preston
says his 13-year-old stepdaughter has come home from school in
tears because of classmate taunts about cosmetics companies killing
animals in lab tests.
   He probably has felt similar emotions lately. Not only is Avon a
target of animal rights protests, the company also is under intense
pressure to improve its financial performance.
   The pressure has been building since Avon rejected a $2.1
billion takeover proposal from Amway Corp., a decision Preston may
live to regret if Avon fails to achieve what some securities
analysts are describing as highly optimistic sales and profit
projections.
   The beauty products giant, known in past years for the slogan
``Ding Dong, Avon Calling'' because of its white-gloved women
door-to-door sales squads, was putting the finishing touches on a
radical make over when Amway's offer landed on its own doorstep
earlier this month.
   In response to the unwanted overture, the management team led by
Preston huddled to plot a revised strategy aimed at justifying
their determination to preserve Avon's independence.
   Preston, during an interview in his office overlooking New
York's Central Park, summed up the goal this way: ``To run this
business differently than it's ever been run before.''
   Put like that, the task sounds simple. Judging by the critical
questions Preston fielded during a session to explain details of
the plan to financial analysts, however, Avon has a lot to prove.
   To be fair, Avon's harshest recent critics may be motivated more
by their own desire for quick profits than byan interest in
enhancing Avon's growth. Takeover stock speculators, for instance,
lost money after buying Avon shares on the hunch Amway's original
$39-a-share offer might incite a bidding war.
   But even those who respect Preston's management and experience
in the direct-selling business think he may have trouble keeping
his promises.
   ``It's really a very aggressive game plan in which all the
pieces of the puzzle have to fit exactly,'' says Andrew Shore,
analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. ``There's no room for
error, everything has to go right. If he doesn't hit these numbers
clearly, there's going to be a credibility problem.''
   Shore, who had been recommending purchase of Avon shares based
on the theory that expectations for the company were overly
pessimistic, says he is reassessing his rating.
   Among the new numbers that have evoked scepticism are 1989
earnings per share from continuing operations of $2.30 to $2.40, on
a fully diluted basis. Avon management now is forecasting 1990
per-share earnings of at least $3.35 and at least $4 in 1991.
   The estimates far exceed management's expectations circulated
privately around the time of the company's annual shareholders
meeting on May 4.
   Avon normally doesn't reveal projections. It departed from usual
practice in an attempt to persuade shareholders that management
made the right decision in rebuffing Amway, a privately held
company based in Ada, Mich. that sells products ranging from
household cleaner to office supplies.
   Many observers say Avon has been on the right trackfor several
years and they applaud Preston's pursuit of a higher profile for
Avon's core beauty business. Avon has nearly completed the
divestiture of its disappointing health care services holdings and
Preston has admitted it was a mistake for Avon to have entered that
business in the first place.
   The transformation hasn't been altogether smooth. Despite 1988
sales of $3.06 billion, largely via 1.4 million independent sales
representatives in the United States and more than 80 other
countries, Avon lost $404.5 million in losses on discontinued
operations.
   Lauren L. Wong, analyst with Oppenheimer &amp; Co. Inc., credits
Prestonwith having the broad experience necessary for Avon to
maintain its ranking as the biggest U.S. direct-selling company and
a major supplier of beauty products.
   Preston, 56, began his Avon career in 1964 as a management
trainee. He's held positions in sales and marketing and
international field operations. As head of the beauty group
starting in 1981, he steered the division out of a slump and
visited sales representatives to learn their complaints.
   His elevation to president and chief operating officer in May
1988 came as a surprise because another Avon executive, John S.
Chamberlin, had been widely believed to be ahead of Preston for the
position.
   Preston was named chief executive officer in September 1988 and
became chairman of the board in January of this year after Hicks
Waldron retired.
   One of the biggest questions about Avon's revised strategy is
why the company has backed off its earlier, higher predictions for
overseas growth. Even after discounting the adverse impact of a
stronger dollar, the overseas estimates still are slightly below
previous expectations.
   Most analysts consider foreign markets to offer the best
opportunities for direct sellers.
   Wong of Oppenheimer says it had been anticipated that sales
outside the United States would outpace domestic sales, but Avon
apparently has scaled back expansion plans abroad. Wong says the
strategy could backfire by sacrificing future growth in favor of
short-term profits.
   Although Avon seems to have discouraged Amway for now, observers
don't think Avon automatically can count on unchallenged
independence, especially if financial results don't meet its
projections.
   Amway still owns a chunk of Avon stock and could make another
pitch some time to Avon's board. Takeover investor Irwin Jacobs
also owns some Avon shares. Mary Kay Corp., the Dallas-based
cosmetics seller, has expressed an interest in Avon and speculation
about other suitors has surfaced.
   Preston says numerous prospective buyers have approached him,
with particular interest in Avon's retail fragrance business,
consisting of some of the country's most popular perfumes sold in
department stores, such as Giorgio. So far, he says he's responded
the same way to everybody: ``The answer is _ not for sale.''
   While Preston's fending off takeover feelers, he also is trying
to deflect criticism from one animal welfare group, People for the
Ethical Treatment of Animals, that doubts Avon's commitment to
discontinuing the use of animals to screen the safety of its
products.
   The criticism is unfair, says Preston, because Avon has led the
trend toward adopting non-animal test methods and has donated money
to researching alternatives.
   Of the animal rights group that has been picking on Avon, even
protesting near Preston's Connecticut home, Preston says : ``I want
nothing to do with their confrontational style. They have set back
the animal rights movement.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 28</NOTE>
