<DOCNO> AP890526-0208 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 1853EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-China-Networks Adv28   05-26 0926</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-China-Networks, Adv 28,0945</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, May 28, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>China on TV: The Living-Room Revolution</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Network crews are applauded by demonstrators in
Beijing, well aware of the power of U.S. television.
   The Chinese government, similarly aware of that power, shuts
down live satellite transmissions to the United States in the heat
of the demonstrations.
   Television brought the world the Civil Rights and anti-war
movements of the 1960s, the mass demonstrations in Iran in the
1970s, the people's uprising in the Philippines in the 1980s. As
the Yippies in Chicago chanted 21 years ago, ``The whole world is
watching!''
   This time we might be at a turning point. The Chinese government
pulled the plug on network transmissions, but that didn't stop it.
   ``You had this wonderful situation of American television
feeding back information (to the United States), and Chinese
Americans using everything from fax machines to telephones to feed
information back to China,'' said Robert Lichter of the
Washington-based Center for Media and Public Affairs, which
monitors the media. ``This really illustrates the truism that free
information is the enemy of authoritariansim, because it undercuts
the ability to control what people know.
   ``We are finally really attaining the `global village' that
Marshall McLuhan had predicted. ... Now it really is possible for
the whole world to be involved in social change anywhere in the
globe as it happens _ and the only thing that can do is speed up
the process.''
   ``The powerful hold press conferences. The powerless hold
demonstrations,'' said Berkeley sociology professor Todd Gitlin,
author of ``Inside Prime Time'' and ``The Sixties.'' ``The media
coverage isn't the only motive for the demonstrations, but it does
amplify what they do.''
   In the case of China, the government miscalculated the effect of
pulling the plug on American networks. That only increased the
coverage _ by 50 percent, according to Lichter.
   On the other hand, said Lichter, the coverage is ``less
important in China than was in the Philippines, because the
situation in China is less dependent on American public opinion.
Deng has less to fear from television than Marcos did,'' since
Marcos counted on American support for his government.
   Nevertheless, American living rooms have been filled the last
two weeks with wrenchingly sympathetic scenes of courageous Chinese
students defying the government and going on hunger strikes in
their quest for greater freedom. Dan Rather called them ``these
kids laying their lives on the line'' for democracy.
   CNN's Bernard Shaw recalled going through roadblocks in Beijing.
``People smiled and waved us on through. And people were applauding
us in Tiananmen Square. It's clear that people know who we are,
`we' meaning journalists _ being broadcast, television, radio or
print, photographers, still or videotape _ they know the importance
and the value of having us cover the story.''
   If the networks portray the Chinese students as the scrappy,
freedom-loving underdogs and the Chinese government hard-liners as
bad guys, they put themselves in the role of the cavalry.
   It seemed the biggest event on American TV last week was the
Chinese government's act of unplugging network satellite
transmissions. The networks seemed to revel in the unusual
confrontation with blatant repression, especially CBS and CNN,
which had the PR advantage of having their most visible anchormen
on the scene, Shaw and Rather.
   ABC and NBC covered CNN being shut down. CNN carried lengthy
coverage of its own negotiations to stay on the air, as did CBS _
14 minutes' worth during the season finale of ``Dallas.''
   ``We actually saw what happens when institutional authorities
confront the media,'' said Gitlin. ``We saw it unfolding in real
time. We saw these functionaries arrive from some Chinese bureau,
we found them telling the CNN people to fold it up, we saw the CNN
guy on the phone to his boss in Atlanta, we saw that whole
exchange. I think we very rarely to see what happens when
institutions are at work. If the media did the same thing in the
case of lots of other events, then I think they would be doing a
great deal to educate a democratic republic.''
   ``The rap on TV is that TV becomes the story,'' said Lichter.
``But this is a story that's even bigger than Dan Rather. I mean,
this is a story so big that the presence of TV, I think, doesn't
really change it that much. It just means we're better informed
than we would be if TV wasn't there.''
   Gitlin recalls that the networks toned down their coverage of
anti-war protests after the Democratic Convention in Chicago in
1968 out of fear they were ``amplifying the sense of dissension.
... Clearly when it comes to China, they're not concerned that they
might be amplifying division. It's very clear to them who are the
good guys and who are the bad guys.''
   ``Part of the difficulty is it's hard to find people who are
defending the Li Peng (hard-line) faction of the government,'' said
Brokaw. ``He's not available, his spokesmen are not available, the
embassy here has clammed up. And there are any number of people who
are willing to be critical of repression and martial law. So in
that regard, I suppose you could make the case that the coverage
does appear to be sympathetic _ but that's because the events are
sympathetic.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Kathryn Baker has covered the television
industry for the Associated Press since 1987.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sun, May 28</NOTE>
