<DOCNO> AP890526-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 0142EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     05-26 0829</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0866</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. economy grew at a moderate 4.3
percent annual rate in the first three months of the year, the
government said in a report economists and the Bush administration
saw as a sign the country's record peacetime expansion is
continuing.
   The Commerce Department's revision in the first-quarter gross
national product to well below its original 5.5 percent estimate
came amid worries that Federal Reserve efforts to stem inflation
could move the economy into a recession.
   But Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher said Thursday the report
shows that ``Fed policy over the past year appears to be succeeding
in steering the economy to a more moderate, but sustainable, growth
path.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corporations' after-tax profits fell 1.7
percent in the first quarter of 1989, the biggest decline in more
than a year, the government said.
   In a report indicating earnings are slowing along with the
economy, the Commerce Department said Thursday after-tax profits
dipped to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $171.6 billion
during the first quarter, down from $174.5 billion during the
previous three-month period.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rising mortgage rates slowed the sale of
existing homes in April to the worst pace in 14 months, the
National Association of Realtors reported.
   The trade group said Thursday sales of single-family homes
declined last month to an annual rate of 3.36 million units, down
1.1 percent from March, off 4.3 percent from a year ago, and the
lowest figure since February of 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top business economists predict the U.S.
economy is headed for a ``soft landing'' in which growth slows
enough to tame inflation and interest rates without toppling the
country into a recession this year.
   The latest survey from the National Association of Business
Economists, released Thursday, projects that the gross national
product, the broadest measure of the economy's health, will grow
2.8 percent this year and 1.8 percent in 1990.
   That would represent a significant retreat from the robust 3.9
percent pace of growth last year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Developer Donald Trump plans to have Eastern
Airlines' Northeast shuttle flying as the renamed Trump Shuttle in
about two weeks, Bruce Nobles, president of Trump Shuttle, said.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland Thursday formally
approved Eastern's $365 million shuttle sale to Trump. Nobles said
Trump was aiming to capture 75 percent of the shuttle market split
with Pan Am Corp. by the first year of operation, but he called
that goal ``a little ambitious.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salomon Brothers Inc. became the first
investment firm sanctioned by the government for violating laws
governing short-selling during the 1987 stock market crash.
   Without admitting or denying guilt, Salomon agreed Thursday to
be censured to settle Securities and Exchange Commission
allegations regarding its short sales, which are a type of
speculation aimed at profiting from market declines.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission
authorized exchanges to compete against one another in trading
stock options, a move designed to benefit customers but opposed by
many of the exchanges.
   The commission voted 5-0 Thursday to phase out current rules
that restrict the trading of particular options to only one
exchange. Beginning Jan. 22, 1990, new options can be traded on
more than one exchange. As of Jan. 21, 1991, existing options will
be open for competition.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration, moving to implement
the most controversial and feared section of the new U.S. trade
law, has targeted trade barriers in Japan, Brazil and India as the
most harmful to American companies, congressional and
administration officials said.
   The officials said Thursday the decision had been made to cite
Japan for its refusal to buy U.S.-made satellites and
supercomputers and its barriers on U.S. lumber products.
   The officials said that India would be cited for its
restrictions on foreign investment and foreign insurance companies
while Brazil would be cited for its import-licensing practices.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strike by AT&amp;T's union workers would have
little impact on customers who dial long-distance directly but
could slow operator service and bring company production of
telecommunications equipment to a virtual halt.
   Union and company officials who commented Thursday on the
potential impact of a strike expressed hope a contract agreement
would be reached by Saturday night's deadline.
   But the unions _ the Communications Workers of America and the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers _ also attacked
anew American Telephone &amp; Telegraph's proposal to shift more health
care costs to workers.
</TEXT>
