<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Trump Bjt   05-26 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Trump, Bjt,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trump Promises `Best of Everything' on New Shuttle Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Real estate tycoon Donald Trump plans to spend
millions of dollars to give his new Trump Shuttle ``the best of
everything'' and may attempt to buy more assets of strike-torn
Eastern Airlines.
   ``You're going to see the friendliest airline, you're going to
see the best managed airline there is,'' Trump said Thursday. ``I
think the service is going to be fantastic.''
   The $365 million deal for the New York-Washington-Boston shuttle
should close in about two weeks and the airline should be operating
as the new Trump Shuttle soon after, he said.
   ``We intend to have the best of everything,'' Trump told a news
conference at his opulent Plaza Hotel in midtown Manhattan.
   Trump also indicated a possible interest in buying other Eastern
assets, such as more planes, saying, ``We're looking at different
elements of Eastern.''
   Trump Shuttle President Bruce Nobles said Trump hopes to capture
75 percent of the shuttle market that is split with Pan Am Corp.
after one year of operation, but he called the target ``a little
ambitious.''
   The shuttle is used mainly by business travelers and was
Eastern's only consistently profitable operation before the March 4
strike by its Machinists, which was joined by its pilots and flight
attendants unions.
   The Eastern shuttle lost many passengers to Pan Am's rival
shuttle because of the walkout and now has less than a 25 percent
market share.
   Trump has pledged to upgrade the shuttle, whose fleet of 21
aging, blue-and-silver Boeing 727s will be refurbished and painted
with red, black and gold stripes and Trump's name on the tail.
   ``We're going to be spending millions of dollars on each
plane,'' Trump said. He also repeated a pledge to exceed federal
regulations in checking each jet for safety.
   ``I'm elated about it. I've been unemployed for three months;
it's a relief,'' said Bill Sanford, a striking Eastern pilot from
Marietta, Ga., who is one of 170 pilots tentatively hired by Trump
Shuttle.
   Trump, who owns several casino-hotels in Atlantic City, N.J.,
also operates a helicopter service between New York and that resort
city. He said he is interested in possibly routing the shuttle to
Atlantic City on weekends.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland on Thursday formally
approved the sale to Trump, which followed withdrawal of a rival
$415 million buyout proposal from America West Airlines, which
could not arrange financing.
   Miami-based Eastern first agreed to sell Trump the shuttle last
October, but the deal was delayed by court challenges from
Eastern's unions and the need for bankruptcy court approval.
   Eastern officials have said the strapped airline would net
around $300 million from the shuttle sale after paying lease
obligations and other related expenses.
   Eastern filed for bankruptcy protection from its creditors March
9.
   Eastern's unions wanted the airline sold as a single entity. But
in addition to the shuttle sale, Eastern's parent Texas Air Corp.
has decided to sell about $1.4 billion in other assets separately
as part of a plan to build a smaller carrier.
   Union representatives are holding discussions with two investor
groups that have submitted formal bids for all of Eastern. One
group is headed by former Piedmont Airlines Chairman William Howard
and the other by Chicago commodities trader Joseph Ritchie.
</TEXT>
