<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 0227EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Steel     05-26 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steel,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bethlehem Steel Chairman Defends Wage Increases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bethlehem Steel Corp. says a doubling of
productivity since steelworkers had their last wage increase in
1982 helps take the sting out of its newly ratified labor contract.
   While the United Steelworkers union was counting ballots
Thursday, Bethlehem's competitors were criticizing the contract's
terms in Washington at the annual conference of the American Iron
and Steel Institute.
   By a margin of nearly 4-1, 11,386-3,009, union members ratified
a 50-month package that raises average base wages by $2.50 per hour
to $13.72 by July 1993.
   ``It was certainly rich enough,'' LTV Steel Co. President David
Hoag said Thursday. ``It covered a lot of things.''
   Bethlehem Steel Chairman Walter F. Williams said the added costs
of the contract can be offset by a modest increase of $18 per ton
in steel prices over the next four years. Bethlehem's prices now
average slightly more than $500 per ton, he said.
   ``I frankly don't understand how anyone could expect us not to
have some increase in our labor costs after being flat for six
years,'' Williams said.
   National Steel Corp. also is nearing a contract agreement with
the USW. An announcement could come as early as today on terms
influenced by the Bethlehem settlement, according to sources who
spoke on condition they not be identified.
   Contracts at National, Inland Steel Corp. and Armco Inc. expire
July 31, the same deadline Bethlehem faced.
   The 20,500 USW members at the nation's second-largest steelmaker
won an immediate base wage increase of $1 per hour, or 8 percent,
to $12.22 an hour as a restoration of past sacrifices. The base
wage will rise by $1 on Jan. 1, 1991, and by 50 cents on Jan. 1,
1992.
   They get an immediate $500 signing bonus and a $500 advance on
profit-sharing payments. Pension and medical benefits will be
sweetened, and three paid holidays and Sunday premium pay will be
restored over the contract life.
   Increased payments early in the contract are mostly obligations
from earlier sacrifices, and the workers will not see new money
until 1991, Williams said.
   USX Corp. Executive Vice President J. Bruce Johnston, formerly
chief labor negotiator for the entire steel industry, called the
Bethlehem agreement unfortunate. One steel executive, speaking
privately, called the terms tragic.
   The hourly increases amount to 4.6 percent per year, and prices
would have to increase only 3.8 percent per year to offset the new
costs, one analyst said.
   Depending on inflation and profit-sharing, the new contract
could raise the company's average labor costs from around $26.50
per hour now to $31.60 per hour when it expires in July 31, 1993,
according to studies,
   Industry-wide labor costs averaged $24.56 per hour in 1988,
according to the AISI.
   Williams said the pact also provides for plant-level
negotiations to streamline work rules and further improve
productivity.
   Productivity has roughly doubled since 1982, lessening the
impact of labor costs on total production costs, he said. The
company can produce a ton of steel with the equivalent of one man
working four hours. That's down from around 8 man-hours per ton six
years ago.
</TEXT>
