<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 0242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ChannelOne     05-26 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Channel One,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>No TV Ads in California Classrooms, Schools Chief Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California's chief educator says he will
withhold state funds from schools that show an experimental
television news program for teen-agers that includes a daily dose
of commercials.
   The creators of Channel One want to offer the 12-minute-a-day
show to schools nationwide, providing satellite dishes, television
sets and video recorders in exchange for a guarantee students will
watch the program daily.
   But Bill Honig, California's superintendent of public education,
said Thursday he would withhold some state money from public
schools that agree to accept the show billed by its makers as an
innovative educational tool.
   Mandatory viewing of ads runs counter to state law defining
schools' educational mission, he said.
   Honig cannot order local school districts to ban the show. But
his control of state funds for education gives him considerable
influence.
   Honig said Channel One, a for-profit venture by Whittle
Communications of Knoxville, Tenn., would in effect put teachers
and school administrators in the position of endorsing commercial
products.
   ``The whole reason for this is to have access to kids' minds,
our youngsters' minds,'' Honig said. ``We would be ceding control
of our curriculum to a commercial enterprise.''
   Whittle, which tested the teen-oriented news show in six schools
across the country this spring, said company lawyers have checked
California law and disagree with Honig's interpretation.
   ``To come out and reject something that's not even in existence
seems to us to be a little bit premature,'' Whittle spokesman David
Jarrard said.
   Teachers who took part in the test screenings have given the
show rave reviews. But several mainstream educational
organizations, including the national Parent-Teacher Association
and the National Association of Secondary School Principals, oppose
widespread adoption of Channel One.
   The show's youthful newscasters present the events of the day,
with an emphasis on how they affect teens. It runs 10 minutes plus
two minutes of ads for blue jeans, candy, hamburgers and other
products.
   In exchange for a guarantee students will watch the show daily,
each school gets a satellite TV dish to receive Channel One and
other programs, a video recorder and a color television set for
each participating classroom. The package is valued at $50,000 per
school.
   Honig would block Channel One from the state's 4.5 million
students by using his authority over state grants that are made to
individual schools on the basis of attendance.
   If every high-school student in the state watched Channel One,
grants for the time spent would amount to $29.8 million, Honig said.
</TEXT>
