<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 0757EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Trade-Autos     05-26 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trade-Autos,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Riegle: Unfair Trading List Ensures Autos Will Be Discussed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration will address barriers
to exports of U.S. autos, even though cars aren't expressly on an
official list of products subject to unfair trade restrictions,
Sen. Donald Riegle says.
   The long-awaited list, announced Thursday, targets trade
barriers in Japan, Brazil and India to fulfill a new U.S. trade law
in a move that could mean huge tariffs against some foreign
products.
   Riegle, D-Mich., played a key role in placing the new provision,
known as Super 301, in the trade bill passed last year. The law
requires the administration to identify the most harmful trade
barriers and gives the administration 18 months to negotiate the
removal of the barriers.
   The list of harmful trade practices in Japan named satellites,
supercomputers and forest products as areas that had suffered from
Japanese trading practices. It omitted the automotive sector, which
accounts for almost two-thirds of the $55 billion U.S. trade
imbalance with Japan.
   But Riegle aides said the inclusion of distribution systems on
the agenda ensured automotive issues would be addressed in
negotiations with Tokyo on trade barriers built into the Japanese
regulatory and marketing system. Closed distribution is one of the
greatest barriers the industry faces to entry into the Japanese
market.
   ``The Super 301 process is having the effect I intended when it
was written,'' Riegle said. ``While other countries could and
should be listed, this initial list is a key step forward.''
   Chrysler Corp., the nation's third largest automaker, said in a
statement it was encouraged that distribution systems in Japan were
included on the trade-imbalance list.
   ``Chrysler will, over the next 12 months, aggressively attempt
to fulfill its commitment to break into the Japanese market as we
have in Europe and Taiwan,'' the company said.
   ``If we are not successful in cracking this market, we will
still have the option to refile for Super 301 designation of auto
distribution as a priority practice,'' Chrysler said.
   If administration talks fail to produce results in 18 months,
the government can levy tariffs of up to 100 percent against
selected imports from an offending country.
   Automobiles and auto parts are not on the formal list and so
would not come under the 18-month rule.
   The list had its critics, including Nobuo Matsunaga, the
Japanese ambassador to the United States.
   ``In light of the good-faith efforts that have been made, the
government of Japan and the Japanese people are greatly
disappointed by this one-sided decision,'' Matsunaga said in a news
release. ``There may well be some domestic backlash in Japan which
will make the resolution of the various problems even more
difficult.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
