<FIRST>r f PM-BankAmericaMeeting     05-26 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BankAmerica Meeting,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Work Needed to Continue Recovery, Chairman Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BankAmerica Corp., still rebuilding after
three years of losses, seeks to grow into the dominant bank on the
West Coast and to focus international efforts in the Pacific Basin,
its chairman said.
   A.W. Clausen, chairman and president of the holding company that
owns the nation's third-largest bank, told stockholders at the
annual meeting Thursday the company must capitalize on 10 quarterly
gains by Bank of America.
   ``It is a record of which we are proud,'' Clausen said of the
recovery, ``but one which we realize represents not the end, but
just the beginning, of our efforts.''
   Last month, the company reported a first-quarter profit of $275
million, or $1.38 a share, up from $109 million, or 56 cents a
share, a year earlier.
   The financial institution returned to the black last year,
posting a year-end profit after a string of losses that began in
1985. The problems stemmed from losses on Third World loans and on
real estate and farm lending in this country.
   Laying out goals, Clausen said: ``We are going to grow
carefully, but with absolute certainty, throughout the Pacific
Coast and be the dominant provider of financial services in the
western United States.''
   International growth will focus on opportunities for finance and
trade in the Pacific Basin, he said.
  
