<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 0809EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-EntertainmentMerger     05-26 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Entertainment Merger,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stockholders Approve Merger of Two Entertainment Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stockholders and directors of United Artists
Communications Inc. and United Cable Television Corp. have approved
the merger of the two companies to form United Artists
Entertainment Co.
   The merger makes UAE the third largest multiple systems operator
of cable television in the nation, with more than 2.4 million
subscribers. The Denver-based company is also the largest U.S.
motion picture theater operator with 2,690 screens in 686 theaters.
   In separate meetings in Denver, shareholders of the two
companies voted to approve the merger agreement which was signed
March 8, 1988, and amended on Sept. 15, 1988, and again on April
18, 1989, it was announced Thursday.
   Under the agreement, stockholders of United Artists will receive
one share of class A UAE common stock with one vote and one share
of Class B UAE common stock with 10 votes for each share of UAC
stock. Fully diluted shares outstanding now total approximately 141
million. The new stock will trade under the symbols UAEA and UAEB.
   United Cable stockholders, received either $38.50 in cash or a
rights unit consisting of one share of UAE Class A common and one
share of UAE Class B common and two rights. The rights which will
be traded separately under the symbol TCOMR, entitle the holder to
receive from Tele-Communications Inc. cash or TCI Class A common in
the future.
   All securities with the exception of the preferred will trade on
NASDAQ's National Market Trading System. The preferred will trade
on the NASDAQ but not on the National Market Trading System.
   Effective immediately, UCTC and UACI common stock will stop
trading on the New York Stock Exchange and NASDAQ respectively.
</TEXT>
