<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 0816EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-UniversalFoods     05-26 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Universal Foods,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Universal Claiming Victory; Others Not So Sure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Universal Foods Corp. officials are claiming
victory in their six-month battle against a hostile takeover by
High Voltage Engineering Corp.
   But others see possible further moves by High Voltage despite
this week's federal appeals court ruling in favor of the
Milwaukee-based Universal Foods.
   ``I think they have to raise their price,'' Milwaukee investment
analyst Martin McDevitt said. ``The court, in effect, has said it
doesn't think much of the Universal defense.
   ``If they (High Voltage) raise the price to, say, $40 or $41,
that has got to get the attention of the Universal board. I don't
think the board can stonewall that,'' McDevitt said.
   High Voltage has offered to buy Universal stock at $38 a share,
a deal valued at about $750 million. Universal stock dropped $1.75
a share on the New York Stock Exchange Thursday to $35.
   The ruling by the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Chicago
affirmed a March 18 decision by U.S. District Judge Joseph P.
Stadtmueller of Milwaukee upholding the constitutionality of
Wisconsin's anti-takeover law. It left unchanged the lower court's
decision upholding Universal's shareholder rights plan.
   Terrence M. O'Reilly, vice president and general counsel for
Universal, said Thursday that the offer by Amanda Acquisition
Corp., a High Voltage subsidiary formed for the acquisition of
Universal, could not proceed after the court decision.
   ``Amanda's offer for Universal cannot proceed in light of its
defeat in the 7th Circuit Court of Appeals'' in Chicago, O'Reilly
said. ``Amanda's counsel told the Court of Appeals that if the
Wisconsin Business Combination Statute were upheld, its takeover
offer would be `doomed.' The court relied on the statement in
disposing of the case.
   ``Unless Amanda was misleading the Court of Appeals, its offer
is over.''
   But High Voltage officials said only that they were reviewing
their options.
   An unidentified High Voltage legal adviser quoted by the
Milwaukee Sentinel mentioned the possibility of filing a motion
asking that the appeals court rule on the legality of the
anti-takeover defense used by Universal.
   High Voltage, based in Burlington, Mass., and headed by New York
City investors, has extended the tender offer several times since
it was first made last December. The offer, scheduled to expire
June 6, is conditional on getting judicial issues resolved.
   ``The court found that although the statute may well be economic
folly, it is constitutional,'' said Clifford Press, High Voltage
deputy chairman.
   ``While not deciding the poison-pill case, the opinion does cast
serious doubt on Universal's `just-say-no' defense. In light of the
court decision, we are reviewing our options,'' he said.
   Guy A. Osborn, Universal president and chief executive officer,
said company leaders feel ``shareholders will profit most if
Universal remains independent to pursue its highly successful
business plan which delivered a 30 percent increase in earnings per
share last year, will do so again this year, and indicated a 20
percent increase against next year.''
   In a 21-page decision, Appeals Judge Frank H. Easterbrook said
``Wisconsin's law may well be folly; we are confident that it is
constitutional.''
   Universal Foods manufactures and markets food ingredients and
selected consumer food items.
</TEXT>
