<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 1028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     05-26 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0281</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market headed higher today in fairly
quiet pre-holiday trading.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 5.31 to 2,487.90 in
the first half hour of the session.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by more than 5 to 4 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 504 up, 393
down and 538 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 21.40 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Prices and interest rates were mixed, showing generally small
changes, in the credit markets today.
   But stocks seemed to benefiting from speculation that the recent
downturn in rates might go further soon, with encouragement from
the Federal Reserve.
   The economy has showed signs of slowing lately, as Fed
policymakers have intended.
   Furthermore, some observers think the central bank might want to
ease credit in order to slow the recent sharp rise of the dollar in
foreign exchange.
   Gainers among the blue chips included American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph, up \ at 35|; General Electric, up | at 53]; USX, up { at
35, and Union Carbide, up ] at 27[.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.38 to 178.43. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .70 at 353.35.
   On Thursday the Dow Jones industrial average slipped 1.28 to
2,482.59.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 7 to 5 on the
NYSE, with 819 up, 636 down and 513 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 154.47 million shares, against 178.60
million in the previous session.
