<HEAD>Mary Kay Cosmetics Interested In Acquiring Avon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To UPDATE with Avon comment, ADDS 1 graf after 3rd graf pvs;
picks up 4th graf pvs, `The letter ... Deletes 9th graf pvs `Neither Mary
Kay ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investor group including Mary Kay Cosmetics
Inc. says it wants to acquire rival Avon Products Inc., which last
week rejected a $2.1 billion takeover bid from Amway Corp.
   John P. Rochon, vice chairman of Mary Kay Corp., parent of the
cosmetics company, late Thursday made public a letter to Avon
saying the investor group has had talks with Avon about a possible
takeover.
   No figures were mentioned in the letter, which was sent to Avon
Chairman James E. Preston.
   Avon spokesman John Cox said the company would have no comment
on Mary Kay's interest at least until after the matter was
discussed at a regularly scheduled board meeting on June 1. In
response to Amway's offer, Preston stated that Avon wasn't for sale.
   The letter said Mary Kay and Avon each would maintain separate
sales forces and identities if an acquisition were successful.
   On Wednesday, stock speculators bid Avon shares higher following
a report that the cosmetics company may be the target of a hostile
takeover attempt.
   ``We have never before publicly disclosed either our interest in
Avon or the fact or content of any of the discussions we or our
financial advisors, the First Boston Corp., have had with Avon or
its advisors,'' the letter said.
   ``However, because recent press accounts involving Avon referred
to Mary Kay Cosmetics, the company now feels it necessary to advise
the people who are key to its success _ its sales force _ of the
nature of its interest in Avon,'' Rochon said.
   If a bid were successful, Avon would be directed by Argonaut
Partners, an investment arm of Mary Kay Cosmetics, Rochon said. He
said Mary Kay sales directors were notified about the interest in
Avon on Thursday.
   On Wednesday, following a USA Today report that investor Irwin
L. Jacobs and an unidentified ``major company'' planned to launch a
joint bid for Avon at $40 a share, Avon stock soared on the New
York Stock Exchange in heavy trading.
   Avon dropped 75 cents to $35.12{ in composite NYSE trading
Thursday after gaining $1.37{ the previous day.
   USA Today had reported that Jacobs and the unidentified company
were in the process of completing financing and other details of
the hostile offer. Jacobs' partner was said to be a company other
than Mary Kay.
   Amway last week was rebuffed by Avon in a $39-a-share takeover
offer that valued Avon at $2.1 billion.
   Jacobs owns 10.3 percent of Avon's common stock through a
partnership with Amway. Amway, an Ada, Mich.-based direct selling
firm, withdrew its offer after Avon's rejection.
</TEXT>
