<FIRST>r f PM-FordPlant 1stLd-Writethru f0036 05-26 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ford Plant, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0036,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Stops Production at Two Escort Plants, First Time in 6 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Wayne plant scheduled shutdown.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. said today it will halt
production temporarily at two plants to shrink inventories of its
Escort subcompact car, last year's most popular automobile.
   Ford spokesman Ray Windecker said production at the company's
Edison, N.J., plant stopped Monday and is to resume June 5. On that
date, the company's plant in Wayne, Mich., will stop production for
a week.
   The two plants are the only ones making the Escort. Ford has
about a 100-day supply of Escorts at the current selling rate,
Windecker said.
   The shutdowns are the first in six years in which Ford has
closed any plant to reduce inventory. Plants typically shut down in
late summer to retool for the next model year.
   In 1988, Ford sold 387,815 Escorts, making it the most popular
vehicle behind Ford and Chevrolet pickup trucks. Through May 20 of
this year, Escorts were selling at a pace 5.1 percent behind last
year's.
   Ford has about 1,500 workers at the Edison plant and about 3,000
at the Wayne plant.
   ``The subcompact market is running below expectations,''
Windecker said.
   Ford officials said in April that an average of 10 percent to 15
percent of the cars it sells are built on overtime. In the past,
Ford has reduced inventories of specific models by slowing the
assembly line or trimming overtime. That strategy failed with the
Escort.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
