<FIRST>r f BC-Chase-CreditCards     05-26 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Chase-Credit Cards,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chase Manhattan Purchases Credit Card Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chase Manhattan Bank will purchase the credit
card portfolio of Michigan National Corp. for more than $220
million, cementing Chase's position as the nation's No. 2 bank
credit card issuer, it was announced Friday.
   The portfolio, held by the Independence One Bank N.A. subsidiary
of Michigan National, consists of more than one million Visas and
MasterCards with outstanding balances totaling about $1.1 billion.
   Chase called the acquisition the largest in the history of the
credit card industry.
   According to a statement from Michigan National, Chase will pay
between $224 million and $228 million based on a formula applied as
of May 31. A Chase spokesman had no comment on the price.
   The addition of the portfolio will increase Chase's cardholder
base to 7 million accounts with total outstandings in excess of $8
billion.
   Independence One is the 12th-largest Visa card issuer in the
United States, Michigan National said in a release.
   While Independence One contributed positively to its parent
company's earnings, Michigan National Chairman Robert Mylod noted
that the credit card business ``is becoming concentrated with many
of the largest banks in the country seeking to be dominant ... The
dramatic portfolio growth of larger issuers has given them very
substantial competitive advantages.''
   The move represents Chase's second credit-card acquisition this
year. Chase purchased Philadelphia-based Meritor Financial Group's
credit card portfolio in January.
   Chase is making the purchase through its Delaware affiliate,
Chase Manhattan Bank (USA). Michigan National is based in
Farmington Hills, Mich.; Independence One is based in Rapid City,
S.D.
</TEXT>
