<HEAD>Grains Higher On Word of Soviet Interest in Wheat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened higher this
morning on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat prices rose in early trading as word swept the floor that
the Soviet Union was in the market for spring wheat. However, wheat
futures drifted downward as trading picked up.
   Corn futures received a boost from heavy rains yesterday in Ohio
and Indiana. The rain could further delay the planting of corn
crops in those states.
   Corn futures were also getting support from good cash prices,
said John Frazier, an analyst with Balfour Maclaine Corp. in
Chicago.
   Soybean prices were being helped by the weakening dollar.
Analysts say the surge in the dollar's value in recent weeks slowed
the pace of soybean exports.
   In early trading, wheat was 1{ cents to 2} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.94 a bushel; corn was 1 cent to
2{ cents higher with July at $2.66 a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 1{
cents higher with July at $1.74{ a bushel; soybeans were a \ cent
to 7 cents higher wtih July at $7.08{ a bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures were lower in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .03 cent lower to .17 cent higher with June at
69.37 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .07 cent to .20 cent lower
with August at 77.65 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to .47 cent
lower with June at 47.95 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.62 to .80 cent lower with July at 31.37 cents a pound.
   Livestock prices settled mostly higher Thursday and pork futures
were lower.
