<FIRST>r f BC-Pickens-Koito     05-26 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Pickens-Koito,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pickens Says He'll Take Fight For Koito To Annual Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMARILLO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   T. Boone Pickens says he will take his
fight for representation on Koito Manufacturing Co.'s board to the
annual meeting of the Japanese auto parts manufacturer.
   ``There's no doubt they don't want an American on the inside,''
Pickens said Thursday. ``We've made it clear that Boone Co. intends
to be a long-term holder, but I'm getting the impression management
and its friends have something to hide.''
   The takeover strategist, who has sought a seat on the board
since his Boone Co. became the company's largest single shareholder
with 20.2 percent of the outstanding stock, complained that on
Wednesday Koito granted a Matsushita Electric Industrial Co.
representative a seat on the board although the Japanese company
has just 5.3 percent of the stock.
   Pickens requested three seats on the board, the same number held
by Toyota Motor Co., which has 19.2 percent of stock in Koito.
   He said in a statement the denial ``is sending a clear signal by
Japan's major corporations that they have no respect or interest in
American investors.''
   Spokesman Mark Helmke said the company had first tried to limit
Pickens to sending only one person to the meeting, but has since
agreed to allow him two people so he can bring an interpreter.
   But Helmke said he expected Pickens will try to attend the
meeting with his partners in Boone Co.
   ``I see nothing wrong with Toyota or any other Japanese company
investing in the United States,'' Pickens said. ``But I also
believe investment has to be a two-way street. In today's global
economy, no country can afford to keep other investors and other
manufacturers out for long.
   ``If Japan's corporate leaders don't open up, Japan is going to
get left behind, and I doubt the Japanese public will stand for
that for too long.''
   Since Pickens acquired his stake in Koito, he has been urging
government action to force Japan to open its doors to foreign
investment.
   Helmke said Pickens is encouraged by the Bush administration's
decision Thursday to include Japan on a list of countries who trade
practices are most harmful to the U.S. economy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
