<DOCNO> AP890526-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 2326EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-ShoppingCenters Adv30   05-26 0933</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Shopping Centers, Adv 30,0966</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Tuesday, May 30 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Major Developer Upbeat About Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who helped transform America's
cornfields and pastures into the phenomenon known as the shopping
mall says he is upbeat about the future of his industry and the
economy.
   Melvin Simon, who started in the shopping center game 30 years
ago by leasing launderettes and developing small centers anchored
by discount stores, launches his most ambitious project in June
with groundbreaking for the Mall of America. He says the
Bloomington, Minn., mall will be America's largest _ big enough to
include its own enclosed theme park.
   Simon's giant new 4.2 million square-foot Mall of America was
one of the star attractions at the International Council of
Shopping Centers convention in Las Vegas. It shared billing with
other major Simon properties, including a major project he will be
developing in France and a look at the unique renovation of the old
Gimbel's building in New York's famed Herald Square.
   ``I'm very upbeat about the economy,'' Simon said as he stood in
front of his company's booth at the annual conclave for shopping
center developers, builders and retailers. ``Everything goes in
cycles but I feel excited about the future. You don't lease (a
center) depending on today's economy, but on what the future holds.
The glass is half filled.''
   How many shopping centers does Indianapolis-based Melvin Simon &amp;
Associates own or manage?
   Simon turns to an employee standing at his side. He's either
lost track or is testing the employee.
   ``We have 207 centers in 38 states,'' the employee responds.
   Simon smiles.
   The numbers make Simon one of the largest managers and
developers of U.S. shopping centers.
   Not bad for the Brooklyn-born, Bronx-raised son of a tailor who
chose to stay in Indianapolis after a tour of military duty there.
   He convinced brother Herbert to join him in selling space for an
Indianapolis shopping center developer, and in 1960 started his own
company.
   Today, Melvin Simon, 62, is chairman of the company that bears
his name and Herbert, 53, is president. Melvin Simon owns
two-thirds of his company and Forbes magazine estimates his fortune
at $550 million. Herbert owns one-third, with a fortune estimated
at $270 million.
   Melvin Simon says he's always believed centers should be more
than just a place to shop.
   Mall of America, he says, will be witness to that theory.
   Grand opening is scheduled for the fall of 1992. Built on the
site of the old Metropolitan Stadium, it will include four major
anchors, 800 specialty stores, 18 theaters _ and Camp Snoopy.
   The latter will be a 300,000-square-foot theme family
entertainment park created and operated by Knott's Berry Farm of
Buena Park, Calif. The park alone will cost $70 million.
   Phase I of the project will cost $600 million and will cover 78
acres. Included will be a golf course and parking space to
accommodate 13,000 vehicles _ an area the size of 96 football
fields.
   Plans call for developing as much as 9.5 million square feet of
space at Mall of America, including hotels and office space. The
Minnesota project is a joint venture with Triple Five Corporation
of West Edmonton, Alberta. Triple Five pioneered the ``mega-mall''
concept with its 5.2 million square-foot West Edmonton Mall.
   Another project coming on line for the Simons this year will be
A&amp;S Plaza in Manhattan, a $400 million renovation of the old
Gimbel's building. A glass wall on the Avenue of the Americas side
will give pedestrians a view of dozens of stores on seven levels.
   To date, the company has developed 11 million square feet of
shopping center space and manages 72.3 million, with 4,450
employees nationwide, including 1,004 in their Indianapolis
headquarters.
   Currently, the company is adding about three major malls and
eight to 10 smaller centers a year to its inventory.
   Today the company normally doesn't get into a project without
owning it _ either outright or in partnership, such as the case of
Mall of America.
   ``We like to keep them and see them grow, so we become part of
the community,'' Herbert Simon said.
   Community involvement is something the Simons are known for in
Indianpolis.
   When the Indiana Pacers appeared ready to exit the city, the
Simons shelled out $13 million for the pro basketball club, keeping
them there.
   They saved a major downtown Indianapolis landmark by undertaking
a $6 million renovation of the Roof Ballroom, where thousands of
Indianapolis citizens had held proms and weddings.
   Their company will be spending $840 million on Circle Centre, an
effort to remodel and revitalize much of downtown Indianapolis.
   Melvin Simon also has tried his hand at the movies, producing
films such as ``Zorro, the Gay Blade'' and ``Porky's.''
   Other major Simon projects include:
   _ Hollywood Promenade, a planned hotel and shopping complex
developed around Mann's Chinese Theater;
   _ Newport Centre, a 1.2 million square-foot project in Jersey
City, N.J. that includes shopping and residental areas;
   _ Fashion Centre at Pentagon City, a 860,000 square-foot complex
at Arlington, Va. that includes a 450-room hotel, shopping and
office space.
   Abroad, meanwhile, the brothers are joining with a French
consortium to build a 270-acre leisure, retail, convention and
trade center known as Europark in Nice, France. Work is scheduled
to begin next year.
   Figures released at the ICSC convention held in late May show
were were 32,560 U.S. shopping centers in 1988, up from 30,600 the
previous year. Those centers generated $627 billion in retail
sales, up from $586 billion in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
