<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 2337EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f AM-BusinessMirror Adv31   05-26 0715</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Mirror, Adv 31,0738</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release AMs Wed., May 31</HEAD>
<HEAD>Have We Learned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the past two decades the United States has
corrected many of the problems that had weakened its international
competitiveness to the point that entire industries were lost to
upstarts.
   Major manufacturers modernized factories, raised quality,
reintroduced the work ethic, cut white-collar bureaucracies,
learned how to export. Government regulators loosened up, and tax
incentives were introduced.
   But, while America can take bows for having learned from history
and taken action to correct its defects, it has a long way to go,
beginning perhaps with the trade and budget deficits and the
factors underlying them.
   While those items are in the news every day, and something is
being done about them, several other problems of great importance
lie dormant, ready to spring up like jacks in the box.
   There is, for instance, the massive question of guiding the
economy.
   The Federal Reserve's faithful weapon against emerging inflation
is to clamp down on the money supply, thus putting upward pressure
on interest rates. It is an effective tool, but many critics see it
as a bludgeon, not a scalpel.
   For example, one of the indicators of inflation used by the Fed
is capacity utilization by the nation's factories. When that
percentage reaches 85, as it almost did earlier this year,
inflation is said to be a real threat.
   Whatever capacity exists beyond that point is thought to be less
efficient, Less efficient production is more costly production, and
more costly production forces industry to raise its prices to
buyers.
   The Fed's approach has been to lessen demand on the factories by
raising interest rates high enough to discourage buyers. Slack is
created, and the least efficient facilities can be retired from use.
   Wait a minute, say the critics. Won't higher interest rates cut
into the capital commitments necessary to increase capacity?
Wouldn't it be wiser of the Fed to see if it could create slack by
encouraging growth in capacity?
   Big questions, but little is ever done about them. Some critical
economists and business people have been arguing the position for
decades, to no avail.
   Also without resolution _ probably to remain so until another
crisis _ is the oil conflict. Are Americans willing to pay higher
prices for oil? Ask the question anywhere and the answer is a
unanimous ``no.''
   But _ Americans also are becoming re-attracted to bigger cars.
Relations with oil-producing nations, such as Iran, are tenuous.
And nobody gets more outraged at ecological damage than do
Americans.
   The nation has no official position on this enormous economic
threat, which can become a sudden reality because of military
actions, oil spills, platform explosions or OPEC decisions.
   Just as oil can break the economy, health care could also. When
lives are involved it is difficult to apply cost restraints,
especially in a profession where the ethic is to do everything
possible to maintain or improve life.
   Attempts to impose business discipline on and by providers of
health care, insurers and users have helped, but the problem
remains. An aging population, rising health-care wages and
scientific equipment contribute mightily.
   Because of these and other factors, health care remained in an
inflationary mode throughout the 1980s, even while general
inflation receded to under 5 percent. And there is little prospect
for controlling that inflation.
   Housing for the poor belongs in the same category of problems.
   A variety of factors have driven up housing prices, important
among them being a spurt in land costs, community restrictions and
environmental concerns. These are among the costs passed on to
buyers who can afford them.
   Housing for the poor, however, has never been profitable without
government assistance in one form or another. Tax benefits have
been used effectively in the past, as have relaxation of zoning or
other inhibitions to building.
   Those tax benefits, however, were greatly reduced in the tax
reformation of 1986. No longer is it profitable, or as profitable,
for investors to put their money into massive construction projects.
   Thus, while single-family home construction has remained strong,
building of multifamily dwellings has plunged. If anything, the
housing situation for the poor has deteriorated rather than
improved.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv AMs Wed., May 31</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890526-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 2338EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-HomeBrewing Adv30   05-26 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Home Brewing, Adv 30,0774</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Tuesday, May 30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Some Beer Lovers, Label Is Their Own</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK SEAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unlike beer guzzlers who dash off to
the store for quick gratification, Lawrence Snyder's customers are
willing to wait up to eight weeks to savor their favorite brew.
   Snyder owns Brew and Wine Hobby in East Hartford, where beer
aficionados can buy everything from the hops, malts and barley to
the siphons, containers and bottles needed to brew their own beer.
   ``It spoils you forever and commercial beers never taste the
same again,'' Snyder said.
   His store, where 25 brands of malt share space with beer mixes
from around the world, is one of perhaps 1,200 across the country
catering to the growing number of Americans who prefer their own
brew to commercial lagers, ales and stouts, according to the
American Homebrewers Association in Boulder, Colo.
   ``There is some work involved, but the satisfaction you get in
the end is worth it,'' said Everett Stone, a computer analyst and
Snyder customer, who has been brewing his own since 1982. ``You can
give it your own personal touch.''
   Home-brewing has only been legal in the United States since
1979. A survey commissioned by Boots of England, a British
drugstore chain, found there were about 1.4 million home-brewers in
the United States as of 1984, the last figures available.
   Home-brewers produce an average 4.5 gallons or two cases of beer
a month and spend about $250 a year on supplies, statistics
compiled by the Homebrewers Association show.
   Snyder, who admits that he actually prefers homemade wine to
beer, got into the home-brewing business by accident. He had lost
his job as an English professor and happened to be in the store
buying some wine-making equipment for his own hobby when the owner
offered him a job as manager in 1972.
   The next year, he bought out the owner, a Pratt &amp; Whitney
engineer who operated the store as a lucrative hobby. Snyder added
home-brewing supplies after it became legal.
   The brewing process, from initial boiling to final bottling and
aging, takes six to eight weeks.
   It begins with the mixing of malt and boiling water for between
15 minutes for light beer or an hour for the heavier, darker stouts.
   Next comes a five-to-seven day fermentation process, when yeast
is added to convert sugar to alcohol and carbon dioxide. Alcohol
content depends on how long it ferments.
   The home-brew is then siphoned from the primary container to a
secondary one where it remains until bottling.
   Prior to bottling, the home-brew is primed, when sugar is added
to help produce carbonation. After bottling, the home-brew must age
two to four weeks before it is ready to drink.
   Daniel Bradford, marketing director for the American Homebrewers
Association, said home-brewing has become painless with the
introduction of canned ingredients imported from Europe that allow
home-brewers to duplicate their favorite import, such as a John
Bull lager or a Tom Caxton Scottish ale.
   ``Supplies are readily available and directions have been
debugged so thoroughly they are foolproof,'' Bradford said.
   Bradford says increased interest in home-brewing also stems from
renewed emphasis on homemade products.
   ``People are interested in cocooning _ doing things at home _
and you can see that in the increased interest in gardening,''
Bradford said. ``The increased interest in gardening is somewhat
analogous to home-brewing.''
   Some home-brewers say they were drawn to their hobby as much by
their wallets as their palates. A can of John Bull lager mix can
produce five gallons of beer or about two-and-a-half cases for as
little as a $1.10 a six-pack. Imported beers retail for between $1
and $2 a bottle.
   ``My motivation was that English beer is difficult to come by
(in the United States) and it is expensive,'' said Mick A. Cogdon
of Enfield, Conn., a 39-year-old sales representatives. ``With
home-brewing you can keep the alcohol down, which lowers calories
and means you can drink more.''
   Snyder said many customers choose home-brew over such homemade
products as wine because it is quicker and easier to make. It is
also a year-round hobby, while the wine-making season runs from
September to November.
   ``First of all we're a beer-drinking society and we want instant
gratification or at least in the not too distant future,'' Snyder
said. ``Wine is very seasonal and takes more skill to make and
requires a longer aging process.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Tuesday, May 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890526-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 1419EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-NTT     05-26 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-NTT,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>NTT's Profits Drop in Face of Competition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese telecommunications giant Nippon Telegraph
and Telephone Corp. said Friday its earnings fell last year as it
faced the fiercest competition it has seen since becoming a private
business.
   NTT, which began its conversion from a government monoply to
private ownership four years ago, posted a 5.2 percent decline in
net income and a 14.3 percent drop in unconsolidated pretax profits
for the fiscal year ended March 31.
   Company officials attributed the drop in profits to lower
long-distance revenue caused by competition from new entrants in
the market, and to a slump in revenue from data communications
services.
   It said its net income fell to 230.6 billion yen, or $1.8
billion, while pretax profits dropped to 425.9 billion yen, or
$3.28 billion, from 496.7 billion yen the previous year.
   Total operating revenue fell 0.2 percent to 5.65 trillion yen,
or $43.48 billion, the company said.
   ``Fiscal 1989 was really the initial year of real competition in
the market. For the first three years after privatization ... we
continued to enjoy monopoly status because our competitors had not
yet started to offer services,'' said Osamu Kajima, deputy manager
of the accounting department, at a news conference.
   As Japan's largest company, NTT has attracted international
attention in the course of its transformation from government
monopoly to semi-private company over the past four years.
   The company was a stock market star in 1987, when the first
portion of its stock was offered to the public. In April 1987, two
months after the stock was offered, a single share of the company
was worth 3.18 million yen, the equivalent of about $24,100.
   Twenty-five percent of shares have been offered on the market,
with the government still holding the remainder.
   But recently the company has fallen on hard times. Its
hard-driving chairman, Hisashi Shinto, resigned last December after
being implicated in the Recruit scandal, and was arrested in March
on bribery charges.
   Competition also has forced NTT to lower its long distance
rates, cutting into profits. Kajima said rate cuts cost NTT 110
billion yen in long distance charges last year.
   Its local telephone services still run large deficits, and it no
longer can rely on its formerly overpriced long-distance services
to make up the difference.
   NTT stock closed at 1.51 million yen Friday, below the 1.6
million yen price it was offered at when the company was first
listed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890526-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 2340EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-CreditMarkets Adv29   05-26 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Credit Markets, Adv 29,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, May 29</HEAD>
<HEAD>Foreign Activity Goes Long Way To Explain Bond Movements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the U.S. bond market rallies, you can
usually thank West Germans, Japanese, Britons and other foreigners.
   At the end of 1988, foreigners held an estimated $634 billion in
U.S. debt, or about 5.6 percent of the $11.3 trillion in
outstanding credit market debt. Last year alone, foreigners pumped
about $106 billion into the U.S. credit market, according to
Federal Reserve statistics.
   So when the bond market rallied recently on the newfound
strength of the U.S. dollar overseas, foreign investment was a
major reason. A host of negative economic and political news in
West Germany, Japan and Britain also played a role.
   The reason? When things aren't going well abroad and U.S.
economic signs are being viewed in a positive light,
dollar-denominated securities become a good investment for
foreigners.
   ``They've turned on the buy signal,'' said Robert Brusca, chief
economist for Nikko Securities International Inc. in New York.
   ``There has been buying of both stocks and bonds,'' he said.
``(Foreigners) have to buy dollars to do that, and they've been
doing that.''
   When the dollar soared last week to a 29-month high against the
West German mark and a 19-month high against the Japanese yen,
foreign investors scrambled to buy U.S. bonds.
   The stock bribery scandal in Japan that has led to Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita's resignation and domestic political
pressures on West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl also have weakened
confidence in those countries.
   And with central banks in West Germany and Japan pondering
whether to raise interest rates in an attempt to stave off the
rising dollar but still taking no action, U.S. bonds remained
attractive.
   The Bank of England boosted its base lending rate a full point
to 14 percent in the middle of last week, fueling speculation that
Japan and West Germany would follow suit, and bond prices backed
off a bit. When interest rates rise, bond prices fall.
   ``The stronger dollar is a confidence builder for the foreign
investor, but if the dollar rises at too rapid a rate it raises
doubts about durability,'' said John Lonski, senior economist at
Moody's Investors Service.
   A shaky economic climate in West Germany and Japan could spur a
tightening of monetary policy.
   In West Germany, the outlook on inflation has been bleak with
high oil prices and a weak mark. In Japan, import prices have
increased rapidly and the yen has sunk, but government officials
there have said no change in monetary policy is yet warranted.
   The initial impact of an interest rate hike by the Bundesbank or
Bank of Japan would reduce the need of the Fed to ease monetary
policy and bring down the value of the dollar, which could reduce
the foreign binge on U.S. bonds.
   The Fed raised interest rates this spring to curb inflation and
economic growth. But with most U.S. economic indicators pointing to
a slowdown, another increase has been viewed as unlikely for now.
   ``Foreign bondholders will find that because of policy changes
in the United States directed at curbing domestic consumption and
increasing exports, the dollar will be worth more in terms of
foreign securities,'' Lonski said.
   Because of huge U.S. trade deficits, foreign holdings of U.S.
debt have increased at average annual rate of 18.9 percent since
the early-1980s, Lonski said.
   As long as the United States imports more than it exports,
foreigners can be expected to continue to loan billions to the
country in the form of debt securities.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv Monday, May 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
