<HEAD>Sluggish Trading Preceeds Holiday Weekend</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
lower in sluggish trading on the Chicago Board of Trade Friday as
uncertainty over the weather and the Memorial Day weekend held down
activity.
   Soybean futures were mixed, with the July contract higher on
reports of heavy trading in Europe of soybean oil and soybean meal.
   ``There is some talk that a number of countries will be
purchasing soybean oil and soybean meal, including the Soviet
Union,'' said Joel Karlin, an analyst with Research Department Inc.
in Chicago.
   Uncertainty over the whether put a damper on most of the market.
National Weather Service Forecasts for next week calls for average
or above-average rain for major crop-producing states.
   Corn futures received a slight boost from heavy rains Thursday
in Ohio and Indiana. The rain could further delay the planting of
corn crops in those states.
   Wheat futures were lower, despite an upswing in exports and
unconfirmed reports the Soviets are in the market for about 300,000
metric tons of red wheat.
   At the close, wheat was 2{ cents to 5 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.93\ a bushel; corn was \ cent
to 4 cents lower with July at $2.64{ a bushel; oats were 1} cents
to 3{ cents lower with July at $1.70 a bushel; soybeans were 13
cents lower to 10{ cents higher with July at $7.12 a bushel.
