<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 1726EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Avon     05-26 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Avon,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Avon's Mum on Mary Kay</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Will be led with closing stock price.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The price of Avon Products Inc. stock bobbed up
again Friday after word of Mary Kay Corp.'s interest in the
cosmetics company resurfaced.
   Speculators bought Avon stock on the possibility that Mary Kay
or another suitor might engage in a relentless pursuit of Avon,
which last week rejected a $2.1 billion takeover bid from Amway
Corp.
   Avon shares gained $1.87{ a share, rising to $37 by midafternoon
as 1.42 million shares changed hands on the floor of the New York
Stock Exchange.
   Buyers were motivated by release of a letter sent to Avon
Chairman and Chief Executive Officer James E. Preston in which John
P. Rochon, vice chairman of Mary Kay Corp., expressed interest in
acquiring Avon.
   The letter, made public Thursday night, contained no details of
the financial aspects of a possible bid, which had been mentioned
in previous news accounts but never publicly confirmed by
Dallas-based Mary Kay.
   Rochon stated the letter was being released so its sales force
would have information about the matter.
   Avon spokesman John Cox said the company would have no comment
on Mary Kay's interest until after it was discussed at a regularly
scheduled board meeting June 1.
   Wall Street securities analysts were uncertain whether Avon
would feel more inclined toward accepting a bid from Mary Kay than
it did toward Amway's advances. In turning down Amway's $39-a-share
offer, Avon blasted its direct selling rival as a totally
unsuitable match and criticized Amway on moral and ethical grounds.
   One of the principle complaints Avon had was the difference in
style between the two direct sellers, which Avon contended would
result in a culture clash that could ruin business.
   In a letter informing Amway that its board had rejected Amway's
proposal, Avon characterized its own 1.4 million sales
representatives as ``friendly'' and ``caring'' with a ``gracious
manner.'' By contrast, Avon accused Amway of fostering zealotry and
high-pressures selling tactics.
   Mary Kay, meanwhile, was apparently anxious to dispel any
misgivings Avon might have about the compatability of the two
companies.
   The letter from Rochon said that if the two companies united,
Mary Kay and Avon each would maintain separate sales forces and
identities.
   ``I do believe _ as you do _ that each company's sales force has
developed a `culture' of its own _ cultures which best remain
distinct,'' Rochon stated.
   He added, however, that the two cultures share the same
underlying values and therefore the management approach ``which has
proved valuable in motivating Mary Kay's sales force to produce
substantial growth will be transferable to Avon.''
   Rochon said an investor group he heads called Argonaut Partners,
which includes Mary Kay Cosmetics Inc., the main holding of
privately-held Mary Kay Corp., has been working with First Boston
Corp. as a financial adviser. A spokeswoman for Mary Kay said she
wasn't at liberty to disclose the partners.
   One takeover stock specialist said the link with First Boston, a
major merger and acquisition investment house, might indicate the
Mary Kay-led investor group intends to wage a dogged attempt to get
control of Avon.
   However, this investor, who spoke on condition that his name not
be used, said Wall Street was reluctant to push Avon shares much
higher because there is a perception Avon's management is
determined to keep the company independent.
   Earlier this week, Avon shares got a lift from a published
report that investor Irwin L. Jacobs and an unidentified major
company planned to launch a joint bid for Avon at $40 a share.
   USA Today reported Jacobs and the unidentified company were in
the process of completing financing and other details of the
hostile offer. Jacobs' partner was said to be a company other than
Mary Kay.
   Jacobs owns 10.3 percent of Avon's common stock through a
partnership with Amway. Amway, an Ada, Mich.-based direct selling
firm, withdrew its offer after Avon's rejection.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
