<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 1644EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-SummerTravel     05-26 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summer Travel,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Vacationers Driving, Taking Shorter Trips</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Vacationers are expected to drive more this summer than last
despite the recent jump in gasoline prices but will take shorter
trips, according to travel industry groups.
   Motor vehicles will account for nearly 83 percent of all summer
travel, with 273 million vacationers expected to travel the
nation's roads and highways in the 14-week period between Memorial
Day and Labor Day, a 4 percent increase over 1988.
   ``The sharp increases in gasoline prices since March 1989,
although higher than usual for the pre-summer travel season, are
not expected to be a serious deterrent to auto vacation travel this
summer,'' the Washington, D.C.-based U.S. Travel Data Center says.
The center's data are based on a national telephone survey of 1,500
households.
   Retail gasoline prices have risen an average of 17.4 cents a
gallon since Easter weekend, the steepest rise between holidays
since Christmas 1979 and Easter 1980, when prices jumped 19 cents a
gallon, according to the American Automobile Association.
   The average retail cost of a gallon of gasoline is $1.254, with
actual costs varying between cities, states and regions and
self-serve or full-service stations.
   Air travel is expected to remain relatively stable at last
summer's level representing about 15 percent of all vacation
travel, while bus and train travel, which represents 1 percent, is
expected to be at capacity.
   Airline fares increased far more than motor fuel in the first
quarter of 1989 _ 6.2 percent versus 2.5 percent _ but
second-quarter motor fuel prices have leaped more than 16 percent,
due to a combination of factors, including the Alaska oil spill and
the strong rise in crude oil prices since January, according to AAA.
   Overall summer vacation travel is expected to rise about 3
percent from last year, with vacationers generally opting for
shorter trips, industry surveys indicate.
   More than half of all summer travelers will make round trips of
500 miles or less, according to AAA. Average domestic miles
traveled are projected to decline to 920 from 970 last summer.
   ``America wants to travel more than ever and its people are
going to satisfy this desire even if the demands of time and
two-income families are forcing them to take three- and four-day
trips in place of one- and two-week vacations,'' said Suzanne Cook,
director of the AAA data center.
   According to the center's survey, the volume of day trips and
trips of up to three nights will rise 7 percent and comprise more
than half of all summer vacation travel.
   Overall travel prices were up 4.5 percent during the first
quarter of this year compared with last year, according to the data
center. Transportation and lodging costs were up 4.1 percent, food
and beverage costs up 4.6 percent and entertainment up 5.6 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890526-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 2014EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-ChicagoMBAs     05-26 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago MBAs,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>University Aims to Make Theory-Based Curriculum More Practical</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students at the University of Chicago's Graduate
School of Business might be at a disadvantage when they land jobs
because of the school's theory-based curriculum, according to a
report released Friday.
   The internal study recommends changing teaching methods to focus
on practical applications.
   ``You try to develop the disciplines underlying business
management, but then you have to follow through and show how they
are applied,'' Kenneth French, professor of finance and chairman of
a 12-member advisory committee, said.
   The panel surveyed the student body and conducted interviews
with recruiters, alumni and focus groups of students and faculty
members. The group received responses from more than 1,350 of its
full- and part-time students.
   Students ``feel that their education would be improved if the
faculty put more emphasis on the business applications of concepts,
theories and empirical evidence we teach,'' the report said.
   While the analytical approach emphasizes well-defined problems
with well-defined answers, students are confronted by ambiguous
problems with no ``right'' answers in the workplace.
   ``Thus, they may not be as well prepared to deal with some of
the demands of their initial job as graduates from other business
schools,'' it said.
   The study was prompted by a BusinessWeek magazine survey
published last fall that ranked Chicago's business school No. 11 in
the nation. Northwestern University's J.L. Kellogg Graduate School
of Management was ranked first.
   ``We didn't do as well as we would have liked,'' said John P.
Gould, dean of Chicago's business school. ``It's not where we have
been traditionally. It is not the quality of this faculty,'' which
includes a number of Nobel Prize-wnning economists and presidential
advisors.
   ``I think we're closer to second or third or first,'' Gould said.
   The report recommended more interaction outside of class between
faculty and students. It also suggested appointing coordinators to
improve weaker courses.
   In addition, the report recommended cutting the number of
full-time MBA candidates by 10 percent. ``Part of our problem is
overcrowding,'' French said. ``And size also works against a sense
of community.''
   Currently the school has 1,123 full-time MBA students, up from
521 in 1970. There also are more than 1,000 part-time students
pursuing MBAs.
   Tuition for full-time MBA candidates will be $15,500 next year,
or $1,550 a course, based on a 10-course school year. Part-time
students pay the same per course fee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890526-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 1707EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     05-26 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0681</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Ends Mixed After Falling Overseas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar continued sliding off the highs it
reached earlier this week but finished mixed in a choppy domestic
session Friday after falling overseas.
   The dollar was the center of a tug-of-war between central banks
from around the world, which joined forces to push it lower, and
traders who viewed a lower dollar as a buying opportunity.
   Thin volume ahead of the long Memorial Day weekend heightened
the dollar's volatility. Most traders spent the day squaring their
positions to protect themselves in the event interest rates rose
overseas when U.S. markets are closed Monday.
   ``Nobody wants to be exposed too much in the dollar over the
weekend,'' said Jack Barbanel, a senior vice president at Gruntal &amp;
Co.
   In London, one dealer complained ``the market had no depth,''
and said many players there finished trading at midday. British
markets also will be closed for a holiday Monday.
   The dollar opened lower in U.S. trading on rumors that Japan was
about to hike its discount rate by 0.75 percent and was further
pressured by talk of a West German rate hike.
   Traders had expected the dollar to retreat from the highs posted
earlier this week. The currency smashed the 2-mark level for the
first time in two and a half years on Monday and finished New York
trading at 2.0115 marks two days later, when it also surged to
close at 143 Japanese yen.
   But the central banks took notice of the gains. ``For the first
time in a long time we've seen coordinated central bank
intervention by even the smaller countries,'' Barbanel said.
   Also, U.S. officials earlier this week spoke out against the
dollar's climb in an effort to stem further increases.
   But when the central banks sold dollars at Friday's lows in an
attempt to depress the currency further, traders viewed it as a
buying opportunity, said Stephen Flanagan, a vice president at
Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.
   While the intervention may have been effective over the course
of the week, Flanagan said it failed Friday. ``The dollar just held
at major support points,'' he said.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 140.40 yen, down from Thursday's
close of 142.35 yen. Later in London, the dollar was quoted at
140.30 yen. In New York the dollar fell to 141.10 yen from 141.23
yen late Thursday.
   In London, the British pound traded at $1.5922, up from $1.5815
late Thursday. But later in New York, sterling dipped to $1.5905
from Thursday's $1.5910.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's rates, included: 1.9835 West German marks, up from
1.9800; 1.7310 Swiss francs, down from 1.7425; 6.7160 French
francs, up from 6.7035; 1,433.75 Italian lire, down from 1,444.50,
and 1.2015 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2068.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,
included: 1.9675 West German marks, down from 1.9965; 1.7155 Swiss
francs, down from 1.7650; 6.6625 French francs, down from 6.7675;
2.2150 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2480; 1,421.75 Italian lire,
down from 1,444.50, and 1.2035 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2105.
   Gold prices fell after finishing mixed overseas. Republic
National Bank of New York said the late bid for a troy ounce of
gold was $363.75, compared with $365.90 Thursday.
   On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $366.00 a troy ounce from $367.00 on Thursday.
   Gold was trading in London at a late bid of $363.75 a troy
ounce, down from $364.75 late Thursday. In Zurich, gold rose 25
cents to close at a bid of $364.50. Earlier in Hong Kong, gold rose
$1.55 an ounce to a closing bid of $366.41.
   On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current delivery
finished at $5.252 a troy ounce, down from $5.267 on Thursday.
Silver rose in London to a bid price of $5.27 a troy ounce, from
$5.26 bid late Thursday.
</TEXT>
