<FIRST>u f AM-MaxwellHouse     05-26 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Maxwell House,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Foods Fires Ogilvy, Hires D'Arcy for Maxwell House Coffee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Foods USA said Friday it had fired
Ogilvy &amp; Mather as the advertising agency for its Maxwell House
coffee brand, which Ogilvy has touted for 31 years as being ``Good
to the last drop.''
   The food company said that following a review of several months
it was awarding the account valued at more than $50 million to
D'Arcy Masius Benton &amp; Bowles, another New York-based ad agency.
   The switch comes after Maxwell House lost its longstanding
position as the biggest selling domestic coffee brand to Procter &amp;
Gamble's Folgers.
   ``This was a tough call that in the final analysis was based
strongly on strategy and creative recommendations,'' Ray Viault,
president of Maxwell House said in a statement from company
headquarters at White Plains, N.Y.
   The account loss comes as a blow to Ogilvy &amp; Mather, the largest
U.S. unit of the Ogilvy Group. Ogilvy Group management recently
accepted an $864 million buyout offer from Britain's WPP Group PLC,
another advertising giant.
   However, both General Foods and Ogilvy &amp; Mather said the pending
takeover had nothing to do with the Maxwell House account switch.
They said the agency review started months before the WPP deal was
negotiated.
   ``It's a tough blow,'' said Ogilvy Chairman Kenneth Roman. ``We
thought we did a very good job, but they thought the other agency
did a better job.''
   Roman declined to speculate whether the account loss would lead
to layoffs at the agency, which has handled Maxwell House since
1958.
   Ogilvy &amp; Mather has other major assignments from General Foods,
including Post cereals and Tang and Country Time beverages and
several assignments for coffee and other products overseas.
   The account win is the second major victory for D'Arcy in two
weeks. Miami-based Burger King Corp. tapped D'Arcy and Saatchi &amp;
Saatchi Advertising to split its $200 million-plus account on May
18.
   Clayton Wilhite, president of the U.S. division of D'Arcy,
congratulated the agency's employees in a memo for what was
``arguably the two biggest back-to-back new assignments in industry
history.''
   D'Arcy has worked with General Foods since 1929 and creates
adverrtsiing for its Cool Whip topping and Good Seasons salad
dressing.
   The Maxwell House brand has been losing ground in the shrinking
U.S. coffee market in recent years.
   John McMillin, food industry analyst for Prudential-Bache
Securities, said Maxwell House lost its long-standing ranking as
the biggest selling brand in the U.S. coffee market to Folgers.
   He said Maxwell House's share of the $3.9 billion market fell to
25 percent in 1988 from just over 27 percent of a $4.1 billion
market in 1987, while Folgers' share rose to 27.9 percent from 27
percent.
   McMillin said the new managers at General Foods, which has
become part of the Kraft General Foods Group at Philip Morris Cos.
Inc., are intent on reestablishing Maxwell House as the
best-selling coffee brand.
   ``A new ad agency may give the brand a little bit of life,'' he
said.
   While Ogilvy has used the ``Good to the last drop'' slogan in
its Maxwell House advertising, General Foods credits Theodore
Roosevelt for coining the phrase decades earlier.
   The company said Roosevelt used the phrase to describe coffee at
the Maxwell House hotel in Nashville where it is believed the brand
was born.
   Among Ogilvy's more recent ads for Maxwell House have been
commercials featuring commentator Linda Ellerbee and weatherman
Willard Scott touting results of recent taste tests that compared
Maxwell House and Folgers.
   Ogilvy got some encouraging news Friday despite the Maxwell
House account loss. Cotton Inc., a New York-based concern
representing cotton growers that had considered moving its account
in the wake of the WPP deal, said it had decided to keep its $10
million assignment at Ogilvy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
