<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-26 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quiet Trading on Markets As Holiday Approaches</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
lower Friday in sluggish trading on the Chicago Board of Trade, as
activity was muted by uncertainty over the weather and by the
impending Memorial Day weekend.
   On other markets, energy futures were higher, precious metals
were lower and livestock and meat prices were down.
   Soybean futures were mixed, with the July contract higher on
reports of heavy trading in Europe of soybean oil and soybean meal.
   ``There is some talk that a number of countries will be
purchasing soybean oil and soybean meal, including the Soviet
Union,'' said Joel Karlin, an analyst with Research Department Inc.
in Chicago.
   Wheat settled 2{ cents to 5 cents lower with the contract for
delivery in July at $3.93{ a bushel; corn was { cent to 4 cents
lower with July at $2.64\ a bushel; oats were 2{ cents to 3{ cents
lower with July at $1.70 a bushel; soybeans were 13 cents lower to
9{ cents higher with July at $7.11 a bushel.
   Uncertainty over the weather put a damper on most of the market.
National Weather Service forecasts for next week call for average
or above-average rain for major crop-producing states.
   Corn futures were boosted slightly by heavy rains Thursday in
Ohio and Indiana. The rain could further delay the planting of corn
crops in those states.
   Wheat futures were lower, despite an upswing in exports and
reports the Soviets were in the market for spring and red winter
wheat.
   After the close of trading, the Agriculture Department announced
the sale to the Soviet Union of 200,000 metric tons of wheat under
its export bonus program.
   Energy futures were higher in quiet trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange. Analysts say the market has settled into a
narrow trading range as next month's meeting in Vienna of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries approaches.
   OPEC members are to decide on production quotas for the second
half of the year and whether to change the benchmark price for its
oil, now at $18 a barrel.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 4 cents to 18 cents higher
with July at $19.52 a barrel; heating oil was .15 cent to .87 cent
higher with June at 49.20 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .23
cent lower to .33 cent higher with June at 66.39 cents a gallon.
   Gold and silver futures were lower in sluggish trading on New
York's Commodity Exchange.
   Prices rose modestly at the start of trading, but as the dollar
renewed its rise, gold and silver futures began to fall as investor
took profits from the previous two days' advances, said Peter
Cardillo, an analyst with Josephthal &amp; Co. in New York.
   Gold was $1 to $1.40 lower with June at $365.90 a troy ounce;
silver was 1.3 cents lower with July at $5.305 a troy ounce.
   Livestock and pork futures mostly were lower in light trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Cattle were lower on a non-existing cash market and expectations
of lower prices next week, said Dale Benson, an analyst for Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Hog prices declined because of slackening demand and large
numbers of pork bellies in cold storage.
   Live cattle were .20 cent to .48 cent lower with June at 68.77
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent to .50 cent lower with
August at 77.22 a pound; hogs were .15 cent to 1.15 cents lower
with June at 47.60 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .50 cent
to 1.17 cents lower with July at 31.07 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
