<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 1815EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     05-26 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prices Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices advanced Friday, recovering from an
early decline on the strength of the dollar and signs that
inflation might be moderating.
   The Treasury's key 30-year bond rose 11-16 point, or nearly $7
for every $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the
opposite direction from price, declined to 8.61 percent from 8.67
percent late Thursday.
   Trading was described as thin in advance of the Memorial Day
holiday weekend, and the markets closed earlier than usual.
   Prices began the day on the down side after the government
reported consumer spending shot up 1.1 percent in April, the
biggest advance in nearly a year. The spending data fueled the
market's fears of inflation, which erodes the value of fixed-income
investments such as bonds.
   But bond prices later recovered as traders examined personal
income figures released by the government, said Maury Harris, chief
economist with PaineWebber Inc.
   The Commerce Department said personal income rose a weak 0.4
percent last month compared with hikes of 0.8 percent in March and
1 percent in February. The April figure was lower than the market
expectations of a 0.7 percent increase, Harris said.
   The better-than-expected report gave traders hope that the
inflation rate might be slowing.
   The dollar was mixed against other currencies, but showed signs
of defying central banks' attempts to drive it lower. Its
resilience carried over to the bond market, analysts said.
   In the secondary market for Treasury securities, prices of
short-term government issues were up [ point to 5-32 point,
intermediate maturities gained 9-32 point to 11-32 point and
long-term issues advanced { point, according to figures provided by
Telerate Inc., a financial information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, rose 3.32 to 1,151.87.
   In corporate trading, industrial bonds rose. Moody's Investment
Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return on a
portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or
longer, picked up 0.11 to close at 313.69.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds was unchanged. The average yield to maturity
edged down to 7.45 percent from 7.46 percent late Thursday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills, meanwhile, declined to
9.02 percent as the discount fell 5 basis points to 8.52 percent.
Yields on six-month bills slipped to 9.10 percent as the discount
fell 9 basis points to 8.43 percent. Yields on one-year bills
declined to 8.90 percent as the discount lost 6 basis points to
8.26 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted at 911-16 percent, down from 913-16 percent late
Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
