<FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 1823EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-SteelTalks     05-26 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steel Talks,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Steel, USW Reach Labor Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE DRESSLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Steel Corp. and the United
Steelworkers said Friday they'd tentatively agreed on a 50-month
contract that restores pay cuts and matches wage gains won by the
union at Bethlehem Steel Corp.
   The National settlement is the second among four major producers
that faced expiring contracts July 31. It was approved by local
presidents on the union negotiating committee late Thursday, the
same day union members ratified the Bethlehem contract.
   National had been expected to tailor its agreement to the
Bethlehem settlement even though National's profits per ton of
steel are the lowest among the major U.S. producers.
   ``This agreement looks both forward and backward,'' Buddy Davis,
the union's chief negotiator, and negotiating secretary Harry
Lester said in a statement. ``It recognizes that our members have
not had a wage increase since 1982 and that they have made
significant sacrifices to help the company return to
profitability.''
   The contract, effective June 1, covers 7,300 union members at
the three plants operated by the nation's sixth-largest steelmaker,
St. Louis, Portage, Ind., and Ecorse, Mich.
   It restores wage sacrifices made in 1986, raising average base
wages by $1.81 per hour to $13.69 by the time it expires in July
1993, said union spokesman Gary Hubbard.
   By a margin of nearly 4-1, union members Thursday ratified a
50-month package with No. 2 Bethlehem that raises average base
wages by $2.50 per hour to $13.72 by July 1993.
   National employees will get a $500 payment in recognition of
past concessions and a $500 cash advance on profit-sharing for
1989. Pension and medical benefits also will be improved, and new
training programs will be offered.
   ``From a practical standpoint, I don't think they could have
given less, because there hasn't been a wage increase since 1982,''
said steel analyst Charles Bradford of Merrill Lynch Capital
Markets. ``This looks about in line with inflation. The only
problem is the steel prices aren't going up along with inflation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
