<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     05-26 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures End Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices finished mostly higher Friday
in quiet trading in advance of the Memorial Day holiday weekend.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the July contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, ended at
$19.52 a 42-gallon barrel, up 4 cents.
   Prices of crude contracts for delivery after July also rose.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale home
heating oil for delivery in June edged up 0.15 cent to 49.20 cents
a gallon. Contracts for the other delivery months jumped more than
0.80 cent a gallon.
   The June contract for unleaded gasoline fell 0.22 cent to 66.39
cents a gallon. Most other months rose, however.
   Analysts said there were no fresh factors influencing prices,
and most of the movements resulted from oil traders balancing their
positions in advance of the holiday weekend.
   ``Not a whimper, not a whisper,'' said Peter Beutel, assistant
director of the energy group at Elders Futures Inc.
   Traders continue to speculate about the outcome of an OPEC
meeting scheduled for next month, Beutel said.
   In recent days, buyers have been reluctant to accumulate
significant holdings ahead of the meeting of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries that is set to begin in Vienna,
Austria, on June 5.
   There has been speculation that the 13-nation cartel may decide
to boost production limits.
</TEXT>
